'147','','1','Matt','71.63.150.135','mjb2600@gmail.com','http://www.interwebz.us','Using Python + Scapy it\'s really simple..\n\n<pre>\n\n>>> arping(\"192.168.0.0/24\", timeout=2)\nBegin emission:\n**Finished to send 256 packets.\n\nReceived 2 packets, got 2 answers, remaining 254 packets\n00:11:22:33:44:55 192.168.0.1\n00:11:22:33:44:66 192.168.0.3\n(<ARPing: TCP:0 UDP:0 ICMP:0 Other:2>, <Unanswered: TCP:0 UDP:0 ICMP:0 Other:254>)\n</pre>\n\nAlso, check out one of my previous posts <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=140\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>.  The first script in the post uses Perl to discover network devices via ARP.','2010-05-17 15:59:57','2010-05-17 20:59:57','0','0','207','','2'),(
'148','','1','Matt','71.63.150.135','mjb2600@gmail.com','http://www.interwebz.us','Using \'arping()\' in a script form would look like this:\n\n<pre>\n\n#!/usr/bin/python\n\nfrom scapy.all import *\n\ndef usage():\n  print \"Usage: arp-discover.py <range>\"\n  print \"IE: arp-discover.py 192.168.0.0/24\"\n  sys.exit(1)\n  \nif len(sys.argv) != 2:\n  usage()\n\nrange = sys.argv[1]\n\narping(range, timeout=2)\n</pre>\n\nHope that answers your question..','2010-05-17 16:11:26','2010-05-17 21:11:26','0','0','207','','2'),(
