'192','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','Erik,\n\nDid you go to school for web design?  I ask because I\'ve always found it interesting that security always kind of takes a backseat in school when they\'re teaching programming, web design, networking, etc.\n\nI think my next post will be about information discovery through websites.  It will include some google hacking (I still have a difficult time using that term.. google \"hacking\".. really??)\n\nI\'m going to be busy this weekend (parties! woot!) so it might not be posted until next week.. but stay tuned.  ;-)','2010-05-27 07:14:45','2010-05-27 12:14:45','0','0','267','','2'),(
'193','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','Sie, if you want to talk privately about that, I\'m definitely game.. but, honestly, the header info that I pasted here is about as interesting as headers get, for the most part.. lol\n\nI\'ll see if I can\'t come up with something creative regarding headers.\n\nIs the email that you provided your real one?\n\nAlso, if you go to <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/cgi/env.cgi\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.attackvector.org/cgi/env.cgi</a>, that\'s a script similar to the one in this post, but instead of logging the header info, it displays it, so you can see the information that your browser is giving up to the websites that you visit.\n\nSOME of the information displayed can be changed on the clients side, which can sometimes help in throwing people off, but the important stuff (like, X_FORWARDED_FOR and REMOTE_ADDR) are (usually) out of your control.\n\nI\'ll be talking about some of this in part 3 of this series.  :-)','2010-05-27 07:21:51','2010-05-27 12:21:51','0','0','267','','2'),(
