'235','','1','Marc Ruef','80.238.216.33','marc.ruef@computec.ch','http://www.scip.ch','Hello,\n\nOnce again, a nice post!\n\nIf you are interested in client enumeration, you might want to take a look at two projects of mine:\n\n* browserrecon is going to identify web browsers according to the http headers sent in the request. See http://www.computec.ch/projekte/browserrecon/\n* midfp is going to identify mail clients according to the structure of their message-id (mid). See http://www.scip.ch/?labs.20090911\n\nRegards,\n\nMarc','2010-06-10 09:33:22','2010-06-10 14:33:22','0','0','299','','0'),(
'236','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Marc I just played with Browsercon.. very cool.  It doesn\'t appear to recognize Chrome, however.  Chrome passes Mozilla/5.0....Chrome, so you might want to add a search pattern for Chrome.  Also, is the goal of this project to be 100% passive?  If not, you may want to add a reverse connect to standard proxy ports (8080, 9001, 9030, etc).\n\nIs the fingerprinting done with just the user_agent?  Or does it take into account other aspects of the browser as well?\n\nAs for midfp, that\'s fricken awesome!  I love that you included all of the search patterns.  I\'ve been thinking about writing a filter for mimedefang that does something similar, but grabs the client, originating IP, and other information that could be useful when tracking down a sender.','2010-06-10 13:04:21','2010-06-10 18:04:21','0','235','299','','2'),(
'237','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Sie: Actually, you raise an interesting subject.  I knew they were assigned dynamically, but I\'m sure they don\'t change all that frequently.. so I wonder what information could be had by targeting phones via the internet.  Email headers, browser headers, port scanning, etc.  I\'m going to have to play around with this\n\nGenerally, the Originating_IP header is going to be the real sender.  The \"Received from\" headers include all of the mail servers and whatnot.  Do a reverse lookup on the IP\'s in the \"received from\" headers and it should tell you pretty clearly whether or not it\'s a mailserver or a client.\n\nEveryone tells me that I look like Duff Goldman, so I figured, eh.. why not? ;-)','2010-06-10 13:17:09','2010-06-10 18:17:09','0','233','299','','2'),(
'238','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Marc: Also.. don\'t know if you saw this post or not, but this is a lot of fun when it comes to passively (kind of) gathering information about a user..\n\nhttp://www.attackvector.org/?p=238','2010-06-10 13:19:36','2010-06-10 18:19:36','0','236','299','','2'),(
'239','','1','Sie','20.138.1.245','vickers.j.simon@sky.com','','Just to let you know I did a reverse lookup on the IP\'s and the X_Originating_IP appears to be a mail server of the service I use, lets say Yahoo. The Final recieved header resolves to an unknown client on a network provider that I use, say T-Mobile.\n\nRecieved = T-Mobile Client\nOriginating_IP = Yahoo mail server\n\nAs for mobile devices I just powered off the phone and back on to obtain a new lease. Not sure what the real TTL would be.','2010-06-11 03:43:44','2010-06-11 08:43:44','0','0','299','','0'),(
'240','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','That\'s interesting.. I wonder why it did it that way.\n\nDid you use the phones browser, or something, to go to Yahoo\'s website and send the mail?  Or did you use the mail client built into the phone?\n\nI\'d be interested in seeing the headers of an email sent directly from the phone, bypassing any web service all together.\n\nI\'ll try to make some time to play with this today myself.. :-)','2010-06-11 09:48:48','2010-06-11 14:48:48','0','0','299','','2'),(
'241','','1','godknows','85.67.183.170','myname@email.com','','So you are saying that this info you can use for tracking\n\n\"Received: by 10.213.112.212 with SMTP id x20mr859543ebp.1.1276036240432; Tue, 08 Jun 2010 15:30:40 -0700 (PDT)\nReturn-Path: \nReceived: from [10.0.1.4] (cpc1-pete1-2-3-cust123.know.cable.virginmedia.com [86.0.12.123])\netc\"\n\ncan only be extracted from ppl who use desktop mail clients? Isn\'t there a way to get this info from a mail sent from a gmail account?','2010-06-11 14:53:48','2010-06-11 19:53:48','0','0','299','','0'),(
'242','','1','Marc Ruef','84.74.85.225','marc.ruef@computec.ch','http://www.computec.ch/mruef/','Hello Matt,\n\nThank you for your kind words :)\n\nThe last update of the fingerprint database of the browserrecon dates back to June 2008. This is why Chrome is not detected properly (it was not released back then!). I should update the fingerprint database, I know ;)\n\nbrowserrecon uses different fingerprint matches within the http header of the browser request. Therefore, not only the User-Agent is considered. For example header order, header values and value order is also taken into account. More details are available here:\n\nhttp://www.computec.ch/projekte/browserrecon/?s=documentation\n\nYes, the project is completely passive. But I did some experimental testing where I try to determine the browser version according to active actions. Take a look at:\n\n* http://www.scip.ch/?labs.20090710 (Queue of GET Requests)\n* http://www.scip.ch/?labs.20090904 (Ajax Support)\n\nRegards,\n\nMarc\n\nPS: Of course I know your earlier posts. I read all of them ;)','2010-06-12 04:24:02','2010-06-12 09:24:02','0','0','299','','0'),(
'243','','1','-Sie-','94.15.52.103','vickers.j.simon@sky.com','','Hi Matt, I used the mail client so it would be sending via the email service SMTP server. I could send you a mail via both, web mail via browser on phone &amp; via mail client if you wish? (As long as you \'behave\' with the information ;) )','2010-06-12 14:12:04','2010-06-12 19:12:04','0','0','299','','0'),(
