'245','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@-Sie-: Haha.. I\'ll be good.. I promise.  :-)\n\nSeriously, though.. whenever I\'m handling someone elses information.. if I make a post of it, I make sure to obfuscate their information.. so, no worries.\n\nYou can email them to matt@attackvector.org','2010-06-14 09:10:00','2010-06-14 14:10:00','0','243','299','','2'),(
'246','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@godknows:  Not just from people using desktop mail clients.  In the post, I point out that it\'s people who use both desktop mail clients and the web interface.\n\nAs far as Google, and I hate to say words like \"can\'t\", but.. it would appear that as of this writing, you cannot (*cringe*) extract that information from someone sending you an email using a gmail account.\n\nI have tested this thoroughly myself and have never been able to find any trace of my real IP address in the headers of an email that I\'ve sent through gmail.  Could I be wrong?  Most definitely.. but through my testing, I\'ve not been successful.\n\nThis is not to say, however, that the recipient couldn\'t simply email Google and provide the timestamp/headers/email of an abusive email originating from a gmail account and have Google shut that account down.\n\nIf someone has experienced something different than I have regarding the leaking of information through headers of emails originating from Gmail, PLEASE let me know.  I\'ll update my post and do more testing of my own.','2010-06-14 09:15:37','2010-06-14 14:15:37','0','241','299','','2'),(
'247','','1','~R','72.33.0.55','stack.overflow01@gmail.com','','\"To be honest, Im not sure why some emails have the X-Originating-IP and some dont..\"\n\nMatt, Acc to the RFCs, all X-* headers are optional, guess Google decided to do away with some of these in their email subsystem.','2010-06-18 13:10:30','2010-06-18 18:10:30','0','0','299','','0'),(
'248','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@~R:  Yeah, I know that it\'s at their discretion.. but what I meant (and maybe should have made more clear) is that sometimes, through the same provider, you\'ll get the \"X-Originating-IP\" and sometimes you wont.  I\'m guessing it has something to do with different servers in their farm being configured differently, but I don\'t know that for fact.','2010-06-21 09:35:48','2010-06-21 14:35:48','0','247','299','','2'),(
