'363','','1','snow','91.89.196.14','daniel.n.wb@googlemail.com','','If you had firewalls in that case ;D\n\nNo, in my opinion the only way to keep the net neutrality (with or without the article? =D) as it is is to educate people about basic security, which is difficult to achieve with this old generation of politicians. \nThe money invested into the \"Bundestrojaner\" (federal trojan) to \'lower crime rates\' (the dummy argument here was child pornography (as for internet censorship now too) which is bloated to a huge mafia in the media ) would have been better invested into basic security training and general education about internet related topics (or even an federal security suite, which is ridiculous..). \n\nSo the situation in Germany is not quite ideal, but at least not as bad as in GB/Australia (general) or in the USA (copyright related).','2010-06-30 12:46:08','2010-06-30 17:46:08','0','0','418','','0'),(
'364','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@snow:  Yeah, we\'re having all sorts of fun over here with the RIAA and the MPAA all the other organizations that end with \"AA\".\n\nI don\'t know if there is really an ideal situation to the problems the internet faces.. but people are definitely taking security more seriously these days than in the past.  The scene has changed from hacking and defacing websites to give shout outs to your friends on IRC to fraud, extortion, and espionage - far more serious crimes.','2010-06-30 13:19:27','2010-06-30 18:19:27','0','363','418','','2'),(
'365','','1','snow','91.89.196.14','daniel.n.wb@googlemail.com','','I think that appropriate security measures for all kinds of hosts would prevent at least the crimes of script kiddies and such.... I guess most of the truly expierienced people who deserved the title \'hacker\' are not interested in commiting crimes anyway? I have only a little idea of what you call the scene and probably this is kind of an idealist view, so excuse me if I make wrong assumptions.\n\nOf course there will always be crime in a completly neutral environment, but when most hosts can defend themselves on a basic level, the people who do not gain responsibility with their expierience remain.... which I thought to be a minority up to now.','2010-06-30 14:22:41','2010-06-30 19:22:41','0','0','418','','0'),(
'366','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@snow:  I consider myself a hacker and the people I hang out with, I would consider hackers as well.  We don\'t, usually, set out to break the law, but often times things we do does, in fact, break the law, even though our intent is not malicious.  Script kids are generally the ones out committing the real crimes, I guess.. but I\'ve noticed as of late there appears to be more and more skilled hackers getting a piece of the pie.\n\nWhats frustrating, though, is that businesses and individuals alike all have the ability to defend themselves.. if they\'d only open a web browser and google a bit.  ;-)','2010-06-30 14:29:16','2010-06-30 19:29:16','0','365','418','','2'),(
'367','','1','snow','91.89.196.14','daniel.n.wb@googlemail.com','','Okay, that was roughly my view of the things going on. \n\nThese basic media competence is what I mean with education about security... \nto take it to a less complex level: The only thing German schools have achieved is use of Firefox for most people, even tho they do not know why... 90% of Germans my age (18) do not even consider that their Adobe Reader could be insecure (because they are simply not told). \nI will not start to tell what security means on my school\'s \'central server\' and pretty much any other publicly used server... same thing for public routers, which commonly use the default password for, probably even worse, the default crappy router software.\nWhatever more skilled hackers taking part in intented crimes is alarming... and somewhat requires to change my view on these kind of measures....','2010-06-30 14:50:13','2010-06-30 19:50:13','0','0','418','','0'),(
'368','','1','Sie','20.138.1.245','vickers.j.simon@sky.com','','It is the age old story of Security vs Accessibility. People are not in the know so they have to make things \'idiot\' proof which often means less secure. Unfortunately there is no end, you have to teach people to cover all the security holes the hacker only has to find one.\n\nKeeps me in a job thou so who am I to complain!','2010-07-01 05:09:08','2010-07-01 10:09:08','0','0','418','','0'),(
'369','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Sie:  Ditto.. but I\'m not concerned about ever being out of a job.  As technology grows, so will security.. and hopefully my blog!  :-)','2010-07-01 08:33:54','2010-07-01 13:33:54','0','368','418','','2');
