'393','','1','Sie','20.138.1.245','vickers.j.simon@sky.com','','Just thinking about attacks like this and others with users accessing links / IP that points to the metasploit box. Is the Link/Program/Exploit their side a handler as such or purely a pointer? If it is purely a pointer what is stopping you using an arp spoof twist and point any url to your metasploit box?\n\nYes it involves access to the network but there are ways and means, could this be used to exploit a box without user intervention?\n\nJust a thought between things I am possibly far off the mark......','2010-07-22 06:03:18','2010-07-22 11:03:18','0','0','457','','0'),(
'394','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Sie:  No, it\'s not just a pointer.  It\'s actually kind of an interesting vulnerability.  It only gets executed when Windows renders the icon for a shortcut.  I tried a bunch of different methods to get a Windows box to execute the exploit (ie: net use //whatever/whatever), but, as best I can tell, it needs to be opened in with explorer (not internet explorer, however, you can make it work that way, too).','2010-07-22 09:00:19','2010-07-22 14:00:19','0','393','457','','2'),(
'395','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Larry:  Yeah, I posted it to Full Disclosure because I hadn\'t seen any other demo\'s of the exploit, so I figured it was relevant.  It was as close to spamming as I\'m willing to go.  ;-)\n\nMy first post I wrote about this was really, really bashing SANS for their hype of this.  After playing with it for awhile and considering the impact this has, I laid off a bit, but I still don\'t think they were justified in raising Infocon to yellow.  I mean, I get where they\'re coming from, but....','2010-07-22 09:02:39','2010-07-22 14:02:39','0','392','457','','2'),(
'396','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@null:\n\nmsf &gt; search lnk\n[*] Searching loaded modules for pattern \'lnk\'...\n\nExploits\n========\n\n   Name                                                Rank       Description\n   ----                                                ----       -----------\n   windows/browser/ms10_xxx_windows_shell_lnk_execute  excellent  Microsoft Windows Shell LNK Code Execution\n\nmsf &gt; use windows/browser/ms10_xxx_windows_shell_lnk_execute\nmsf exploit(ms10_xxx_windows_shell_lnk_execute) &gt; \n\nNo leading \"exploit\" on my box.  Is it different on yours?','2010-07-22 09:06:32','2010-07-22 14:06:32','0','391','457','','2'),(
'397','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@Sie:  The other thing, is that you can put the .lnk file anywhere and it will execute, but I\'m experiencing some problems with this at the moment.  I took the .lnk file that was generated by metasploit and copied it to a USB key (as well as a regular directory on the C: drive of my vmware image) and it wouldn\'t trigger until I right clicked on the file.  I\'m not quite sure why.','2010-07-22 09:09:59','2010-07-22 14:09:59','0','393','457','','2'),(
