'528','','1','Matt','70.89.197.145','matt@attackvector.org','http://www.attackvector.org','@dehaul:  I understand and appreciate the difficulty of writing large pieces of software, especially when it\'s done as a large team.  Integration, consistency, etc. all make it a difficult task to manage.\n\nHowever.  In the \"<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythical_man_month\" rel=\"noindex\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mythical Man Month</a>\", Brooks talks about the idea of adding more and more people to projects and the problems that it causes, which is what Microsoft suffers from.  Not only that, but a software giant such as Microsoft, which is worth billions and billions of dollars has the resources available to produce solid code.\n\nYes, Linux has its vulnerabilities, too.  But, there are a few key differences:\n\n1) When a vulnerability is discovered, a patch is issued within hours, not days, not weeks, not years.  There was recently a vulnerability found in \'sudo\'.  Just about as soon as I was done reading the advisory, my autoupdate agent popped up indicating that it wanted to update sudo.  Why can\'t Microsoft seem to accomplish this feat?  Why do I have to wait for a week, or more, for an 0day fix?\n\n2) Vulnerabilities are often found by developers of Linux, not by hackers.  Because source code is openly available to all aspects of Linux, Joe Schmoe programmer can go through the code and if he notices something out of the ordinary, he can report it.  Unlike Microsoft where kids can sit and fuzz the crap out of a program until they discover something.  Developers generally don\'t sit around fuzzing.\n\nI think you\'re wrong to say that Microsoft is targeted due to its market share.  If that were the case, every hacker and their dog would be targeting LAMP, considering that Microsoft cannot touch it when it comes to internet services.  Apache, last I saw, is run on approximately 34% of internet servers, IIS is around 12%.\n\nYes, I will agree that Microsoft brought the computer to the home, which I do appreciate.  My life didn\'t start on Linux, it was DOS, then 3.1, then a mix of Linux and 95.  I never ran Windows 98 or up.  I\'ve also never had a virus, or spyware, nor have I had my identity stolen.  Out of everyone that I know, I\'m the only one who can say this.  Ironically, I\'m also the only one that I know that runs solely Linux.  Hell, even the Windows fanboy Krebs suggests using Linux to do stuff on the internet (<a href=\"http://voices.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2009/10/avoid_windows_malware_bank_on.html\" rel=\"noindex\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://voices.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2009/10/avoid_windows_malware_bank_on.html</a>).\n\nTo be honest, and security completely aside, the fundamental design of Windows is flawed, for the end user, anyway.  One of the biggest issues that I see with Windows is the registry.  Everyone knows that a week after you buy a computer, it wont be as fast as it was when you first bought it.  Why?  The registry.  It is a constantly growing beast that continually takes longer to load the more you use your computer until eventually your computer is so slow that you either have to start from scratch, or buy a new one.  This has worked out remarkably well for Microsoft, but not so well for the consumer.  Microsoft has left it up to the applications to clean up the registry after themselves, but there are soo many terribly written programs out there that this never seems to happen.  If I remove a program, I want it gone.  Period.  I don\'t want 8000 hives saving information in the registry \"in case I decide to reinstall\".\n\nI guess, ultimately, I just expect more out of a company that charges absurd amounts of money for its software, when the end product is slow, bulky, buggy, and will likely get you owned.','2010-09-09 10:05:22','2010-09-09 15:05:22','0','525','573','','2'),(
'529','','1','dehaul','192.101.136.224','dehaul@gmail.com','','Thanks for the nice response... \n\n\nI still think that the market share of Windows does drive those who wish others ill will to attack it. It is used on about 89% of desktops according to this Wikipedia article:\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usage_share_of_operating_systems\n\nThe stupid desktop user is the weakest link - not the server admins. If stupid users were using more of another operating system, say Apple, I really believe the malware writers would focus their attention on those other systems.\n\n\nI am a software developer for a Windows product, and I fuzz it a lot :) I will agree that developers do not usually sit around fuzzing - but I think that is also true of OS X and Linux developers as well.\n\n\nI also agree the registry sucks, but I can see how in a development meeting 15 years ago, it seemed like a good idea at the time. Same with their stupid COM interface.\n\n\n\"I guess, ultimately, I just expect more out of a company that charges absurd amounts of money for its software, when the end product is slow, bulky, buggy, and will likely get you owned.\"\n\nThat is a fair point that can only be made by the person who has the money in their pocket. Unfortunately, 89% of the desktop users have also evaluated this decision and went with Windows. \n\nI also continue to make the same decision as you have - and even have converted my wife :) Hooray for Ubuntu!','2010-09-10 17:52:32','2010-09-10 22:52:32','0','0','573','','0');
