'534','','1','xett','114.75.166.35','skinbearxett@gmail.com','','I have foundquality and quantity to be very rarely linked. An example of this is cars. \n\nLook at the history of the Internal Combustion Engine powered automobile. First developed in the mid 19th century the first cars were very loud, slow and produced lots of fumes. Newspapers from the day ridicule the automobile as a poorly designed tool which was of such low quality it would fade from existance in a short period. \n\nElectric cars were also made around the same time, enjoying much greater success than fueled versions. They were quiet, fast and produced no fumes. Why then do we have fueled cars now?\n\n1914, enter Henry Ford. He started the production line with the Ford Model T. Purely by affordability he managed to spread the fueled car through America, Europe and even the edges of Asia. Over the years his methodology has been applied to almost all other production goods. \n\nThere was no benifit which the Ford Model T had over any other car at the time but for cost, and nowdays the cost for an electric is the same. However due to the market saturation of fueled cars electrics are not taking off at the rate they should.','2010-10-30 03:41:04','2010-10-30 08:41:04','0','0','573','','0'),(
