'60','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=60','0','open','','2','This is probably going to consist of multiple parts, the first part being the concept and background, the next part being some code to implement, and the third will be about putting it all together and what it looks like in the wild.\n\nBut, first, we\'ll start with some background.\n<!--more-->\nMan in the Middle attacks (MiM from here on out) have been around for about as long as we\'ve had networks.  They range in complexity, but in simplest of terms, a MiM attack is one where the attacker convinces the network that he is the gateway, forcing network traffic to be routed through his machine before leaving the network, thus allowing him to sniff all the data flowing in and out of the network.  Needless to say, you don\'t want this to happen to you.\n\nThe one piece of this attack that makes it more difficult for an attacker is that he needs to already be on your network in some fashion.  Whether he hacked a box, or got in through a backdoor, or worm, or.. whatever.. he first needs to gain some sort of access to your network in order to be able to pull this off.  That said, it\'s not that difficult to gain access enough to pull off a MiM attack.\n\nSo, step one for an attacker is to gain access.  Lets say that he got in by crafting a PDF and sending it to an employee who opened it.  Lets say the payload of this PDF was one that utilized the VNC.DLL, allowing remote access.  I picked on PDF because it seems that there are just far too many vulnerabilities in Adobe Reader as of late.\n\nOk, so the attacker now has remote access to one of your companies workstations.  He connects after hours and essentially takes over this machine while everyone from the office is at home sleeping.  He begins poking and prodding around the network and determines that penetrating the servers is easier said than done.  Enter, ARP poisoning.\n\nHe opens up the web browser on this newly compromised machine and downloads \"Cain & Abel\", which is a \"password recovery tool\".  This tool has the ability to sniff network packets and poison arp tables.  Not exactly sure how this helps in password recovery, but...\n\nAfter installing Cain & Abel, he begins broadcasting packets to the network that look like this:  \n\n10.0.0.1 = gateway router\n10.0.0.10 = compromised machine that attacker is controlling with Cain & Abel\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n13:41:46.243899 arp who-has 10.0.0.1 tell 10.0.0.10\n13:41:46.243918 arp reply 10.0.0.1 is-at 00:AA:AA:AA:AA:AA\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so now he knows that the router resides at 00:AA:AA:AA:AA:AA.  Lets say the the compromised machine has the mac address of 00:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB.  Cain & Abel will then begin injecting unicast packets that looks something like this:\n\nThis time, 10.0.0.1 = gateway and 10.0.0.55 = coworker\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n13:41:51.101101 arp who-has 10.0.0.1 tell 10.0.0.55\n13:41:51.241002 arp reply 10.0.0.1 is-at 00:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB\n13:41:51.301101 arp who-has 10.0.0.55 tell 10.0.0.1\n13:41:51.401101 arp reply 10.0.0.55 is-at 00:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, what just took place is he told 10.0.0.55 that the router (10.0.0.1) is located at 00:BB:BB.... and then told the router that 10.0.0.55 is located at 00:BB:BB.  Cain & Abel will set up a quick and dirty routing table, allowing this to be transparent to everyone on the network and is now officially acting as the network gateway for 10.0.0.55.  Any data to or from this computer first goes through the compromised machine.  And, since Cain & Abel is a \"password recovery tool\", it will sniff the network flow for anything similar to \"user\" and \"password\" and log anything matching.\n\nCain & Abel will do this for every box on the network, forcing all data in and out of the network to first go through this machine.  This network is now, most definitely, \"owned.\"  Especially when the sysadmin gets into the office in the morning and logs in to his machine, and then into the firewall, and mail server, and NAS, and every other major service box on the network.  Every username and password that he sends will be logged.  Lets hope that he decides that the website needs some updating today.  Having his username and password to the FTP server for the website would be pretty sweet.\n\nEXCEPTIONS: If the sysadmin uses SSH (which he should be!) to log in to these machines, the traffic will be encrypted and wont be deciphered.  However, since the network is already compromised, sniffing the user/password that he\'s using to mount file shares will be trivial, and because of his role at the company, he\'s probably got elevated privileges.\n\nOnce a MiM attack is successful, you are in a really, really bad spot.  The level of compromise is severe, as it\'s not isolated to one machine, it\'s network wide.  You do not want to be in this situation.  Ever.\n\nThere are countless tools available on the internet to pull off a MiM attack.  And, no, if you\'ve heard that by having a switched network that you\'re protected from this, you\'re sadly mistaken.  It was easier back in the day on non-switched networks, because you only had to poison one table.  Now with switched networks, you have to poison each machine you want to sniff.  Big whoop, this is why God created for() loops.\n\nNow, you may be thinking \"Yeah, but I don\'t let my users run Adobe, or IE, or Firefox, or Office, or any software at all on their machines.. our network is impenetrable\".  Well, besides having the most unproductive office ever, what about that 802.11 AP that you have set up in the conference room so that when there are meetings, people can bring their laptops and have internet/network access without having to run wires everywhere?  Oh  you\'re using WEP++SUPERDUPERPSK++DEFCON5 to protect your wireless?  You might want to Google for, like, \'aircrack-ng\'.\n\nThere are tons of vulnerabilities surrounding wireless.  Wireless has no place on a corporate network and using this attack method, the attacker doesn\'t even need to compromise a machine.. just the WEP key.  Once compromised, he can inject packets all day long using his own computer.  Ponder that for a minute, and then think about your local coffee shop, or whatever other hotspot you use.  No need to even compromise the wireless network in that situation.. just sit down, order an espresso and poison the crap out of the network, forcing all of the other customers to send their data to you.\n\nTo those out there who are immediately going to run out and attempt this hack... keep in mind that you are not invisible and you can be traced.  I am not going to get into how, or how to avoid being traced, though, because that\'s not really the point of this post.  Just know that it\'s easy to locate the attacker by using his mac address.  \"Lets see, it\'s a Dell card.. there are 2 people here using Dell\'s.. one is a 78 year old woman looking up recipes.. the other is a 17 year old kid who has a tshirt that says, \"I read your email\".  Hmm....\"\n\nOk, so, I think you get the idea.. this is a dangerous, dangerous, often overlooked attack vector.  Most admins know that it exists, but don\'t realise to what extent it\'s capable, or how to protect against it.\n','','2010-03-23 14:17:30','2010-03-23 19:17:30','','','2010-03-23 14:17:30','2010-03-23 19:17:30','arp-poisoning-and-man-in-the-middle-attacks','0','','publish','ARP Poisoning and Man in the Middle Attacks [part 1]','post',''),(
'66','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=66','0','open','','2','So, CanSecWest hosted Pwn2Own again this year, which is essentially a challenge offered to hackers across the world to come in to a controlled environment, given certain targets to attack, and the first to successfully compromise the target, wins the target computer/phone/whathaveyou and a decent chunk of change.\n\nPwn2Own has been responsible for some major advances in exploitation and vulnerabilities (Ahem.. Wifi hacking/WEP cracking).  Every year, the bar definitely gets raised and the people contending definitely have their work cut out for them.  In fact, I\'m usually blown away by the people who attend this event.  From what I can tell, they\'re in the upper echelons of the security world.\n<!--more-->\nToday was the first day of the conference and the three major browsers fell.  Internet Explorer 8, Firefox, and Safari.  Google Chrome remains standing, because no one chose to target that browser.  Chalk up another victory to Google.\n\nThe exploitation of IE8 is rather substantial, as it was IE8 running on Windows 7, which, according to Microsoft, has been built around the concept of security.  It\'s also the 3rd version of Windows to utilise \"DEP\" (Data Execution Protection).  DEP is essentially sandbox in which all software runs.  So, to effectively exploit IE8, not only do you need to exploit the browser itself, you also need to find your way out of the sandbox.  This is easier said than done.\n\nFirefox was also pwned on the Windows 7 platform.  It will be interesting to see if both hackers used the same tricks to escape DEP.  Unfortunately, because like, every big technology company known to man is a sponsor of this event, the contestants are under strict rules to not give out any information on the vulnerability/exploit they used to compromise the target.  I\'m not sure how long this vow of silence is supposed to last, but I\'ve seen exploits released into the wild very shortly after Pwn2Own, so.. we\'ll see!\n\nThe other browser that went down was Safari.  Interestingly enough, Charlie Miller once again targeted Apple and showed that Mac is more easily pwnable than Windows.  Charlie Miller is responsible for the exploitation of more than 20 vulnerabilities in Apple software.  This ranges from the iPhone, to Adobe.  He claims that Mac is far more easy to exploit because of its lack of security features such as DEP and ASLR (address space layout randomization).\n\nI find this a little interesting because Mac OSX was built on top of a really solid foundation, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and various other components from various other unices.  I guess, though, it\'s foundation came to be before PaX (Linux\'s version of ASLR - built before ASLR.  So, there.) was common.  I\'m pretty confident in saying, though, after today, that the next Mac OS released will have some form of DEP, ASLR, PaX, etc.\n\nNow, about Google Chrome.  I love Google, I really, truly, do.  I\'m one of the biggest Google fan boys there are, but they\'re not perfect, so to assume that they weren\'t pwned today doesn\'t mean they wont be.  \n\nGoogle Chrome has additional security features beyond that of DEP and ASLR that make it more difficult to exploit.  Granted.  However, targeting a browser which has minimal market share doesn\'t make much sense.  If 1% of your website visitors are using Chrome, and the other 99% are using a mixture of Safari, Firefox, and IE.. well, guess which browsers are going to be targeted?\n\nThat said, because it\'s not being targeted, as of yet, maybe that gives enough reason to switch over to it.  ;-)\n\nTo be honest, based on the results, your best bet for web browsing security, is a tightly secured Linux box running Google Chrome.  Plus, that set up is free.  Hmm, more secure, and free.  How can you go wrong?\n\nSorry, I\'m a Linux fan boy as well.\n\n','','2010-03-25 12:47:11','2010-03-25 17:47:11','','','2010-03-25 12:47:11','2010-03-25 17:47:11','pwn2own-lesson-learned-dont-browse-the-web','0','','publish','Pwn2Own lesson learned - Don\'t browse the web.','post',''),(
'69','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=69','0','open','','2','Well, we\'re on to part two.  For part two of this post, I\'d like to talk about wireless vulnerabilities and how the Man in the Middle (MitM from now on) attack comes in to play on a wireless network.\n\nMost of us have, or have used, a wireless network.  There are, essentially, two different types.  Those that are wide open, available for anyone to connect to, and those that are not wide open and that use some type of encryption and require a key to connect.\n\nI\'m not going to really cover the wide open networks, because absolutely no compromise needs to take place in order to do MitM and you simply shouldn\'t run one.  \'Nuff said.  If you don\'t know how to secure yours, or don\'t know if yours is open or secured, visit your wireless router manufacturer\'s website for instructions on enabling encryption (WEP, WPA, etc.)  But, before you do that, continue reading, as it will help you choose which version of encryption you enable.\n<!--more-->\nHere is a chart to show the seriousness of this issue.\n\nThis chart shows the breakdown of the different types of wireless networks that I found on my latest war drive.  I was able to find 3,000 networks in about 30 minutes.  If you don\'t know what war driving is, click <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wardriving\">here</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.interwebz.us/pics/piechart2.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.interwebz.us/pics/piechart2.jpg\"></a>\n\nThat chart should frighten you, because there\'s a REALLY good chance that you aren\'t one of the machines in the green.\n\nEssentially, about 70% of the networks that I found were hackable.\n\nSo, now that we know that there\'s no shortage of available networks, lets discuss the attacks against these.\n\nAny machines using a network in the blue are wide open to compromise.\n\nAny machines using a network in the yellow or orange are hackable, and the networks in the green are either very difficult to compromise, or there is no known exploits to compromise this type of network.\n\nThe networks in orange are secured by WEP, and those in yellow utilize WPA+TKIP or PSK.  We\'ll start with WEP.\n\nEach packet transmitted across a WEP secured network contains a 3 byte IV (Initialization Vector) as part of each packet.  In simple terms, this IV is a part of the key used to secure the wireless network.  So, if we collect enough packets, it\'s possible to assemble these IV\'s into something we can crack and get the key.\n\nIn order to collect IV\'s, though, we need traffic.  If someone isn\'t using the wireless network, there wont be much traffic so we have to generate traffic.  There are a number of ways to do this.. the easiest way is to associate with the access point and send ARP requests.  The AP will broadcast responses, thus generating the traffic that we need to collect to crack the IV\'s.  The attacker will need about 20,000 IV\'s in order to crack a WEP key.  It takes about 5 minutes, so very little patience is needed.  Once the IV\'s are collected, it takes my laptop about 30 seconds to crack a 128bit key.  Once I have the key, I\'m in.\n\nThe other type of network is WPA+TKIP or PSK.  These work differently, as they don\'t transmit IV\'s with each packet.. but the key is sent when the client first connects.  No one wants to sit around and wait for a client to disconnect and reconnect, though.. that could take forever.  So, what we do, is run our sniffer, associate with the AP and send a deauthenticate packet spoofed from one of the clients.  This will disconnect the client and the client will automatically try to reauthenticate.  When it does, we\'ll be listening and will catch the key with our sniffer.  Then, we run a simple brute force attack against it.  Depending on how difficult the key is, it could take 2 seconds, or 2 years.  I\'ve yet to encounter one that takes longer than 10 minutes.\n\nOK, so, now we\'re connected to a wireless network.  Unlike the previous example, where an attacker compromises a windows box and utilizes a tool called Cain & Abel, in this scenario he\'s connected via his own computer.  Because of the tools used to hack a wireless network, we\'ll assume he\'s using Linux.\n\nHe\'ll now use a tool named Ettercap to perform a MitM attack against the network.  Once again, he\'ll poison the ARP table and redirect network traffic through his computer before sending it to the gateway.  By doing so, he\'ll collect all the data going in and out of the network.\n\nOne frightening point to include here is that Ettercap has the ability to forge SSL certificates, meaning that it will also collect encrypted network traffic.  This means that he\'s not just going to be collecting mostly benign data, he\'ll now be collecting usernames and passwords to banks and financial websites.\n\nPart 3 of this post is going to talk about measures you can take to protect yourself from these attacks.\n','','2010-04-03 15:55:34','2010-04-03 20:55:34','','','2010-04-03 15:55:34','2010-04-03 20:55:34','arp-poisoning-and-man-in-the-middle-attacks-part-2','0','','publish','ARP Poisoning and Man in the Middle Attacks [part 2]','post','');
