'267','25','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=267','0','open','','2','View part 1 of this post <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=265\">here</a>\n\nOk, so we have lots of email addresses and names of employees.. but we know nothing of their network.  And, again, because this is the preliminary discovery process, we\'re going to avoid getting too aggressive.  We just want to collect information at this point.\n\nFirst, lets take a look at DNS.\n\nI\'ll be using console tools, but there are many websites that will provide this information as well.  I would actually suggest using these website tools in lieu of console tools where possible because the IP seen in the logs will be the websites IP, not yours.\n\nTwo of my favorite websites for IP/DNS stuff are:\n<!--more-->\n<a href=\"http://www.serversniff.net\">www.serversniff.net</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.robtex.com/\">www.robtex.com</a>\n\nCheck them out.. \n\nAnyway, the first thing I want is an overview of their external network.  There are a few ways of doing this.. I\'ll show two of them here.\n\n1)  Simple DNS lookups.  If the company is one that owns a block of IP\'s, you can just resolve each individual IP address.  You can find out IP block information from <a href=\"https://www.arin.net/\">ARIN</a>.\n\nUsing this method, I have their netblock info, and I\'ve gathered another email address.  This one is the email address of, apparently, their uber tech.  heidi_hXX@xyz.com.\n\nKnowing their block of IP\'s helps us tremendously.  It prevents us from having to do anything that might look suspicious (ie - zone transfers).  Here\'s what we find:\n\n<blockquote>\nOrgName:    XYZ\nOrgID:      XYZ\nAddress:    6455 Some Drive\nCity:       Dallas\nStateProv:  TX\nPostalCode: 12345\nCountry:    US\n\nNetRange:   1.2.3.0 - 1.2.3.255 \nCIDR:       1.2.3.0/24 \n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n# nmap -sL 1.2.3.0/24|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){if(/^.*?fors+(w+.*?s+(.*)/) { print \"$1\"; }}\'\n\nxyzweb.xyz.com (1.2.3.103)\nwww.xyz.com (1.2.3.106)\nmail.xyz.com (1.2.3.107)\nmug.xyz.com (1.2.3.108)\nse-gate1.xyz.com (1.2.3.109)\n..snip..\nipmail.xyz.com (1.2.3.170)\ncitrix.xyz.com (1.2.3.178)\nns2.xyz.info (1.2.3.201)\nwork.xyz.com (1.2.3.216)\nstorageim.xyz.com (1.2.3.219)\ngov.xyz.com (1.2.3.226)\n..snip..\n</blockquote>\n\nAll sorts of neat information.  Apparently they do something with the government, they run Citrix, and I would bet that ipmail is probably a webmail type of a thing.\n\nMethod #2 is doing a zone transfer.  This will probably end up telling you more than just doing the reverse lookups..\n\n<blockquote>\n# nmap --script dns-zone-transfer.nse --script-args dnszonetransfer.domain=xyz.com -p53 ns.xyz.info\n\nStarting Nmap 5.30BETA1 ( http://nmap.org ) at 2010-05-25 13:32 CDT\nNSE: Script Scanning completed.\nNmap scan report for ns.xyz.info (1.2.3.200)\nHost is up (0.0040s latency).\nPORT   STATE SERVICE\n53/tcp open  domain\n| dns-zone-transfer:  \n| xyz.com                 SOA     ns.xyz.info hostmaster.xyz.info  \n| xyz.com                 A       1.2.3.106                           \n| xyz.com                 NS      ns2.xyz.info                         \n| xyz.com                 NS      ns.xyz.info                          \n| xyz.com                 MX      ipmail.xyz.com                       \n| xyz.com                 TXT    \n| ns2.xyz.info            A       1.2.3.201                           \n| access.xyz.com          A       3.2.1.137                          \n| activewatch.xyz.com     A       1.2.3.131                           \n| apps.xyz.com            A       1.2.3.133                           \n| awfiles.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.164                           \n| blog.xyz.com            A       1.2.3.224                           \n| blogs.xyz.com           A       1.2.3.224                           \n| cbt.xyz.com             A       1.2.3.112                           \n| citrix.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.178                           \n| cortex.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.222                           \n| cortex1.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.222                           \n| cortex2.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.221                           \n| crm.xyz.com             CNAME  \n| cutlass.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.156                           \n| dtree.xyz.com           A       1.2.3.155                           \n| easyquote.xyz.com       A       1.2.3.134                                           \n| forms.xyz.com           CNAME  \n| forums.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.118                           \n| gov.xyz.com             A       1.2.3.226                           \n| hbserver.xyz.com        A       1.2.3.115                           \n| info.xyz.com            MX      mail.somedomain.com\n| info.xyz.com            TXT    \n| inside.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.108                           \n| ipmail.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.170                           \n| itreq.xyz.com           A       1.2.3.113                           \n..huge snip..                          \n| support.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.154                           \n| survey.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.149                           \n| training.xyz.com        A       1.2.3.115                           \n| version.xyz.com         A       1.2.3.177                           \n| versions.xyz.com        A       1.2.3.177                           \n| websvc.xyz.com          A       1.2.3.166                           \n| work.xyz.com            A       1.2.3.216                           \n| www.xyz.com             A       1.2.3.106                           \n| www2.xyz.com            A       1.2.3.198                           \n| xyz.xyz.com             A       1.2.3.128                                              \n|_xyz.com                 SOA     ns.xyz.info hostmaster.xyz.info  \n\nNmap done: 1 IP address (1 host up) scanned in 4.32 seconds\n</blockquote>\n\nI wasn\'t going to paste the whole thing, but.. yeah.  That actually tells us a ton.. storage, portals, and partners, oh my!  This gives us a plethora of targets when it\'s time to really begin testing.\n\nNow, I\'d really like to know a little about the internal network.  I think the easiest way to accomplish this, and correct me if I\'m wrong, is through email.  On their website, they have a contact@xyz.com email address, as do most companies.\n\n<blockquote>\nTo: contact@xyz.com\nFrom: steve_smith@hotmail.com\nSubject: SQL Storage Solution\n\nHi, could you please send me some information regarding your SuperDuper SQL Storage Solution?\n\nThanks!\n\nSteve Smith\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\nTo: Steve Smith\nFrom: Mary RXX\nSubject: Re: SQL Storage Solution\n\nHi Steve,\n\nHere is our brochure.  Would you like one of our sales associates contact you?\n\nThanks,\nMary RXX\n[contact info here]\n</blockquote>\n\nNo, Mary, I\'ll contact them.. I already have all their email addresses, names, highschools, degrees, and home phone numbers.. but for the time being, we have what we want..\n\n<blockquote>\nReceived: from mail.xyz.com (mail.xyz.com [1.2.3.107])\n..snip..\nReceived: from local-mail.xyz.com (gw1.xyz.com [10.0.1.2])\n	by mail.xyz.com (8.14.1/8.14.1) with ESMTP id o4PIgSRX030051\n	for <steve_smith@hotmail.com>; Tue, 25 May 2010 13:42:29 -0500\n..snip..\nX-Mailer: Lotus Notes Release 8.0 August 18, 2009\n..snip..\nX-MIMETrack: Serialize by Router on XYZSERVER-1/XYZ(Release 8.0.3|September 26, 2009)\nX-Scanned-By: MIMEDefang 2.64 on 10.0.1.4\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, they\'re doing NAT (duh.. who doesn\'t), but.. it also appears that they have a sendmail server living in the DMZ (as indicated by the MIMEDefang line), which is 10.0.1.4.  Then, they have this box named \'gw1.xyz.com\', with the IP of 10.0.1.2, where there appears to be a Lotus Notes server.  I would really like to know what things look like behind that second gateway.  Time to send another email.\n\nThis time, we\'re going to have to be a bit more crafty because we need for the recipient to click on a link.  Sales people are the best to target when trying to obtain information through getting them to click on stuff.  They receive tons of email, all day long from random people interested in products/whatever.  So, we do something like this.\n\nIf you read part 1 of this post, you\'ll know that we found the sales executives name, and I was able to pair it up with an email address:\n\n<blockquote>\nTo: ken_bXX@xyz.com\nFrom: steve_smith@hotmail.com\nSubject: Product comparison\n\nHi Ken,\n\nMary RXX told me to send this question on to you.. could you please evaluate the product shown here and let me know how it compares to yours?\n\nEssentially, I want to know how to justify the additional cost of buying XYZ\'s over this (a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/cgi/productdocument.cgi\")one(/a).\n\nThanks,\nSteve Smith\n</blockquote>\n[Note]: I had to change the \"<\" to \"(\" around the anchor tag because Wordpress was converting this to an actual link, even when using the pre tag.\n\nThe \"productdocument.cgi\" looks something like this:\n\n<pre>\n#!/usr/bin/perl -wT\nuse strict;\nuse CGI qw(:standard);\nuse CGI::Carp qw(warningsToBrowser fatalsToBrowser);\n\nprint header;\nprint start_html(\"Environment\");\nopen(F, \">>log.log\") || die \"$!\";\nforeach my $key (sort(keys(%ENV))) {\n    print F \"$key = $ENV{$key}<br>n\";\n}\nprint \"(meta http-equiv=\"REFRESH\" content=\"0\";url=http://www.somedomain.com/neat/document.pdf\")\"\nprint end_html;\n</pre>\n[Note:] Again with the stupid (\'s instead of <\'s!\n\nSo, Ken will get the email, click on the link, and then be redirected to some random PDF that shows product details.  He\'ll then probably email me back with a woody about how much better his product is than the one in the PDF... but that\'s not what we\'re interested in.  The \"productdocument.cgi\" script logs all of the environment variables when he clicks on the link.  What I\'m looking for is something pertaining to a proxy, or being forwarded...\n\n<blockquote>\n..huge snip..\nHTTP_USER_AGENT = Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.01; Windows NT 6.0)\nHTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR = 10.0.0.201\nREMOTE_ADDR = 1.2.3.4\nREMOTE_PORT = 1234\n..huge snip..\n</blockquote>\n\nIE 6.. really?  I\'ll bet the penetration part of this is going to be easy.\n\nAnyway!\n\nLook what we have!  There\'s an X_FORWARDED_FOR header, giving us the internal IP of the workstation that clicked on my link.  Now if I need to write anything, I\'ll know, minimally, the network layout of their internal-internal LAN.\n\nAt this point, we have employee names, email addresses, the DNS topography, email server information, we know that they have a DMZ and an internal LAN beyond that, and we know the layout of it, to a certain extent.\n\nWe also know that they\'re running old software, which says something about their update policy.  He\'s probably not the only person running IE 6 in that office.  We also know that he has no problem clicking on random links.  We\'ll keep this in mind when figuring out what the best way into this network is.\n\nThere are a number of other avenues that I could take to obtain more information, but, honestly, I\'m rather certain that I\'ll be able to reach my goal (internal file server and client database) with the information I have.  Knowing that the clients on the internal lan use old software gives me a definite point of attack.  I did notice, though, that they\'re running some AV on their mailserver in the DMZ, so I\'ll have to avoid sending anything with a payload through email, so, honestly, I\'ll probably just use browser_autopwn (part of Metasploit) and send our helpful sales guy a link.  I\'ll target him, specifically, because I would bet that he\'s got full access to the client database, as his job involves getting new clients and contacting current clients.\n\nPart 3 of this post will discuss some of the things that company XYZ could have done to, at least, make my job harder, though most of the information I\'ve obtained thus far is impossible to completely hide.\n\n','','2010-05-26 07:39:01','2010-05-26 12:39:01','','','2010-05-26 07:39:01','2010-05-26 12:39:01','corporate-information-discovery-part-2','0','','publish','Corporate Information Discovery [Part 2]','post',''),(
'275','15','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=275','0','open','','2','About a month ago I wrote a post going over some code that I wrote that basically went out and grabbed email addresses after doing search queries.  I\'ve since updated the code and was asked to post it, so I decided to just recreate the entire post.\n\nHere\'s the new code.  \n<!--more-->\n\n<b>Note</b>: If you use this repeatedly in too short of amount of time, Google will temporarily ban you from doing searches.  It happened to me lots while I was writing this.. lol.  They\'re pretty uppity about using their search engine for automated queries.. and even more so when it appears that you\'re searching for email addresses.\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n# www.attackvector.org\n# 5/27/2010\n\n\nif($ARGV[0] eq \"\") {\n  print \"Usage: harvest.pl <domain>n\";\n  print \"IE: harvest.pl gmail.comn\";\n  exit(0);\n}\n      \n\n$domain = $ARGV[0];\n\n# We don\'t want to use a domain name when searching LinkedIn, we want the\n# company name, so strip off .whatever\n($ldomain) = (split /./, $domain)[0];\n\n# These are the search queries that we run.\n%engines = ( \n  \"http://www.google.com/search....\" => \"Google\",\n  \"http://search.yahoo.com/search?....\" => \"Yahoo\",\n  \"http://www.altavista.com/web/results?...\" => \"AltaVista\",\n  \"http://www.google.com/search?...\" => \"LinkedIn\",\n);\n\n$i = 0;\n\n\nforeach $engine (keys %engines) { \n  # I prefer using lynx instead of LWP for a number of reasons.  I realize that this\n  # breaks its portability and calling external programs is a programming\n  # blaspheme, but.. \n  open(F, \"lynx -dump \"$engine\"|\") || die \"$!\";\n  print \"$engines{$engine} results...n\";\n  while(<F>) {\n    # Verify that it\'s an email address.  I\'m pretty sure this will catch\n    # any RFC compliant address and add it to the %addrs hash.\n    if(/^.*?(w{1}[w-.]*@$domain).*/) {\n      $addrs{$1}++;\n    }\n    # This grabs the names from our LinkedIn search\n    if(/^.*?d+.s+[d+](w+s+w+)s+-s+LinkedIn.*/) {\n      $i = 1;\n      $name = $1;\n      $names{$name}++;\n      next;\n    }\n    # This grabs their title/description.  It\'s \"2\" because the description\n    # line is wordwrapped, so we want to grab both lines and then push it\n    # into an array.  This is necessary in order to get the description to\n    # fit on a single line.  This creates an array with the name of the\n    # person.  So, after this, there could be an array named @bob.barker(). \n    # Is this even kosher? lol\n    if(/^s+(w+.*)/ && $i <= \"2\") {\n      push(@{$name}, $1);\n      $i++;\n    }\n  }\n  \n  # Now we cycle through the %addrs hash and print them in no particular\n  # order.  This will also give you a feel for how much better one search\n  # engine is over another.\n  foreach $line (keys %addrs) {\n    print \"$line found $addrs{$line} timesn\";\n    $addrs{$line} = \"0\";\n  }\n  print \"n\";\n}\n\n# Cycle through the %names hash and print the name and dump the entire array\n# that matches the name.\nprint \"LinkedIn Title Searchn\";\nforeach $line (keys %names) {\n  print \"$line - @{$line}n\";\n}\n</pre>\n\nThe output looks like this:\n\n<blockquote>\nAltaVista results...\nShareholder.Relations@pepsi.com found 1 times\n\nYahoo results...\ncustomer.service@pepsi.com found 1 times\nNicole.Bradley@pepsi.com found 1 times\nnicole.bradley@pepsi.com found 1 times\nShareholder.Relations@pepsi.com found 1 times\n\nGoogle results...\npepsico.foundation@pepsi.com found 1 times\ncustomer.service@pepsi.com found 1 times\npepsicompany@pepsi.com found 1 times\njeff.dahncke@pepsi.com found 2 times\nDahncke@pepsi.com found 1 times\nwebmaster@pepsi.com found 1 times\nRelations@pepsi.com found 2 times\nDetwiler@pepsi.com found 1 times\ncaitlin.faughnan@pepsi.com found 2 times\nnicole.bradley@pepsi.com found 2 times\ninfo@pepsi.com found 2 times\nterri.maini@pepsi.com found 1 times\ndavid.dececco@pepsi.com found 1 times\nTyson@pepsi.com found 1 times\nNicole.Bradley@pepsi.com found 1 times\nPBGPressCenter@pepsi.com found 1 times\nShareholder.Relations@pepsi.com found 0 times\n\nLinkedIn results...\npepsico.foundation@pepsi.com found 0 times\ncustomer.service@pepsi.com found 0 times\npepsicompany@pepsi.com found 0 times\njeff.dahncke@pepsi.com found 0 times\nDahncke@pepsi.com found 0 times\nwebmaster@pepsi.com found 0 times\nRelations@pepsi.com found 0 times\nDetwiler@pepsi.com found 0 times\ncaitlin.faughnan@pepsi.com found 0 times\nnicole.bradley@pepsi.com found 0 times\ninfo@pepsi.com found 0 times\nterri.maini@pepsi.com found 0 times\ndavid.dececco@pepsi.com found 0 times\nTyson@pepsi.com found 0 times\nNicole.Bradley@pepsi.com found 0 times\nPBGPressCenter@pepsi.com found 0 times\nShareholder.Relations@pepsi.com found 0 times\n\nLinkedIn Title Search\nKatie Lacey - Greater New York City Area - Fmr SVP Marketing, ESPN Led all marketing efforts for Pepsi-Cola North America\'s carbonated\nSteve Honorowski - Greater Detroit Area - Regional Sales Director at Pepsi Beverages Company\nErin Taylor - Sacramento, California Area - Business Development Manager, West BU at Pepsi Bottling Group\nJaime Vasquez - Dallas/Fort Worth Area - International Marketing Executive Pepsi Cola North America. (Public Company; 10001 or more employees;\nPatrick Mork - San Francisco Bay Area - VP Marketing at Getjar Pepsi-Co. (Public Company; 10001 or more employees; PEP; Consumer\nFrank Simone - Greater Chicago Area - Dir of Sales - C&G Channel at Pepsi-Cola Included setting direction for price, promotion, placement and\nVictor Crawford - Greater New York City Area - Executive Vice President Supply Chain Board Member, The Pepsi Bottling Group Foundation Past Board\nPepsi Cordova - United States - -- View Pepsi Cordova\'s professional profile on LinkedIn. LinkedIn is\nRussell Weiner - Greater New York City Area - Proven leader, strategic planner and innovative marketer with over 15 years of experience.\nJanine Waclawski - Greater