'291','6','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=291','0','open','','2','I had a reader leave a comment who was interested in getting a better understanding of what makes a real penetration tester.  He was essentially tired of seeing all of these so-called \"pen testers\" who have adopted the name and rely, almost solely, on tools like Nessus and Metasploit.\n\nBack in the day, we called these individuals \"script kids\".  They were the ankle biters of the hacking community.  They knew what an IP looked like, and understood how to click buttons with their mouse, or, occasionally, ./pwn, but beyond that they were clueless.  These are generally people who want to impress their friends and are rather opportunistic.  Give them a single, decently secured network, and they will fail.\n\nThis is by no means a post to cut down the importance of tools like Nessus and Metasploit.  Both of them are in my tool box and I use them.  I don\'t use Nessus as often because it\'s noisy, but if you\'re not worried about being stealthy, Nessus makes pretty quick work of vulnerability discovery.\n<!--more-->\nSo, anyway, what does it take to be a good/professional penetration tester?  Surprisingly, you don\'t have to be a technological genius to accomplish this.  The best pen testers are the ones who have a balanced approach.  They utilize social, physical, and technical strategies to achieve their goal.  \n\nLets take a few different examples.  An example of a physical approach would be... what is the point of waging a massive attack against a network, trying to breach firewalls, avoid IDS, social engineering the receptionist, etc.. if you can simply walk in to the building a plug a laptop into a network jack and have instant access to everything on the lan?  \n\nExample 2.. the social approach.  Lets say you\'re faced with fort knox level security.  Retina scanners, 32 firewalls, each with IDS, rabid dogs with lasers mounted to their heads, and (insert some other absurd network security devices here).  Well, a physical approach isn\'t going to work here.. and, most likely, a technical style attack isn\'t going to succeed, either.  So, why not have the receptionist (or, anyone else, for that matter) just give you the information that you want?  Learn the lingo of the industry, learn their operations and procedures, then simply social engineer the crap out of them until they give you the information that you want.\n\nExample 3.. the technical approach.  The target is across an ocean.. they don\'t speak English and you don\'t speak Chinese.  This is where your technical ability and tools come in handy.  Metasploit, Nessus, Nmap, oh my.\n\nGenerally when I have a target, I will utilize all three approaches.  My goal is to get in, or obtain certain information.  I honestly don\'t care how I get it, just so long as at the end of the attack, it\'s in my possession.  If you limit yourself to just the technical approach, more often than not, you\'re going to fail.\n\nThis kind of sucks for most computer people, though.  Physical access is generally unavailable, and because we work with computers all day long and tend to not be very social creatures, we lack certain social abilities.  I mean, lets be honest.. there\'s a reason why we spend so much time in front of a computer.  They do what we say, they don\'t argue (much), and they don\'t question our madness.  They\'re like a subservient mistress.  Unfortunately, finding a human which is anything close to as obedient as a computer is next to impossible.  This is where manipulation and coercion comes into play, and this is usually where computer guys fail.\n\nExample:\n\nBob, the computer geek, is at a club.  Unlikely place for him to be, but one of his WoW friends drug him there.  He gets approached by a hot chick because she\'s drunk and think he looks like a heavier version of Leonardo DiCaprio.\n\nHot Chick:  Hi.. what\'s your name??\nBob:  ....Bob?\nHot Chick:  Nice to meet you Bob.. what do you do for a living?\nBob: *staring at boobs.. sweating nervously.. begins pondering why his 33 byte shellcode for \'cat /etc/shadow\' is failing.  jmp? nop? mov?*\nHot Chick:  Bob?  My eyes are up here.. jerk! *walking away*\nBob: huh, huh.. boobies.\n\nEpic.  Failure.\n\nBob, being a computer geek, really is not much of a social creature.  Like a programming language, the social language is something that needs to be learned and if you don\'t do it regularly, you\'re never going to be any good at it.  If you can\'t confidently call up a company and convey your confidence through the phone, you\'re going to be picked apart.\n\nSo, what makes a good penetration tester?  One who is equally as versed in programming, networking and usage of tools as he is with his social language.  We generally are not \"computer geeks\".. we hang out, we party, we go to concerts, we have real, live, in person, physical friends.  We\'re social.\n\nBeyond that, we\'re able to think outside of the box, understand flows of data, and be creative.  An example of getting creative is (I\'ve demonstrated this in a previous post).. but lets say that you want to obtain information about a company\'s LAN.. you can either spend hours trying to gain access.. or.. you can simply send them an email with a link to a website.  Or, send them an email asking for information about a product, then examining the headers when they respond.  Simple, mildly creative, and quick.\n\nBut, again, someone just relying upon technical ability may overlook the simplicity of a method like this.  \n\nTo summarize, what makes a good penetration tester is the ability to be social, creative, technical, and manipulative.  Not everyone has these characteristics, so they have to be developed.  I developed my social ability as a sales person once long long ago.  I was one of those computer geeks who never left the computer.. then I was forced to get a job (I was in my teens.. hush.)  For the first month, I was so out of my element.. having to walk up to people and engage them in conversation and attempt to manipulate them into buying something was definitely not my personality.\n\nBut, then I saw my coworkers making big bucks because they were able to do this.. so I watched, learned, and forced myself over my insecurities and eventually started to come across as a confident individual with no fear who was able to talk to anyone about anything.  The direct result was an increase in pay.  I then realized that using this as a hacker was also very, very beneficial.\n\nNow, I\'m still an introvert, for the most part, but I have no problem talking to people and people don\'t believe that I\'m actually really shy.\n\nOn a side note, chicks really dig this characteristic.  So, it comes in handy both in social situations as well as corporate.  Most receptionists are female, after all.\n\nFor the female readers out there (do I have any??) you, unfortunately, are at a bit of a disadvantage when it comes to social engineering.  Sort of.\n\nChicks have the ultimate trump card when it comes to being manipulative.  Because it\'s often said that it\'s a \"man\'s world\", men are generally the ones who are in positions of power.  And women are stuck with coming across as a \"bitch\" when they try to act confident, so this is not the approach you want to take when trying to social engineer.  Also, avoid speaking with other women in this process.  Chicks are vicious to one another.  A chick trying to social engineer another chick would be like running in front of a firing squad.  Sure, occasionally a round will miss.. but the majority of them are going to hit you.\n\nThat said, you have an even better target.  The men.  And, since they\'re in a position of power, it\'s generally easy to get the information you want without having to worry about access restrictions.\n\nHow do you do this?  Well, sex.  No, I don\'t mean whoring yourself.. but women, ultimately, have the real power.  They can get a guy to do whatever they want by a bat of the eye lashes, talking in a certain way, or acting helpless.  Men cannot resist helping a woman in distress.. it\'s hard coded into us.  So, sure.. you may be the epitome of confidence, but occasionally you\'ll have to humble yourself and use your body and your sex to get what you want.  Humiliating, you say?  What\'s more humiliating is when the vice president of the company realizes that some chick was able to steal his entire client base because she bat her eyelashes and shows some leg and cleavage.\n\nWhat can I say?  We\'re pigs.. chicks, use it to your advantage.  Seriously, if a chick called me up and acted like she knew what she was talking about and started asking me to send her stuff or give her information, I\'d be like, wtf.  Bitch.  However, if the same chick called me up and used a seductive voice and acted, somewhat, helpless.. that would trigger some neanderthal genetic trait in me and I\'d get owned.\n\nSad, when you think about it.  What\'s even more sad, is my mind would probably be saying \"YOU SHOULDN\'T GIVE HER THAT.  NO!  STOP!\".. but I still would.\n\n\n','','2010-06-04 11:39:22','2010-06-04 16:39:22','','','2010-06-04 11:39:22','2010-06-04 16:39:22','what-it-takes','0','','publish','What it takes.','post',''),(
'299','16','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=299','0','open','','2','First, I want to appologize for slacking the last few days on posting.  Life > blog.  Sorry, just a simple fact.  ;-)\n\nSo, as I\'ve shown in a few different posts, using header information (both browser and email) can be a simple but effective way of collecting information about a target.  It helps to determine what software they\'re running, IP addresses, network configuration, so on and so forth.  I haven\'t talked much about how to defend against these leaks, though.  So that\'s what I\'m going to do here.  I will show you the headers, the information they leak, and how to fix them.  This post is going to cover email, while my next post will cover browser headers.\n\nIn my first \"<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=173\">Invasion of Privacy</a>\" post, I used email header information to find out the real IP address of Steve, the guy who sent me the spam.  This information helped to determine geographic location, which ultimately helped in getting his address, which then lead to complete ownership.\n<!--more-->\nYou want to avoid having your real IP shown in headers as much as possible.  Sometimes it probably doesn\'t matter, but other times, it\'s a serious issue.  So, lets discuss the ways people send and receive email.\n\nMethod 1)  You have your average desktop user using Outlook, Outlook Express, Eudora, Thunderbird, whatever.  They pop and send email using their ISP\'s email server.  Locating their IP information is simple.\n\n<blockquote>\nReceived: by 10.213.112.212 with SMTP id x20mr859543ebp.1.1276036240432; Tue, 08 Jun 2010 15:30:40 -0700 (PDT)\nReturn-Path: <someguy@gmail.com>\nReceived: from [10.0.1.4] (cpc1-pete1-2-3-cust123.know.cable.virginmedia.com [86.0.12.123])\n        by mx.someisp.com with ESMTPS id 16sm3669165ewy.11.2010.06.08.15.30.37\n        (version=TLSv1/SSLv3 cipher=RC4-MD5);\n        Tue, 08 Jun 2010 15:30:39 -0700 (PDT)\nFrom: Some Guy <someguy@gmail.com>\n</blockquote>\n\nYou\'ll notice that the last received line before the \"From\" header shows that an email was received to a server with the IP of 10.0.1.4 from a client with the IP of 86.0.12.123, and it\'s even nice enough to do the reverse lookup for us.  Additionally, look for the \"X-Mailer\" header.  This gives the name of the email client that the user is using.  With the version.  I appreciate that software companies make my life easier.\n\nAnyway, so this person\'s real IP address is 86.0.12.123.  \"Okay, so how do you prevent this information from being leaked?\"  Well, the short answer is.. you don\'t.  Which is actually good for all parties involved, because this information is crucial when tracking down spam.\n\nThe more detailed answer is.. find a proxy to bounce through before sending via smtp.  Good luck, however.  If you pay for a proxy service, they probably allow you this luxury, but I\'m not aware of any free proxy service that will proxy smtp.  Again, this is because they don\'t want to protect the spammers, nor do they want to be the ones winding up in the RBL\'s.  So.. just know that if you\'re sending via a traditional email client, the end user will have your IP address.\n\nMethod 2)  Today I think most people have migrated to web mail.  gmail, yahoo, hotmail, yada yada yada.. for obvious reasons.  Next time you get an email from, say, a yahoo email address, check out the full headers.  You should see something like this:\n\n<blockquote>\nReceived: from [75.92.123.123] by web110403.mail.gq1.yahoo.com via HTTP; Thu, 03 Jun 2010 07:10:48 PDT\nX-Mailer: YahooMailClassic/11.0.8 YahooMailWebService/0.8.103.269680\n</blockquote>\n\nOr\n\n<blockquote>\n....\nX-Originating-IP: [75.92.123.123]\n</blockquote>\n\nTo be honest, I\'m not sure why some emails have the \"X-Originating-IP\" and some don\'t.. maybe it depends on which Yahoo server the email is sent through, or something.. but.  I\'ve noticed that with Hotmail, the X-Originating-IP is almost always in the headers.\n\nOne thing to note.  Gmail does not include this header, nor does it provide a \"Received\" header that includes the clients IP address.  I believe this is due to how gmail\'s servers route email.  So, by using the Gmail web interface, you won\'t be leaking your IP.\n\nHow can you stop this?  Using a web proxy (like Tor) will hide your IP.. but then you run into the risk of sending credentials through a proxy, which leads to other security risks.  So, caveat emptor.\n\n\nMethod 3)  Using a standard email client to pop/smtp through email providers like yahoo, hotmail, gmail, et. al.\n\nWell, by using this method, you\'ll wind up generating pretty much all of the headers listed above, and, again, your only solution would be to find a proxy that will relay port 25.\n\nWhats the moral of this story?  Be careful of who you send email to, what you respond to, and what headers your email service/client is generating.  Regularly send emails to yourself and check the headers.  (Do not email to the same address that you\'re sending from, this will not generate the same headers as if you sent to someone else.  You need to have 2 email addresses.)\n\nThe way I have my email system set up is, well, overly complicated, but it provides a few different failsafes in case one of my services decides to begin including their clients real IP\'s in the headers.  I essentially use gmail as a proxy, and no, not in the way you think.\n\n;-)\n\n','','2010-06-09 11:33:06','2010-06-09 16:33:06','','','2010-06-09 11:33:06','2010-06-09 16:33:06','email-headers-and-information-leaks','0','','publish','Email headers and information leaks.','post',''),(
'308','11','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=308','0','open','','2','Facebook is constantly battling with the issue of privacy, while trying to maintain a service that doesn\'t wind up like MySpace.  The new privacy controls make things a lot easier for the end user to protect his/her information.\n\nThis makes my job a little more difficult, because now I actually have to work to obtain information.  Sort of.\n\nOne of my backup techniques that I use when I encounter a Facebook page that is, mostly, set to private, is the profile picture.  (Btw, when I say Facebook, I mean myspace, facebook, twitter, linkedin, etc etc etc.)\n\nYou\'re probably asking, \"So what.. what can a profile picture tell you about anything?\"  Ah, young grasshoppa, there are many things a profile picture can tell you.  Besides the obvious, what if I told you that you could use a profile picture the same way that you would use a name when trying to reveal someones identity?\n<!--more-->;\nWe\'ll start with this kid.  I have no idea who he is, but he was the first on the list when I did a search on facebook.\n\n<center><img width=\"600\" src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/pics/flickr.png\"></center>\n\nHe\'s actually done a pretty good job at setting his profile to private.  There is literally nothing on his profile page except for \"sex: male\" (not sure that this is accurate.. lol).  Totally does not tell me anything.  But, what about his profile picture?\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/pics/flickr.jpg\"></center>\n\nThere\'s a service called \"tineye.com\" (<a href=\"http://www.tineye.com\">www.tineye.com</a>) which does whats called a \"reverse image search\".  When I copy &amp;amp; paste the URL of his profile picture from facebook, I get the following:\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/pics/flickr2.png\"></center>\n\nAll sorts of stuff.\n\nOne thing to note.. you need to verify that the profile picture that you\'re using is actually a picture of the target and not just some random picture.  In this case, it\'s beginning to look like this is just a random picture of some EMO kid, but I think you get the idea behind this method.\n\nAlso, it doesn\'t really even have to be their profile picture, to be honest.  You could use any picture that they\'ve posted on their social website, which they may have posted on some other website.\n\nI have used this method, successfully, on people who believed that they had done a good job at protecting their information.  Most had, but they overlooked that using the same profile picture on their facebook, myspace, twitter, and flickr page allowed me to pull together enough information to build a profile of them.  One page may have said a birthdate, another said a name, and yet another said the name of a spouse, etc.  It\'s definitely a round-robin way of doing things, but it\'s kind of like the hail marry bomb when everything else has failed.\n\nI suggest playing around with this technique and test it on yourself.  A new rule to follow, similar to passwords, is don\'t use the same profile picture on multiple websites unless you don\'t mind having all of your information found.  ;-)\n','','2010-06-09 12:58:24','2010-06-09 17:58:24','','','2010-06-09 12:58:24','2010-06-09 17:58:24','social-sites-profile-pictures-and-privacy','0','','publish','Social sites, profile pictures and privacy.','post','');
