'397','5','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=397','0','closed','','2','I realize that this is about as close to plagerism as I can get without literally scraping his website, but I\'m essentially reposting it because I think people really, honestly, need to pay attention to this.  I hear a lot of whining from people when I tell them that their password is weak, or they tell me \"eh, I don\'t care if they get my password\".  Really?\n\nThe original post, \"How I\'d Hack Your Weak Passwords\" was written by John Pozadzides at \"<a href=\"http://onemansblog.com/2007/03/26/how-id-hack-your-weak-passwords/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">One Man\'s Blog</a>\".  I would suggest reading it, because I\'m not going to reinvent the wheel, just show others how the wheel works.\n<!--more-->\nI\'ve touched on the topic of cracking passwords, but I haven\'t really gone into any great detail on it.  So, that\'s what I\'m going to do here.  I want to actually show people how long it really takes to crack a weak password.  This could be your password to Facebook, Twitter, your email, your bank, your credit card company, whatever.  This will also apply to companies who have not instituted a strict password policy and maybe this will help to convince them to do so.\n\nIn his article, John talks about the readily available password crackers.  My favorite, as I\'ve mentioned, is John the Ripper.  Very fast, very effective.  It\'s centuries old (ok, maybe not centuries, but 15 years on the internet IS centuries) and there have not been, to my knowledge, any other crackers released that have ever come close to JTR.  This tells me that it was done right the first time.  How often does that happen?\n\nAnyway, I\'m going to use a list of passwords that I\'ve found.. *cough*\n\n<blockquote>\nlynx -dump \"http://www.google.com/search?q=inurl:(service|authors|administrators|users)+ext:pwd+%22%23+-FrontPage-%22&hl=en&num=500&sa=N\"|perl -le \'while(<STDIN>){if(/^.*?#.*?Page.*?s+(.*?:.*?)..*/) { print $1; }}\' >> passwords.txt\n</blockquote>\n\n*cough*....\n\nAnywho.. I have a list of 30 usernames and encrypted passwords.  This will represent the password list of a small company.\n\n<blockquote>\npurchas:MHEcGWKkOq1B2\nchapan1:kDMyyutUNFBIs \ndan:BPp5Xv7z1kpfA\n</blockquote>\n\nSo, earlier in the month I posted my gigantic <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/thelist.txt.bz2\">wordlist</a> in my \"<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/brute-force-with-thc-hydra/\">Brute Force with THC Hydra</a>\" post.  We\'re going to start by using this list to quickly crack the weakest of the weak passwords in this list.\n\n<blockquote>\n# john -wordfile:thelist.txt service.pwd\nLoaded 30 passwords with 30 different salts (Standard DES [48/64 4K])\nvoyager1         (epaaw)\nsabrina0         (harmony)\nTheresa1         (randy)\nbugeye20         (crowcreek)\n14damone         (themother)\nelmarko1         (rondieck)\ndesign           (royal)\ndevries1         (a-iba)\nfamilyle         (jonathan)\ndramquee         (badbreath)\nstargell         (kingbros)\nbisaccia         (bright)\nguesses: 12  time: 0:00:26:20 100%  c/s: 241196  trying: Eric143 - millan12\n</blockquote>\n\n12 passwords in 26 minutes, so it took about 2 minutes to crack each password.  Notice whats common among all of those.. they\'re all lower case, about 8 characters, and contain some numbers.  But, the real key to these passwords, is that the characters that are in the password form a word.  \"family\", \"design\", \"voyager\".. that\'s what made these so easy to crack.  Do your passwords look anything like this?\n\nNow we will switch over to incremental mode.  This is a slower process, but, technically, more effective.\n\nWhile we wait, I\'ve stolen this table from \"<a href=\"http://onemansblog.com/2007/03/26/how-id-hack-your-weak-passwords/\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">One Man\'s Blog</a>\" that is eye opening.\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/table.png\"></center>\n\nLook at the line for 8 character passwords.  2.42 days for passwords which are only lower case, and 2.10 centuries for passwords that use all characters (mixed case, numbers, etc).  Bump it up to 9 characters, and you have a rock solid password.  This table assumes that the letters are random and not using dictionary words, though.\n\nSo, I let John run over the weekend and here are the additional ones that the incremental mode found:\n\n<blockquote>\nLoaded 18 passwords with 18 different salts (Standard DES [48/64 4K])\n21062            (nobody)\njabber69        (mandy)\ncoolioz           (louisiana)\nguesses: 1  time: 2:19:36:27  c/s: 240996  trying: lobboac1 - letdlorb\n</blockquote>\n\nNot as successful as I would have hoped, but.. if this was the password file for a company, I now have credentials for half of their employees.\n\nAnyway, because of the awesome article that John wrote, plus the multitude of other articles regarding the use of John, I\'m going to keep this short and sweet.  The moral of the story is:  Use strong passwords, or don\'t piss and moan when you get owned.  We\'ve told you, many times, and you couldn\'t be inconvenienced by using a more complex password.\n\nIf you want to use stronger passwords, check out my post <a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/perl-password-generator/\">Perl Password Generator</a>.\n\n','','2010-06-28 11:47:13','2010-06-28 16:47:13','','','2010-06-28 11:47:13','2010-06-28 16:47:13','how-your-passwords-get-hacked','0','','publish','How your passwords get hacked.','post',''),(
'401','11','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=401','0','open','','2','<blockquote>\nA Minnesota man has been indicted for hacking into his neighbor\'s Wi-Fi network and posing as the neighbor to threaten U.S. Vice President Joe Biden and e-mail child pornography, the U.S. Department of Justice said.\n\nThe indictment, filed Thursday in U.S. District Court for the District of Minnesota, charges Barry Vincent Ardolf, 45, of Blaine, Minnesota, with two counts of aggravated identity theft, one count of making threats to the president and successors to the presidency, one count of unauthorized access to a protected computer, one count of possession of child pornography, and one count of distribution of child pornography.\n</blockquote>\n\n(Source: <a href=\"http://www.networkworld.com/news/2010/062410-man-charged-with-hacking-neighbors.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Network World</a>)\n\n<!--more-->\n\nThis is amusing.  I want to talk about where this guy went wrong, because I think one of the major threats we face right now is the fact that it can be made to be impossible to track someone down on the internet, but this guy obviously failed miserably.\n\nFirst, he used his neighbors Wi-Fi.  This is an issue for a few reasons.  Obviously when you threaten the (vice) president, they\'re going to investigate.  Part of this investigation, I\'m sure, is questioning neighbors, friends, and family.  So, it was inevitable that a fed would eventually wind up on his doorstep.\n\nSecond, he decided to use his neighbors identity.  Sure, this would be funny if you were to sign up for a porn mailing list, or something for erectile dysfunction, but to do this when threatening a public official, is idiotic.  I mean, obviously it\'s not funny to try to get someone else in this level of trouble, even if you do hate them for whatever reason, but you\'ve now narrowed the search area by a lot.  Why?  The feds are eventually going to conclude that this was done using his Wi-Fi, which leaves a relatively small area for the perpetrator to be located.\n\nThird, it is trivial to triangulate on a Wi-Fi signal, so finding the signal of someone who\'s using your Wi-Fi is a simple process.\n\nFourth, child porn is no joke.  It\'s a quick, quick way to get locked up, even if the other charges get dropped.  I mean, putting all of the moral and ethical issues surrounding child porn aside, simply having it on your computer is a quick ticket to the slammer.  Dumb.\n\nSo, how could he have successfully pulled this off?  Really easily, actually.\n\n1) Take a drive.  Using a wireless network right next door to you is idiotic.  You\'re, what, 15 feet away from your neighbor?  You don\'t think they\'re going to check your place if they find out that the middle man (your neighbor) has a wireless network?  Think again.  \"But I spoof my mac address and I\'m uberleet\".  Good luck, dude.  When they confiscate your computer and find \"macspoof\", they\'re going to put 2 and 2 together.\n\nSo, drive X amount of miles from your house and THEN use a wireless network.  They\'re everywhere, I\'m sure you\'ll find one.\n\n2) The idea of using the wireless network as the anonymizer is pretty dumb, because they (the feds, police, the people that throw you in prison) will still know your approximate physical location.  And, since these guys get paid to do ask questions and investigate stuff, they have all day, every day to track you down.  And I guarantee, if you park in front of someones house for a few hours, people are going to notice.  Think about it.. if someone was sitting outside of your house, parked, with a laptop at 2am, wouldn\'t you take notice?  Maybe make a mental note of the make, model, color of the car and a vague description of the occupant?  I would.\n\nUse a fricken proxy, people.  Sure, drive your car out to suburbia, find a wireless network, pwn it, use it.. but before sending death threats to presidents and whatnot, TURN ON TOR!  OR SOMETHING!  Geez.  By using proxies, you gain an additional level of anonymity, because now your anonymizer is being anonymized.  So, if, by some chance, the Tor operator in Germany is logging and hands them over to the feds, it\'ll still only lead back to the wireless network that you used, which is not your neighbors.\n\nAlso, if you were to use a different wireless network every time you did whatever it was that you were doing, it would make the job of tracking you down significantly more difficult.  The TOR IP changes, the source IP changes.  And, even if they were to track it back to the wireless you\'re physically miles and miles and miles away with no association with that wireless network.  I would never reuse one that I\'ve already used once for something illegal.  Last thing I want is for the SWAT team to firebomb my car because I\'m using the same wireless network as I did last week and they\'ve finally tracked it down.\n\nMake CERTAIN that the proxy that you\'re using is properly configured, as mentioned in my post \"<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/browser-headers-and-information-leaks/\">Browser Headers and Information Leaks</a>\"  You don\'t want to spend all this time searching for a proxy, spoofing your mac, finding a far out wireless network, only to have the proxy that you use send x_forwarded_for out with every header.  Kind of defeats the purpose.\n\n3) Spoof your mac address.  I know I knocked it a few paragraphs ago, but used in conjunction with #1 and #2, this just adds an additional layer.\n\n4) Change the finger print of your browser.  User agent, version, etc.  Hell, make it random.  I have an idea for a real simple shell script/perl script that would start Chromeum using a randomly selected user agent from an array of user agents, I just haven\'t gotten around to it yet.\n\n5) Make sure that the laptop that you\'re using is secure.  You don\'t want people to be able to grab info from your laptop remotely.  This will make it more difficult to finger print you.  If you run Linux, make your box come across as Windows, if you run Windows, pretend to bet Mac OSX.  The more obfuscated the trail is, the more difficult you make their job.  Eventually they\'ll hit a point where they wonder if you\'re even worth the man hours that they\'re putting in.  Obviously, this is dependent upon the crime you\'ve committed.  I\'m not sure where presidential death threats fall.  Probably pretty high up there, I would imagine.\n\n6) Do NOT use the identity of someone that you know.  Why?  Obviously you\'ve never heard of the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_degrees_of_separation\">6 degrees of separation.</a>.  Choose a random name.. Bob Barker, Kevin Smith, John Hormone, something.  You don\'t want anything linking to you in any way.\n\n7) Try to use an OPEN wireless network.  Not everyone possesses the skill to hack a \"secured\" wireless network.  If, somehow, they get back to you and find that you have the aircrack suite and a bunch of custom scripts to make it easier, it\'s going to be hard to deny that you hack wireless networks.  If, however, the wireless network that was owned was open and could be used by anyone who happens to drive by their house, well.. this pretty much raises the \"reasonable doubt\" issue.\n\n8 ) Most wireless routers keep logs of connected clients and/or web sited visited (ActionTec\'s do this).  You will want to delete these.  This should be a no brainer.  No logs, no evidence.  \n\nIn closing, just remember.. you don\'t want to create a trail, and the trail that you do leave is winding, confusing, and convoluted.  You want to create separation between you and the networks used, both physical and digital separation.  \n\nOperate like a ninja;  Dark, anonymous, quiet.\n\n\n','','2010-06-28 13:14:14','2010-06-28 18:14:14','','','2010-06-28 13:14:14','2010-06-28 18:14:14','man-charged-with-hacking-neighbors-wi-fi-to-threaten-biden','0','','publish','Man charged with hacking neighbors Wi-Fi to threaten Biden','post',''),(
'405','11','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=405','0','open','','2','I\'m doing more research than writing today, but I wanted to share this as it seems most people don\'t really understand how a social security number works or what you can identify by knowing someones number and I haven\'t come across much that discusses this topic, so!\n\nFirst, for those of you who live under a rock, or across the pond, a social security number is in the format of xxx-xx-xxxx.  Everyone knows this, right?  But did you know that those numbers represent stuff?\n\nFor example, the first three digits (known as \"Area Numbers\") indicate the state of birth.  Here\'s the cross reference:\n\n<!--more-->\n[update]\n\nOne of my readers pointed out that not necessarily are the first three digits the state of birth.  Here\'s the explanation:\n\n<blockquote>\nThe area numbers were assigned to geographical locations in a manner\nanalogous to the way in which ZIP codes were later assigned (in particular,\narea numbers increase from east to west across the continental US as do the\nZIP codes).  Most area numbers were assigned according to state (or\nterritorial) boundaries, although the series 700-729 was assigned to\nrailroad workers regardless of location (this series of area numbers was\ndiscontinued in 1964 and is no longer used for new SSNs).  With few\nexceptions, each geographical area is assigned a range of area numbers.\nArea numbers assigned prior to 1972 are an indication of the location of the\nSSA office which originally issued the SSN.  Since 1972 SSNs have been\nissued centrally and the area number in SSNs assigned since 1972 corresponds\nto the residence location of the applicant as indicated on the application\nfor the SSN.\n</blockquote>\n\nAdditionally, I just found a new tool that seems kind of interesting.. check it out <a href=\"http://stevemorse.org/ssn/ssn.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>\n\n[/update]\n\n<table>\n<tr>\n  <td width=\"15%\">001-003</td><td width=\"15%\">New Hampshire</td><td width=\"15%\">400-407</td><td width=\"15%\">Kentucky</td><td width=\"15%\">530</td><td width=\"25%\">Nevada</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>004-007</td><td>Maine</td><td>408-415</td><td>Tennessee</td><td>531-539</td><td>Washington</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>008-009</td><td>Vermont</td><td>416-424</td><td>Alabama</td><td>540-544</td><td>Oregon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>010-034</td><td>Massachusetts</td><td>425-428</td><td>Mississippi</td><td>545-573</td><td>California</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>035-039</td><td>Rhode Island</td><td>429-432</td><td>Arkansas</td><td>574</td><td>Alaska</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>040-049</td><td>Connecticut</td><td>433-439</td><td>Louisiana</td><td>575-576</td><td>Hawaii</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>050-134</td><td>New York</td><td>440-448</td><td>Oklahoma</td><td>577-579</td><td>District of Colombia</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>135-158</td><td>New Jersey</td><td>449-467</td><td>Texas</td><td>580</td><td>Virgin Islands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>159-211</td><td>Pennsylvania</td><td>468-477</td><td>Minnesota</td><td>581-584</td><td>Puerto Rico</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>212-220</td><td>Maryland</td><td>478-485</td><td>Iowa</td><td>585</td><td>New Mexico</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>221-222</td><td>Delaware</td><td>486-500</td><td>Missouri</td><td>586</td><td>Pacific Islands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>223-231</td><td>Virginia</td><td>501-502</td><td>North Dakota</td><td>587-588</td><td>Mississippi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>232-236</td><td>West Virginia</td><td>503-504</td><td>South Dakota</td><td>589-595</td><td>Florida</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>237-246</td><td>North Carolina</td><td>505-508</td><td>Nebraska</td><td>596-599</td><td>Puerto Rico</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>247-251</td><td>South Carolina</td><td>509-515</td><td>Kansas</td><td>600-601</td><td>Arizona</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>252-260</td><td>Georgia</td><td>516-517</td><td>Montana</td><td>602-626</td><td>California</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>261-267</td><td>Florida</td><td>518-519</td><td>Idaho</td><td>627-645</td><td>Texas</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>268-302</td><td>Ohio</td><td>520</td><td>Wyoming</td><td>646-647</td><td>Utah</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>303-317</td><td>Indiana</td><td>521-524</td><td>Colorado</td><td>648-649</td><td>New Mexico</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>318-361</td><td>Illinois</td><td>525</td><td>New Mexico</td><td>362-386</td><td>Michigan</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>526-527</td><td>Arizona</td><td>387-399</td><td>Wisconsin</td><td>528-529</td><td>Utah</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<table>\n<tr><td>\n  650-699 unassigned, for future use\n</td></tr>\n<tr><td>\n  700-728 Railroad workers through 1963, then discontinued\n</tr></td>\n<tr><td>\n  729-799 unassigned, for future use\n</tr></td>\n<tr><td>\n  800-999 not valid SSNs.  Some sources have claimed that numbers\n</tr></td>\n<tr><td>\n          above 900 were used when some state programs were converted\n          to federal control, but current SSA documents claim no\n          numbers above 799 have ever been used.\n</tr></td>\n</table>\n\nSo, if you come across someone with a social security number starting with 585, you know that they were born in New Mexico.  Neat, right?\n\nThe middle two numbers are called the \"Group Numbers\".  I\'m going to quote this rather than try to explain it myself..\n\n<blockquote>\nThe group number is not related to geography but rather to the order in which SSNs are issued for a particular area. Before 1965, only half the group numbers were used: odd numbers were used below 10 and even numbers were used above 9. In 1965 the system was changed so assignments continued with the low even numbers and the high odd numbers. So, group numbers for each area number are assigned in the following order:\n\nOdd numbers, 01 to 09\nEven numbers, 10 to 98\nEven numbers, 02 to 08\nOdd numbers, 11 to 99\nGroup codes of \"00\" aren\'t assigned\n\nIn each region, all possible area numbers are assigned with each group number before using the next group number. This means the group numbers can be used to find a chronological ordering of SSNs within a region. When new group numbers are assigned to a state, the old numbers are usually used up first.\n\nSSA publishes a list every month of the highest group assigned for each SSN Area. For example, if the highest group assigned for area 999 is 72, then we know that the number 999-04-1234 is an invalid number because even Groups under 9 have not yet been assigned.\n</blockquote>\n\nThen we\'re left with the serial number:\n\n<blockquote>\nSerial numbers are assigned in chronological order within each area and group number as the applications are processed. Serial number \"0000\" is never used. Before 1965, when number assignment was transferred from field offices to the central office, serial numbers may have been assigned in a strange order. (Some sources claim that 2000 and 7000 series numbers were assigned out of order. That no longer seems to be the case.) Currently, the serial numbers are assigned in strictly increasing order with each area and group combination.\n</blockquote>\n\nSomething to ponder.. it\'s rather trivial to get the last 4 of someones social security number.. because they\'re 4 digits, they\'re \"perfect\" for 4 digit pin numbers (hint: NEVER USE THE LAST 4 OF YOUR SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBER AS YOUR PIN.  Thank you.)\n\nSo, if you have the last 4 of someone\'s social security number, and you know their state of birth, you have 7 out of 9 numbers of their social... :-)\n\nThis is more of an FYI post, because periodically I run across people who really don\'t know much about SS #\'s and figure I\'d help edumicate them.\n\n','','2010-06-29 14:53:24','2010-06-29 19:53:24','','','2010-06-29 14:53:24','2010-06-29 19:53:24','social-security-number-format','0','','publish','Social Security Number Format','post','');
